@node "Contributors" "g77.guide/Contributors"
@next "Funding"
@prev "GNU Free Documentation License"
@toc "Main"

Contributors to GNU Fortran
***************************

In addition to James Craig Burley, who wrote the front end, many people
have helped create and improve GNU Fortran.

   * The packaging and compiler portions of GNU Fortran are based
     largely on the GCC compiler.  See @{"gcc.guide/Contributors to GCC" link "gcc.guide/Contributors"},
     for more information.

   * The run-time library used by GNU Fortran is a repackaged version
     of the @{b}libf2c@{ub} library (combined from the @{b}libF77@{ub} and @{b}libI77@{ub}
     libraries) provided as part of @{b}f2c@{ub}, available for free from @{b}netlib@{ub}
     sites on the Internet.

   * Cygnus Support and The Free Software Foundation contributed
     significant money and/or equipment to Craig's efforts.

   * The following individuals served as alpha testers prior to @{b}g77@{ub}'s
     public release.  This work consisted of testing, researching,
     sometimes debugging, and occasionally providing small amounts of
     code and fixes for @{b}g77@{ub}, plus offering plenty of helpful advice to
     Craig:

          Jonathan Corbet

          Dr. Mark Fernyhough

          Takafumi Hayashi (The University of
          Aizu)--<takafumi\@u-aizu.ac.jp>

          Kate Hedstrom

          Michel Kern (INRIA and Rice University)--<Michel.Kern\@inria.fr>

          Dr. A. O. V. Le Blanc

          Dave Love

          Rick Lutowski

          Toon Moene

          Rick Niles

          Derk Reefman

          Wayne K. Schroll

          Bill Thorson

          Pedro A. M. Vazquez

          Ian Watson

   * Dave Love (<d.love\@dl.ac.uk>) wrote the libU77 part of the run-time
     library.

   * Scott Snyder (<snyder\@d0sgif.fnal.gov>) provided the patch to add
     rudimentary support for @{b}INTEGER*1@{ub}, @{b}INTEGER*2@{ub}, and @{b}LOGICAL*1@{ub}.  This
     inspired Craig to add further support, even though the resulting
     support would still be incomplete.  This support is believed to be
     completed at version 3.4 of @{b}gcc@{ub} by Roger Sayle
     (<roger\@eyesopen.com>).

   * David Ronis (<ronis\@onsager.chem.mcgill.ca>) inspired and
     encouraged Craig to rewrite the documentation in texinfo format by
     contributing a first pass at a translation of the old
     @{b}g77-0.5.16/f/DOC@{ub} file.

   * Toon Moene (<toon\@moene.indiv.nluug.nl>) performed some analysis of
     generated code as part of an overall project to improve @{b}g77@{ub} code
     generation to at least be as good as @{b}f2c@{ub} used in conjunction with
     @{b}gcc@{ub}.  So far, this has resulted in the three, somewhat
     experimental, options added by @{b}g77@{ub} to the @{b}gcc@{ub} compiler and its
     back end.

     (These, in turn, had made their way into the @{b}egcs@{ub} version of the
     compiler, and do not exist in @{b}gcc@{ub} version 2.8 or versions of @{b}g77@{ub}
     based on that version of @{b}gcc@{ub}.)

   * John Carr (<jfc\@mit.edu>) wrote the alias analysis improvements.

   * Thanks to Mary Cortani and the staff at Craftwork Solutions
     (<support\@craftwork.com>) for all of their support.

   * Many other individuals have helped debug, test, and improve @{b}g77@{ub}
     over the past several years, and undoubtedly more people will be
     doing so in the future.  If you have done so, and would like to
     see your name listed in the above list, please ask!  The default
     is that people wish to remain anonymous.

@endnode

@node "Funding" "g77.guide/Funding"
@next "Funding GNU Fortran"
@prev "Contributors"
@toc "Main"

Funding Free Software
*********************

If you want to have more free software a few years from now, it makes
sense for you to help encourage people to contribute funds for its
development.  The most effective approach known is to encourage
commercial redistributors to donate.

   Users of free software systems can boost the pace of development by
encouraging for-a-fee distributors to donate part of their selling price
to free software developers--the Free Software Foundation, and others.

   The way to convince distributors to do this is to demand it and
expect it from them.  So when you compare distributors, judge them
partly by how much they give to free software development.  Show
distributors they must compete to be the one who gives the most.

   To make this approach work, you must insist on numbers that you can
compare, such as, "We will donate ten dollars to the Frobnitz project
for each disk sold."  Don't be satisfied with a vague promise, such as
"A portion of the profits are donated," since it doesn't give a basis
for comparison.

   Even a precise fraction "of the profits from this disk" is not very
meaningful, since creative accounting and unrelated business decisions
can greatly alter what fraction of the sales price counts as profit.
If the price you pay is $50, ten percent of the profit is probably less
than a dollar; it might be a few cents, or nothing at all.

   Some redistributors do development work themselves.  This is useful
too; but to keep everyone honest, you need to inquire how much they do,
and what kind.  Some kinds of development make much more long-term
difference than others.  For example, maintaining a separate version of
a program contributes very little; maintaining the standard version of a
program for the whole community contributes much.  Easy new ports
contribute little, since someone else would surely do them; difficult
ports such as adding a new CPU to the GNU Compiler Collection
contribute more; major new features or packages contribute the most.

   By establishing the idea that supporting further development is "the
proper thing to do" when distributing free software for a fee, we can
assure a steady flow of resources into making more free software.

     Copyright (C) 1994 Free Software Foundation, Inc.
     Verbatim copying and redistribution of this section is permitted
     without royalty; alteration is not permitted.

@endnode

@node "Funding GNU Fortran" "g77.guide/Funding GNU Fortran"
@next "Getting Started"
@prev "Funding"
@toc "Main"

Funding GNU Fortran
*******************

James Craig Burley (<craig\@jcb-sc.com>), the original author of @{b}g77@{ub},
stopped working on it in September 1999 (He has a web page at
`http://world.std.com/%7Eburley/'.)

   GNU Fortran is currently maintained by Toon Moene
(<toon\@moene.indiv.nluug.nl>), with the help of countless other
volunteers.

   As with other GNU software, funding is important because it can pay
for needed equipment, personnel, and so on.

   The FSF provides information on the best way to fund ongoing
development of GNU software (such as GNU Fortran) in documents such as
the "GNUS Bulletin".  Email <gnu\@gnu.org> for information on funding the
FSF.

   Another important way to support work on GNU Fortran is to volunteer
to help out.

   Email <gcc\@gcc.gnu.org> to volunteer for this work.

   However, we strongly expect that there will never be a version 0.6
of @{b}g77@{ub}.  Work on this compiler has stopped as of the release of GCC
3.1, except for bug fixing.  @{b}g77@{ub} will be succeeded by @{b}g95@{ub} - see
`http://g95.sourceforge.net'.

   See @{"Funding Free Software" link "Funding"}, for more information.

@endnode

@node "Getting Started" "g77.guide/Getting Started"
@next "What is GNU Fortran?"
@prev "Funding GNU Fortran"
@toc "Main"

Getting Started
***************

If you don't need help getting started reading the portions of this
manual that are most important to you, you should skip this portion of
the manual.

   If you are new to compilers, especially Fortran compilers, or new to
how compilers are structured under UNIX and UNIX-like systems, you'll
want to see @{"What is GNU Fortran?" link "What is GNU Fortran?"}.

   If you are new to GNU compilers, or have used only one GNU compiler
in the past and not had to delve into how it lets you manage various
versions and configurations of @{b}gcc@{ub}, you should see @{"G77 and GCC" link "G77 and GCC"}.

   Everyone except experienced @{b}g77@{ub} users should see @{"Invoking G77" link "Invoking G77"}.

   If you're acquainted with previous versions of @{b}g77@{ub}, you should see
@{"News About GNU Fortran" link "News"}.  Further, if you've actually used previous
versions of @{b}g77@{ub}, especially if you've written or modified Fortran code
to be compiled by previous versions of @{b}g77@{ub}, you should see @{"Changes" link "Changes"}.

   If you intend to write or otherwise compile code that is not already
strictly conforming ANSI FORTRAN 77--and this is probably everyone--you
should see @{"Language" link "Language"}.

   If you run into trouble getting Fortran code to compile, link, run,
or work properly, you might find answers if you see
@{"Debugging and Interfacing" link "Debugging and Interfacing"}, see @{"Collected Fortran Wisdom" link "Collected Fortran Wisdom"}, and see
@{"Trouble" link "Trouble"}.  You might also find that the problems you are encountering
are bugs in @{b}g77@{ub}--see @{"Bugs" link "Bugs"}, for information on reporting them, after
reading the other material.

   If you need further help with @{b}g77@{ub}, or with freely redistributable
software in general, see @{"Service" link "Service"}.

   If you would like to help the @{b}g77@{ub} project, see @{"Funding GNU Fortran" link "Funding GNU Fortran"},
for information on helping financially, and see @{"Projects" link "Projects"}, for
information on helping in other ways.

   If you're generally curious about the future of @{b}g77@{ub}, see @{"Projects" link "Projects"}.
If you're curious about its past, see @{"Contributors" link "Contributors"}, and see
@{"Funding GNU Fortran" link "Funding GNU Fortran"}.

   To see a few of the questions maintainers of @{b}g77@{ub} have, and that you
might be able to answer, see @{"Open Questions" link "Open Questions"}.

@endnode

@node "What is GNU Fortran?" "g77.guide/What is GNU Fortran?"
@next "G77 and GCC"
@prev "Getting Started"
@toc "Main"

What is GNU Fortran?
********************

GNU Fortran, or @{b}g77@{ub}, is designed initially as a free replacement for,
or alternative to, the UNIX @{b}f77@{ub} command.  (Similarly, @{b}gcc@{ub} is designed
as a replacement for the UNIX @{b}cc@{ub} command.)

   @{b}g77@{ub} also is designed to fit in well with the other fine GNU
compilers and tools.

   Sometimes these design goals conflict--in such cases, resolution
often is made in favor of fitting in well with Project GNU.  These
cases are usually identified in the appropriate sections of this manual.

   As compilers, @{b}g77@{ub}, @{b}gcc@{ub}, and @{b}f77@{ub} share the following characteristics:

   * They read a user's program, stored in a file and containing
     instructions written in the appropriate language (Fortran, C, and
     so on).  This file contains @{i}source code@{ui}.

   * They translate the user's program into instructions a computer can
     carry out more quickly than it takes to translate the instructions
     in the first place.  These instructions are called @{i}machine
     code@{ui}--code designed to be efficiently translated and processed by
     a machine such as a computer.  Humans usually aren't as good
     writing machine code as they are at writing Fortran or C, because
     it is easy to make tiny mistakes writing machine code.  When
     writing Fortran or C, it is easy to make big mistakes.

   * They provide information in the generated machine code that can
     make it easier to find bugs in the program (using a debugging
     tool, called a @{i}debugger@{ui}, such as @{b}gdb@{ub}).

   * They locate and gather machine code already generated to perform
     actions requested by statements in the user's program.  This
     machine code is organized into @{i}libraries@{ui} and is located and
     gathered during the @{i}link@{ui} phase of the compilation process.
     (Linking often is thought of as a separate step, because it can be
     directly invoked via the @{b}ld@{ub} command.  However, the @{b}g77@{ub} and @{b}gcc@{ub}
     commands, as with most compiler commands, automatically perform
     the linking step by calling on @{b}ld@{ub} directly, unless asked to not do
     so by the user.)

   * They attempt to diagnose cases where the user's program contains
     incorrect usages of the language.  The @{i}diagnostics@{ui} produced by the
     compiler indicate the problem and the location in the user's
     source file where the problem was first noticed.  The user can use
     this information to locate and fix the problem.  (Sometimes an
     incorrect usage of the language leads to a situation where the
     compiler can no longer make any sense of what follows--while a
     human might be able to--and thus ends up complaining about many
     "problems" it encounters that, in fact, stem from just one
     problem, usually the first one reported.)

   * They attempt to diagnose cases where the user's program contains a
     correct usage of the language, but instructs the computer to do
     something questionable.  These diagnostics often are in the form
     of @{i}warnings@{ui}, instead of the @{i}errors@{ui} that indicate incorrect usage
     of the language.

   How these actions are performed is generally under the control of
the user.  Using command-line options, the user can specify how
persnickety the compiler is to be regarding the program (whether to
diagnose questionable usage of the language), how much time to spend
making the generated machine code run faster, and so on.

   @{b}g77@{ub} consists of several components:

   * A modified version of the @{b}gcc@{ub} command, which also might be
     installed as the system's @{b}cc@{ub} command.  (In many cases, @{b}cc@{ub} refers
     to the system's "native" C compiler, which might be a non-GNU
     compiler, or an older version of @{b}gcc@{ub} considered more stable or
     that is used to build the operating system kernel.)

   * The @{b}g77@{ub} command itself, which also might be installed as the
     system's @{b}f77@{ub} command.

   * The @{b}libg2c@{ub} run-time library.  This library contains the machine
     code needed to support capabilities of the Fortran language that
     are not directly provided by the machine code generated by the @{b}g77@{ub}
     compilation phase.

     @{b}libg2c@{ub} is just the unique name @{b}g77@{ub} gives to its version of @{b}libf2c@{ub}
     to distinguish it from any copy of @{b}libf2c@{ub} installed from @{b}f2c@{ub} (or
     versions of @{b}g77@{ub} that built @{b}libf2c@{ub} under that same name) on the
     system.

     The maintainer of @{b}libf2c@{ub} currently is <dmg\@bell-labs.com>.

   * The compiler itself, internally named @{b}f771@{ub}.

     Note that @{b}f771@{ub} does not generate machine code directly--it
     generates @{i}assembly code@{ui} that is a more readable form of machine
     code, leaving the conversion to actual machine code to an
     @{i}assembler@{ui}, usually named @{b}as@{ub}.

   @{b}gcc@{ub} is often thought of as "the C compiler" only, but it does more
than that.  Based on command-line options and the names given for files
on the command line, @{b}gcc@{ub} determines which actions to perform, including
preprocessing, compiling (in a variety of possible languages),
assembling, and linking.

   For example, the command @{b}gcc foo.c@{ub} @{i}drives@{ui} the file @{b}foo.c@{ub} through the
preprocessor @{b}cpp@{ub}, then the C compiler (internally named @{b}cc1@{ub}), then the
assembler (usually @{b}as@{ub}), then the linker (@{b}ld@{ub}), producing an executable
program named @{b}a.out@{ub} (on UNIX systems).

   As another example, the command @{b}gcc foo.cc@{ub} would do much the same as
@{b}gcc foo.c@{ub}, but instead of using the C compiler named @{b}cc1@{ub}, @{b}gcc@{ub} would use
the C++ compiler (named @{b}cc1plus@{ub}).

   In a GNU Fortran installation, @{b}gcc@{ub} recognizes Fortran source files
by name just like it does C and C++ source files.  It knows to use the
Fortran compiler named @{b}f771@{ub}, instead of @{b}cc1@{ub} or @{b}cc1plus@{ub}, to compile
Fortran files.

   Non-Fortran-related operation of @{b}gcc@{ub} is generally unaffected by
installing the GNU Fortran version of @{b}gcc@{ub}.  However, without the
installed version of @{b}gcc@{ub} being the GNU Fortran version, @{b}gcc@{ub} will not be
able to compile and link Fortran programs--and since @{b}g77@{ub} uses @{b}gcc@{ub} to do
most of the actual work, neither will @{b}g77@{ub}!

   The @{b}g77@{ub} command is essentially just a front-end for the @{b}gcc@{ub} command.
Fortran users will normally use @{b}g77@{ub} instead of @{b}gcc@{ub}, because @{b}g77@{ub} knows
how to specify the libraries needed to link with Fortran programs
(@{b}libg2c@{ub} and @{b}lm@{ub}).  @{b}g77@{ub} can still compile and link programs and source
files written in other languages, just like @{b}gcc@{ub}.

   The command @{b}g77 -v@{ub} is a quick way to display lots of version
information for the various programs used to compile a typical
preprocessed Fortran source file--this produces much more output than
@{b}gcc -v@{ub} currently does.  (If it produces an error message near the end
of the output--diagnostics from the linker, usually @{b}ld@{ub}--you might have
an out-of-date @{b}libf2c@{ub} that improperly handles complex arithmetic.)  In
the output of this command, the line beginning @{b}GNU Fortran Front End@{ub}
identifies the version number of GNU Fortran; immediately preceding
that line is a line identifying the version of @{b}gcc@{ub} with which that
version of @{b}g77@{ub} was built.

   The @{b}libf2c@{ub} library is distributed with GNU Fortran for the
convenience of its users, but is not part of GNU Fortran.  It contains
the procedures needed by Fortran programs while they are running.

   For example, while code generated by @{b}g77@{ub} is likely to do additions,
subtractions, and multiplications @{i}in line@{ui}--in the actual compiled
code--it is not likely to do trigonometric functions this way.

   Instead, operations like trigonometric functions are compiled by the
@{b}f771@{ub} compiler (invoked by @{b}g77@{ub} when compiling Fortran code) into machine
code that, when run, calls on functions in @{b}libg2c@{ub}, so @{b}libg2c@{ub} must be
linked with almost every useful program having any component compiled
by GNU Fortran.  (As mentioned above, the @{b}g77@{ub} command takes care of all
this for you.)

   The @{b}f771@{ub} program represents most of what is unique to GNU Fortran.
While much of the @{b}libg2c@{ub} component comes from the @{b}libf2c@{ub} component of
@{b}f2c@{ub}, a free Fortran-to-C converter distributed by Bellcore (AT&T), plus
@{b}libU77@{ub}, provided by Dave Love, and the @{b}g77@{ub} command is just a small
front-end to @{b}gcc@{ub}, @{b}f771@{ub} is a combination of two rather large chunks of
code.

   One chunk is the so-called @{i}GNU Back End@{ui}, or GBE, which knows how to
generate fast code for a wide variety of processors.  The same GBE is
used by the C, C++, and Fortran compiler programs @{b}cc1@{ub}, @{b}cc1plus@{ub}, and
@{b}f771@{ub}, plus others.  Often the GBE is referred to as the "gcc back end"
or even just "gcc"--in this manual, the term GBE is used whenever the
distinction is important.

   The other chunk of @{b}f771@{ub} is the majority of what is unique about GNU
Fortran--the code that knows how to interpret Fortran programs to
determine what they are intending to do, and then communicate that
knowledge to the GBE for actual compilation of those programs.  This
chunk is called the @{i}Fortran Front End@{ui} (FFE).  The @{b}cc1@{ub} and @{b}cc1plus@{ub}
programs have their own front ends, for the C and C++ languages,
respectively.  These fronts ends are responsible for diagnosing
incorrect usage of their respective languages by the programs the
process, and are responsible for most of the warnings about
questionable constructs as well.  (The GBE handles producing some
warnings, like those concerning possible references to undefined
variables.)

   Because so much is shared among the compilers for various languages,
much of the behavior and many of the user-selectable options for these
compilers are similar.  For example, diagnostics (error messages and
warnings) are similar in appearance; command-line options like @{b}-Wall@{ub}
have generally similar effects; and the quality of generated code (in
terms of speed and size) is roughly similar (since that work is done by
the shared GBE).

@endnode

@node "G77 and GCC" "g77.guide/G77 and GCC"
@next "Invoking G77"
@prev "What is GNU Fortran?"
@toc "Main"

Compile Fortran, C, or Other Programs
*************************************

A GNU Fortran installation includes a modified version of the @{b}gcc@{ub}
command.

   In a non-Fortran installation, @{b}gcc@{ub} recognizes C, C++, and
Objective-C source files.

   In a GNU Fortran installation, @{b}gcc@{ub} also recognizes Fortran source
files and accepts Fortran-specific command-line options, plus some
command-line options that are designed to cater to Fortran users but
apply to other languages as well.

   See @{"gcc.guide/Programming Languages Supported by GCC" link "gcc.guide/G++ and GCC"}, for
information on the way different languages are handled by the GCC
compiler (@{b}gcc@{ub}).

   Also provided as part of GNU Fortran is the @{b}g77@{ub} command.  The @{b}g77@{ub}
command is designed to make compiling and linking Fortran programs
somewhat easier than when using the @{b}gcc@{ub} command for these tasks.  It
does this by analyzing the command line somewhat and changing it
appropriately before submitting it to the @{b}gcc@{ub} command.

   Use the @{b}-v@{ub} option with @{b}g77@{ub} to see what is going on--the first line
of output is the invocation of the @{b}gcc@{ub} command.

@endnode

@node "Invoking G77" "g77.guide/Invoking G77"
@next "News"
@prev "G77 and GCC"
@toc "Main"

GNU Fortran Command Options
***************************

The @{b}g77@{ub} command supports all the options supported by the @{b}gcc@{ub} command.
See @{"gcc.guide/GCC Command Options" link "gcc.guide/Invoking GCC"}, for information on the
non-Fortran-specific aspects of the @{b}gcc@{ub} command (and, therefore, the
@{b}g77@{ub} command).

   All @{b}gcc@{ub} and @{b}g77@{ub} options are accepted both by @{b}g77@{ub} and by @{b}gcc@{ub} (as well
as any other drivers built at the same time, such as @{b}g++@{ub}), since adding
@{b}g77@{ub} to the @{b}gcc@{ub} distribution enables acceptance of @{b}g77@{ub} options by all of
the relevant drivers.

   In some cases, options have positive and negative forms; the
negative form of @{b}-ffoo@{ub} would be @{b}-fno-foo@{ub}.  This manual documents only
one of these two forms, whichever one is not the default.


 @{" Option Summary     " link "Option Summary"}  Brief list of all @{b}g77@{ub} options,
                        without explanations.
 @{" Overall Options    " link "Overall Options"}  Controlling the kind of output:
                        an executable, object files, assembler files,
                        or preprocessed source.
 @{" Shorthand Options  " link "Shorthand Options"}  Options that are shorthand for other options.
 @{" Fortran Dialect Options " link "Fortran Dialect Options"}  Controlling the variant of Fortran language
                             compiled.
 @{" Warning Options    " link "Warning Options"}  How picky should the compiler be?
 @{" Debugging Options  " link "Debugging Options"}  Symbol tables, measurements, and debugging dumps.
 @{" Optimize Options   " link "Optimize Options"}  How much optimization?
 @{" Preprocessor Options " link "Preprocessor Options"}  Controlling header files and macro definitions.
                         Also, getting dependency information for Make.
 @{" Directory Options  " link "Directory Options"}  Where to find header files and libraries.
                        Where to find the compiler executable files.
 @{" Code Gen Options   " link "Code Gen Options"}  Specifying conventions for function calls, data layout
                        and register usage.
 @{" Environment Variables " link "Environment Variables"}  Env vars that affect GNU Fortran.

@endnode

@node "Option Summary" "g77.guide/Option Summary"
@next "Overall Options"
@toc "Invoking G77"

