@node "Char Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Char Intrinsic"
@next "ChDir Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@prev "CExp Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Char Intrinsic
..............

     Char(I)

Char: @{b}CHARACTER*1@{ub} function.

I: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Returns the character corresponding to the code specified by I,
using the system's native character set.

   Because the system's native character set is used, the
correspondence between character and their codes is not necessarily the
same between GNU Fortran implementations.

   Note that no intrinsic exists to convert a numerical value to a
printable character string.  For example, there is no intrinsic that,
given an @{b}INTEGER@{ub} or @{b}REAL@{ub} argument with the value @{b}154@{ub}, returns the
@{b}CHARACTER@{ub} result @{b}'154'@{ub}.

   Instead, you can use internal-file I/O to do this kind of conversion.
For example:

     INTEGER VALUE
     CHARACTER*10 STRING
     VALUE = 154
     WRITE (STRING, '(I10)'), VALUE
     PRINT *, STRING
     END

   The above program, when run, prints:

             154

   See @{"IChar Intrinsic" link "IChar Intrinsic"}, for the inverse of the @{b}CHAR@{ub} function.

   See @{"AChar Intrinsic" link "AChar Intrinsic"}, for the function corresponding to the ASCII
character set.

@endnode

@node "ChDir Intrinsic (subroutine)" "g77.guide/ChDir Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@next "ChMod Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@prev "Char Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

ChDir Intrinsic (subroutine)
............................

     CALL ChDir(DIR, STATUS)

DIR: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

STATUS: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; OPTIONAL; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Sets the current working directory to be DIR.  If the STATUS
argument is supplied, it contains 0 on success or a nonzero error code
otherwise upon return.  See @{b}chdir(3)@{ub}.

   @{i}Caution:@{ui} Using this routine during I/O to a unit connected with a
non-absolute file name can cause subsequent I/O on such a unit to fail
because the I/O library might reopen files by name.

   Some non-GNU implementations of Fortran provide this intrinsic as
only a function, not as a subroutine, or do not support the (optional)
STATUS argument.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"ChDir Intrinsic (function)" link "ChDir Intrinsic (function)"}.

@endnode

@node "ChMod Intrinsic (subroutine)" "g77.guide/ChMod Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@next "CLog Intrinsic"
@prev "ChDir Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

ChMod Intrinsic (subroutine)
............................

     CALL ChMod(NAME, MODE, STATUS)

NAME: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

MODE: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

STATUS: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; OPTIONAL; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Changes the access mode of file NAME according to the specification
MODE, which is given in the format of @{b}chmod(1)@{ub}.  A null character
(@{b}CHAR(0)@{ub}) marks the end of the name in NAME--otherwise, trailing blanks
in NAME are ignored.  Currently, NAME must not contain the single quote
character.

   If the STATUS argument is supplied, it contains 0 on success or a
nonzero error code upon return.

   Note that this currently works by actually invoking @{b}/bin/chmod@{ub} (or
the @{b}chmod@{ub} found when the library was configured) and so might fail in
some circumstances and will, anyway, be slow.

   Some non-GNU implementations of Fortran provide this intrinsic as
only a function, not as a subroutine, or do not support the (optional)
STATUS argument.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"ChMod Intrinsic (function)" link "ChMod Intrinsic (function)"}.

@endnode

@node "CLog Intrinsic" "g77.guide/CLog Intrinsic"
@next "Cmplx Intrinsic"
@prev "ChMod Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

CLog Intrinsic
..............

     CLog(X)

CLog: @{b}COMPLEX(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

X: @{b}COMPLEX(KIND=1)@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Archaic form of @{b}LOG()@{ub} that is specific to one type for X.  See
@{"Log Intrinsic" link "Log Intrinsic"}.

@endnode

@node "Cmplx Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Cmplx Intrinsic"
@next "Complex Intrinsic"
@prev "CLog Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Cmplx Intrinsic
...............

     Cmplx(X, Y)

Cmplx: @{b}COMPLEX(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

X: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}, @{b}REAL@{ub}, or @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Y: @{b}INTEGER@{ub} or @{b}REAL@{ub}; OPTIONAL (must be omitted if X is @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}); scalar;
INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   If X is not type @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}, constructs a value of type @{b}COMPLEX(KIND=1)@{ub}
from the real and imaginary values specified by X and Y, respectively.
If Y is omitted, @{b}0.@{ub} is assumed.

   If X is type @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}, converts it to type @{b}COMPLEX(KIND=1)@{ub}.

   See @{"Complex Intrinsic" link "Complex Intrinsic"}, for information on easily constructing a
@{b}COMPLEX@{ub} value of arbitrary precision from @{b}REAL@{ub} arguments.

@endnode

@node "Complex Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Complex Intrinsic"
@next "Conjg Intrinsic"
@prev "Cmplx Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Complex Intrinsic
.................

     Complex(REAL, IMAG)

Complex: @{b}COMPLEX@{ub} function, the exact type being the result of
cross-promoting the types of all the arguments.

REAL: @{b}INTEGER@{ub} or @{b}REAL@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

IMAG: @{b}INTEGER@{ub} or @{b}REAL@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}gnu@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns a @{b}COMPLEX@{ub} value that has @{b}Real@{ub} and @{b}Imag@{ub} as its real and
imaginary parts, respectively.

   If REAL and IMAG are the same type, and that type is not @{b}INTEGER@{ub}, no
data conversion is performed, and the type of the resulting value has
the same kind value as the types of REAL and IMAG.

   If REAL and IMAG are not the same type, the usual type-promotion
rules are applied to both, converting either or both to the appropriate
@{b}REAL@{ub} type.  The type of the resulting value has the same kind value as
the type to which both REAL and IMAG were converted, in this case.

   If REAL and IMAG are both @{b}INTEGER@{ub}, they are both converted to
@{b}REAL(KIND=1)@{ub}, and the result of the @{b}COMPLEX()@{ub} invocation is type
@{b}COMPLEX(KIND=1)@{ub}.

   @{i}Note:@{ui} The way to do this in standard Fortran 90 is too hairy to
describe here, but it is important to note that @{b}CMPLX(D1,D2)@{ub} returns a
@{b}COMPLEX(KIND=1)@{ub} result even if @{b}D1@{ub} and @{b}D2@{ub} are type @{b}REAL(KIND=2)@{ub}.  Hence
the availability of @{b}COMPLEX()@{ub} in GNU Fortran.

@endnode

@node "Conjg Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Conjg Intrinsic"
@next "Cos Intrinsic"
@prev "Complex Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Conjg Intrinsic
...............

     Conjg(Z)

Conjg: @{b}COMPLEX@{ub} function, the @{b}KIND=@{ub} value of the type being that of
argument Z.

Z: @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Returns the complex conjugate:

     COMPLEX(REALPART(Z), -IMAGPART(Z))

@endnode

@node "Cos Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Cos Intrinsic"
@next "CosH Intrinsic"
