@node "DTime Intrinsic (subroutine)" "g77.guide/DTime Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@next "EOShift Intrinsic"
@prev "DTanH Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

DTime Intrinsic (subroutine)
............................

     CALL DTime(TARRAY, RESULT)

TARRAY: @{b}REAL(KIND=1)@{ub}; DIMENSION(2); INTENT(OUT).

RESULT: @{b}REAL(KIND=1)@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Initially, return the number of seconds of runtime since the start
of the process's execution in RESULT, and the user and system
components of this in @{b}TARRAY(1)@{ub} and @{b}TARRAY(2)@{ub} respectively.  The value
of RESULT is equal to @{b}TARRAY(1) + TARRAY(2)@{ub}.

   Subsequent invocations of @{b}DTIME()@{ub} set values based on accumulations
since the previous invocation.

   On some systems, the underlying timings are represented using types
with sufficiently small limits that overflows (wraparounds) are
possible, such as 32-bit types.  Therefore, the values returned by this
intrinsic might be, or become, negative, or numerically less than
previous values, during a single run of the compiled program.

   Some non-GNU implementations of Fortran provide this intrinsic as
only a function, not as a subroutine.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"DTime Intrinsic (function)" link "DTime Intrinsic (function)"}.

@endnode

@node "EOShift Intrinsic" "g77.guide/EOShift Intrinsic"
@next "Epsilon Intrinsic"
@prev "DTime Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

EOShift Intrinsic
.................

This intrinsic is not yet implemented.  The name is, however, reserved
as an intrinsic.  Use @{b}EXTERNAL EOShift@{ub} to use this name for an external
procedure.

@endnode

@node "Epsilon Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Epsilon Intrinsic"
@next "ErF Intrinsic"
@prev "EOShift Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Epsilon Intrinsic
.................

This intrinsic is not yet implemented.  The name is, however, reserved
as an intrinsic.  Use @{b}EXTERNAL Epsilon@{ub} to use this name for an external
procedure.

@endnode

@node "ErF Intrinsic" "g77.guide/ErF Intrinsic"
@next "ErFC Intrinsic"
@prev "Epsilon Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

ErF Intrinsic
.............

     ErF(X)

ErF: @{b}REAL@{ub} function, the @{b}KIND=@{ub} value of the type being that of argument
X.

X: @{b}REAL@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns the error function of X.  See @{b}erf(3m)@{ub}, which provides the
implementation.

@endnode

@node "ErFC Intrinsic" "g77.guide/ErFC Intrinsic"
@next "ETime Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@prev "ErF Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

ErFC Intrinsic
..............

     ErFC(X)

ErFC: @{b}REAL@{ub} function, the @{b}KIND=@{ub} value of the type being that of argument
X.

X: @{b}REAL@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns the complementary error function of X: @{b}ERFC(R) = 1 - ERF(R)@{ub}
(except that the result might be more accurate than explicitly
evaluating that formulae would give).  See @{b}erfc(3m)@{ub}, which provides the
implementation.

@endnode

@node "ETime Intrinsic (subroutine)" "g77.guide/ETime Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@next "ETime Intrinsic (function)"
@prev "ErFC Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

ETime Intrinsic (subroutine)
............................

     CALL ETime(TARRAY, RESULT)

TARRAY: @{b}REAL(KIND=1)@{ub}; DIMENSION(2); INTENT(OUT).

RESULT: @{b}REAL(KIND=1)@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Return the number of seconds of runtime since the start of the
process's execution in RESULT, and the user and system components of
this in @{b}TARRAY(1)@{ub} and @{b}TARRAY(2)@{ub} respectively.  The value of RESULT is
equal to @{b}TARRAY(1) + TARRAY(2)@{ub}.

   On some systems, the underlying timings are represented using types
with sufficiently small limits that overflows (wraparounds) are
possible, such as 32-bit types.  Therefore, the values returned by this
intrinsic might be, or become, negative, or numerically less than
previous values, during a single run of the compiled program.

   Some non-GNU implementations of Fortran provide this intrinsic as
only a function, not as a subroutine.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"ETime Intrinsic (function)" link "ETime Intrinsic (function)"}.

@endnode

@node "ETime Intrinsic (function)" "g77.guide/ETime Intrinsic (function)"
@next "Exit Intrinsic"
@prev "ETime Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

ETime Intrinsic (function)
..........................

     ETime(TARRAY)

ETime: @{b}REAL(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

TARRAY: @{b}REAL(KIND=1)@{ub}; DIMENSION(2); INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Return the number of seconds of runtime since the start of the
process's execution as the function value, and the user and system
components of this in @{b}TARRAY(1)@{ub} and @{b}TARRAY(2)@{ub} respectively.  The
functions' value is equal to @{b}TARRAY(1) + TARRAY(2)@{ub}.

   On some systems, the underlying timings are represented using types
with sufficiently small limits that overflows (wraparounds) are
possible, such as 32-bit types.  Therefore, the values returned by this
intrinsic might be, or become, negative, or numerically less than
previous values, during a single run of the compiled program.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"ETime Intrinsic (subroutine)" link "ETime Intrinsic (subroutine)"}.

@endnode

@node "Exit Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Exit Intrinsic"
@next "Exp Intrinsic"
@prev "ETime Intrinsic (function)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Exit Intrinsic
..............

     CALL Exit(STATUS)

STATUS: @{b}INTEGER@{ub} not wider than the default kind; OPTIONAL; scalar;
INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Exit the program with status STATUS after closing open Fortran I/O
units and otherwise behaving as @{b}exit(2)@{ub}.  If STATUS is omitted the
canonical `success' value will be returned to the system.

@endnode

@node "Exp Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Exp Intrinsic"
@next "Exponent Intrinsic"
@prev "Exit Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Exp Intrinsic
.............

     Exp(X)

Exp: @{b}REAL@{ub} or @{b}COMPLEX@{ub} function, the exact type being that of argument X.

X: @{b}REAL@{ub} or @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Returns @{b}E**X@{ub}, where E is approximately 2.7182818.

   See @{"Log Intrinsic" link "Log Intrinsic"}, for the inverse of this function.

@endnode

@node "Exponent Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Exponent Intrinsic"
@next "FDate Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@prev "Exp Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Exponent Intrinsic
..................

This intrinsic is not yet implemented.  The name is, however, reserved
as an intrinsic.  Use @{b}EXTERNAL Exponent@{ub} to use this name for an
external procedure.

@endnode

@node "FDate Intrinsic (subroutine)" "g77.guide/FDate Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@next "FDate Intrinsic (function)"
@prev "Exponent Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

FDate Intrinsic (subroutine)
............................

     CALL FDate(DATE)

DATE: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns the current date (using the same format as @{b}CTIME()@{ub}) in DATE.

   Equivalent to:

     CALL CTIME(DATE, TIME8())

   Programs making use of this intrinsic might not be Year 10000 (Y10K)
compliant.  For example, the date might appear, to such programs, to
wrap around (change from a larger value to a smaller one) as of the
Year 10000.

   See @{"CTime Intrinsic (subroutine)" link "CTime Intrinsic (subroutine)"}.

   Some non-GNU implementations of Fortran provide this intrinsic as
only a function, not as a subroutine.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"FDate Intrinsic (function)" link "FDate Intrinsic (function)"}.

@endnode

@node "FDate Intrinsic (function)" "g77.guide/FDate Intrinsic (function)"
@next "FGet Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@prev "FDate Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

FDate Intrinsic (function)
..........................

     FDate()

FDate: @{b}CHARACTER*(*)@{ub} function.

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns the current date (using the same format as @{b}CTIME()@{ub}).

   Equivalent to:

     CTIME(TIME8())

   Programs making use of this intrinsic might not be Year 10000 (Y10K)
compliant.  For example, the date might appear, to such programs, to
wrap around (change from a larger value to a smaller one) as of the
Year 10000.

   See @{"CTime Intrinsic (function)" link "CTime Intrinsic (function)"}.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"FDate Intrinsic (subroutine)" link "FDate Intrinsic (subroutine)"}.

@endnode

@node "FGet Intrinsic (subroutine)" "g77.guide/FGet Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@next "FGetC Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@prev "FDate Intrinsic (function)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

FGet Intrinsic (subroutine)
...........................

     CALL FGet(C, STATUS)

C: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

STATUS: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; OPTIONAL; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Reads a single character into C in stream mode from unit 5
(by-passing normal formatted output) using @{b}getc(3)@{ub}.  Returns in STATUS
0 on success, -1 on end-of-file, and the error code from @{b}ferror(3)@{ub}
otherwise.

   Stream I/O should not be mixed with normal record-oriented
(formatted or unformatted) I/O on the same unit; the results are
unpredictable.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"FGet Intrinsic (function)" link "FGet Intrinsic (function)"}.

@endnode

@node "FGetC Intrinsic (subroutine)" "g77.guide/FGetC Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@next "Float Intrinsic"
@prev "FGet Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

FGetC Intrinsic (subroutine)
............................

     CALL FGetC(UNIT, C, STATUS)

UNIT: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

C: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

STATUS: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; OPTIONAL; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Reads a single character into C in stream mode from unit UNIT
(by-passing normal formatted output) using @{b}getc(3)@{ub}.  Returns in STATUS
0 on success, -1 on end-of-file, and the error code from @{b}ferror(3)@{ub}
otherwise.

   Stream I/O should not be mixed with normal record-oriented
(formatted or unformatted) I/O on the same unit; the results are
unpredictable.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"FGetC Intrinsic (function)" link "FGetC Intrinsic (function)"}.

@endnode

