     Float(A)

Float: @{b}REAL(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

A: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Archaic form of @{b}REAL()@{ub} that is specific to one type for A.  See
@{"Real Intrinsic" link "Real Intrinsic"}.

@endnode

@node "Floor Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Floor Intrinsic"
@next "Flush Intrinsic"
@prev "Float Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Floor Intrinsic
...............

This intrinsic is not yet implemented.  The name is, however, reserved
as an intrinsic.  Use @{b}EXTERNAL Floor@{ub} to use this name for an external
procedure.

@endnode

@node "Flush Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Flush Intrinsic"
@next "FNum Intrinsic"
@prev "Floor Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Flush Intrinsic
...............

     CALL Flush(UNIT)

UNIT: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; OPTIONAL; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Flushes Fortran unit(s) currently open for output.  Without the
optional argument, all such units are flushed, otherwise just the unit
specified by UNIT.

   Some non-GNU implementations of Fortran provide this intrinsic as a
library procedure that might or might not support the (optional) UNIT
argument.

@endnode

@node "FNum Intrinsic" "g77.guide/FNum Intrinsic"
@next "FPut Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@prev "Flush Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

FNum Intrinsic
..............

     FNum(UNIT)

FNum: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

UNIT: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns the Unix file descriptor number corresponding to the open
Fortran I/O unit UNIT.  This could be passed to an interface to C I/O
routines.

@endnode

@node "FPut Intrinsic (subroutine)" "g77.guide/FPut Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@next "FPutC Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@prev "FNum Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

FPut Intrinsic (subroutine)
...........................

     CALL FPut(C, STATUS)

C: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

STATUS: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; OPTIONAL; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Writes the single character C in stream mode to unit 6 (by-passing
normal formatted output) using @{b}putc(3)@{ub}.  Returns in STATUS 0 on
success, the error code from @{b}ferror(3)@{ub} otherwise.

   Stream I/O should not be mixed with normal record-oriented
(formatted or unformatted) I/O on the same unit; the results are
unpredictable.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"FPut Intrinsic (function)" link "FPut Intrinsic (function)"}.

@endnode

@node "FPutC Intrinsic (subroutine)" "g77.guide/FPutC Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@next "Fraction Intrinsic"
@prev "FPut Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

FPutC Intrinsic (subroutine)
............................

     CALL FPutC(UNIT, C, STATUS)

UNIT: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

C: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

STATUS: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; OPTIONAL; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Writes the single character UNIT in stream mode to unit 6
(by-passing normal formatted output) using @{b}putc(3)@{ub}.  Returns in C 0 on
success, the error code from @{b}ferror(3)@{ub} otherwise.

   Stream I/O should not be mixed with normal record-oriented
(formatted or unformatted) I/O on the same unit; the results are
unpredictable.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"FPutC Intrinsic (function)" link "FPutC Intrinsic (function)"}.

@endnode

@node "Fraction Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Fraction Intrinsic"
@next "FSeek Intrinsic"
@prev "FPutC Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Fraction Intrinsic
..................

This intrinsic is not yet implemented.  The name is, however, reserved
as an intrinsic.  Use @{b}EXTERNAL Fraction@{ub} to use this name for an
external procedure.

@endnode

@node "FSeek Intrinsic" "g77.guide/FSeek Intrinsic"
@next "FStat Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@prev "Fraction Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

FSeek Intrinsic
...............

     CALL FSeek(UNIT, OFFSET, WHENCE, ERRLAB)

UNIT: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

OFFSET: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

WHENCE: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

ERRLAB: @{b}*LABEL@{ub}, where LABEL is the label of an executable statement;
OPTIONAL.

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Attempts to move Fortran unit UNIT to the specified OFFSET: absolute
offset if WHENCE=0; relative to the current offset if WHENCE=1;
relative to the end of the file if WHENCE=2.  It branches to label
ERRLAB if UNIT is not open or if the call otherwise fails.

@endnode

@node "FStat Intrinsic (subroutine)" "g77.guide/FStat Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@next "FStat Intrinsic (function)"
@prev "FSeek Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

FStat Intrinsic (subroutine)
............................

     CALL FStat(UNIT, SARRAY, STATUS)

UNIT: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

SARRAY: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; DIMENSION(13); INTENT(OUT).

STATUS: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; OPTIONAL; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Obtains data about the file open on Fortran I/O unit UNIT and places
them in the array SARRAY.  The values in this array are extracted from
the @{b}stat@{ub} structure as returned by @{b}fstat(2)@{ub} q.v., as follows:

  1. Device ID

  2. Inode number

  3. File mode

  4. Number of links

  5. Owner's uid

  6. Owner's gid

  7. ID of device containing directory entry for file (0 if not
     available)

  8. File size (bytes)

  9. Last access time

 10. Last modification time

 11. Last file status change time

 12. Preferred I/O block size (-1 if not available)

 13. Number of blocks allocated (-1 if not available)

   Not all these elements are relevant on all systems.  If an element
is not relevant, it is returned as 0.

   If the STATUS argument is supplied, it contains 0 on success or a
nonzero error code upon return.

   Some non-GNU implementations of Fortran provide this intrinsic as
only a function, not as a subroutine, or do not support the (optional)
STATUS argument.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"FStat Intrinsic (function)" link "FStat Intrinsic (function)"}.

@endnode

@node "FStat Intrinsic (function)" "g77.guide/FStat Intrinsic (function)"
@next "FTell Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@prev "FStat Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

FStat Intrinsic (function)
..........................

     FStat(UNIT, SARRAY)

FStat: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

UNIT: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

SARRAY: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; DIMENSION(13); INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Obtains data about the file open on Fortran I/O unit UNIT and places
them in the array SARRAY.  The values in this array are extracted from
the @{b}stat@{ub} structure as returned by @{b}fstat(2)@{ub} q.v., as follows:

  1. Device ID

  2. Inode number

  3. File mode

  4. Number of links

  5. Owner's uid

  6. Owner's gid

  7. ID of device containing directory entry for file (0 if not
     available)

  8. File size (bytes)

  9. Last access time

 10. Last modification time

 11. Last file status change time

 12. Preferred I/O block size (-1 if not available)

 13. Number of blocks allocated (-1 if not available)

   Not all these elements are relevant on all systems.  If an element
is not relevant, it is returned as 0.

   Returns 0 on success or a nonzero error code.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"FStat Intrinsic (subroutine)" link "FStat Intrinsic (subroutine)"}.

@endnode

@node "FTell Intrinsic (subroutine)" "g77.guide/FTell Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@next "FTell Intrinsic (function)"
@prev "FStat Intrinsic (function)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

FTell Intrinsic (subroutine)
............................

     CALL FTell(UNIT, OFFSET)

UNIT: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

OFFSET: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Sets OFFSET to the current offset of Fortran unit UNIT (or to -1 if
UNIT is not open).

   Some non-GNU implementations of Fortran provide this intrinsic as
only a function, not as a subroutine.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"FTell Intrinsic (function)" link "FTell Intrinsic (function)"}.

@endnode

@node "FTell Intrinsic (function)" "g77.guide/FTell Intrinsic (function)"
@next "GError Intrinsic"
@prev "FTell Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

FTell Intrinsic (function)
..........................

     FTell(UNIT)

FTell: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

UNIT: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns the current offset of Fortran unit UNIT (or -1 if UNIT is
not open).

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"FTell Intrinsic (subroutine)" link "FTell Intrinsic (subroutine)"}.

@endnode

@node "GError Intrinsic" "g77.guide/GError Intrinsic"
@next "GetArg Intrinsic"
@prev "FTell Intrinsic (function)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

GError Intrinsic
................

     CALL GError(MESSAGE)

MESSAGE: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns the system error message corresponding to the last system
error (C @{b}errno@{ub}).

@endnode

@node "GetArg Intrinsic" "g77.guide/GetArg Intrinsic"
@next "GetCWD Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@prev "GError Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

GetArg Intrinsic
................

     CALL GetArg(POS, VALUE)

POS: @{b}INTEGER@{ub} not wider than the default kind; scalar; INTENT(IN).

VALUE: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Sets VALUE to the POS-th command-line argument (or to all blanks if
there are fewer than VALUE command-line arguments); @{b}CALL GETARG(0,
VALUE)@{ub} sets VALUE to the name of the program (on systems that support
this feature).

   See @{"IArgC Intrinsic" link "IArgC Intrinsic"}, for information on how to get the number of
arguments.

@endnode

@node "GetCWD Intrinsic (subroutine)" "g77.guide/GetCWD Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@next "GetCWD Intrinsic (function)"
@prev "GetArg Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

GetCWD Intrinsic (subroutine)
.............................

     CALL GetCWD(NAME, STATUS)

NAME: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

STATUS: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; OPTIONAL; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Places the current working directory in NAME.  If the STATUS
argument is supplied, it contains 0 success or a nonzero error code
upon return (@{b}ENOSYS@{ub} if the system does not provide @{b}getcwd(3)@{ub} or
@{b}getwd(3)@{ub}).

   Some non-GNU implementations of Fortran provide this intrinsic as
only a function, not as a subroutine, or do not support the (optional)
STATUS argument.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"GetCWD Intrinsic (function)" link "GetCWD Intrinsic (function)"}.

@endnode

@node "GetCWD Intrinsic (function)" "g77.guide/GetCWD Intrinsic (function)"
@next "GetEnv Intrinsic"
@prev "GetCWD Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

GetCWD Intrinsic (function)
...........................

     GetCWD(NAME)

GetCWD: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

NAME: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Places the current working directory in NAME.  Returns 0 on success,
otherwise a nonzero error code (@{b}ENOSYS@{ub} if the system does not provide
@{b}getcwd(3)@{ub} or @{b}getwd(3)@{ub}).

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"GetCWD Intrinsic (subroutine)" link "GetCWD Intrinsic (subroutine)"}.

@endnode

@node "GetEnv Intrinsic" "g77.guide/GetEnv Intrinsic"
@next "GetGId Intrinsic"
@prev "GetCWD Intrinsic (function)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

GetEnv Intrinsic
................

     CALL GetEnv(NAME, VALUE)

NAME: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

VALUE: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Sets VALUE to the value of environment variable given by the value
of NAME (@{b}$name@{ub} in shell terms) or to blanks if @{b}$name@{ub} has not been set.
A null character (@{b}CHAR(0)@{ub}) marks the end of the name in NAME--otherwise,
trailing blanks in NAME are ignored.

@endnode

@node "GetGId Intrinsic" "g77.guide/GetGId Intrinsic"
@next "GetLog Intrinsic"
@prev "GetEnv Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

GetGId Intrinsic
................

     GetGId()

GetGId: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns the group id for the current process.

@endnode

@node "GetLog Intrinsic" "g77.guide/GetLog Intrinsic"
@next "GetPId Intrinsic"
@prev "GetGId Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

GetLog Intrinsic
................

     CALL GetLog(LOGIN)

LOGIN: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns the login name for the process in LOGIN.

   @{i}Caution:@{ui} On some systems, the @{b}getlogin(3)@{ub} function, which this
intrinsic calls at run time, is either not implemented or returns a
null pointer.  In the latter case, this intrinsic returns blanks in
LOGIN.

@endnode

@node "GetPId Intrinsic" "g77.guide/GetPId Intrinsic"
@next "GetUId Intrinsic"
@prev "GetLog Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

GetPId Intrinsic
................

     GetPId()

GetPId: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns the process id for the current process.

@endnode

@node "GetUId Intrinsic" "g77.guide/GetUId Intrinsic"
@next "GMTime Intrinsic"
@prev "GetPId Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

GetUId Intrinsic
................

     GetUId()

GetUId: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns the user id for the current process.

@endnode

@node "GMTime Intrinsic" "g77.guide/GMTime Intrinsic"
@next "HostNm Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@prev "GetUId Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

GMTime Intrinsic
................

     CALL GMTime(STIME, TARRAY)

STIME: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

TARRAY: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; DIMENSION(9); INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Given a system time value STIME, fills TARRAY with values extracted
from it appropriate to the GMT time zone using @{b}gmtime(3)@{ub}.

   The array elements are as follows:

  1. Seconds after the minute, range 0-59 or 0-61 to allow for leap
     seconds

  2. Minutes after the hour, range 0-59

  3. Hours past midnight, range 0-23

  4. Day of month, range 0-31

  5. Number of months since January, range 0-12

  6. Years since 1900

  7. Number of days since Sunday, range 0-6

  8. Days since January 1

  9. Daylight savings indicator: positive if daylight savings is in
     effect, zero if not, and negative if the information isn't
     available.

@endnode

@node "HostNm Intrinsic (subroutine)" "g77.guide/HostNm Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@next "HostNm Intrinsic (function)"
@prev "GMTime Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

HostNm Intrinsic (subroutine)
.............................

     CALL HostNm(NAME, STATUS)

NAME: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

STATUS: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; OPTIONAL; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Fills NAME with the system's host name returned by @{b}gethostname(2)@{ub}.
If the STATUS argument is supplied, it contains 0 on success or a
nonzero error code upon return (@{b}ENOSYS@{ub} if the system does not provide
@{b}gethostname(2)@{ub}).

   Some non-GNU implementations of Fortran provide this intrinsic as
only a function, not as a subroutine, or do not support the (optional)
STATUS argument.

   On some systems (specifically SCO) it might be necessary to link the
"socket" library if you call this routine.  Typically this means adding
@{b}-lg2c -lsocket -lm@{ub} to the @{b}g77@{ub} command line when linking the program.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"HostNm Intrinsic (function)" link "HostNm Intrinsic (function)"}.

@endnode

@node "HostNm Intrinsic (function)" "g77.guide/HostNm Intrinsic (function)"
@next "Huge Intrinsic"
@prev "HostNm Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

HostNm Intrinsic (function)
...........................

     HostNm(NAME)

HostNm: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

NAME: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Fills NAME with the system's host name returned by @{b}gethostname(2)@{ub},
returning 0 on success or a nonzero error code (@{b}ENOSYS@{ub} if the system
does not provide @{b}gethostname(2)@{ub}).

   On some systems (specifically SCO) it might be necessary to link the
"socket" library if you call this routine.  Typically this means adding
@{b}-lg2c -lsocket -lm@{ub} to the @{b}g77@{ub} command line when linking the program.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"HostNm Intrinsic (subroutine)" link "HostNm Intrinsic (subroutine)"}.

@endnode

@node "Huge Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Huge Intrinsic"
@next "IAbs Intrinsic"
@prev "HostNm Intrinsic (function)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Huge Intrinsic
..............

This intrinsic is not yet implemented.  The name is, however, reserved
as an intrinsic.  Use @{b}EXTERNAL Huge@{ub} to use this name for an external
procedure.

@endnode

@node "IAbs Intrinsic" "g77.guide/IAbs Intrinsic"
@next "IAChar Intrinsic"
@prev "Huge Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

IAbs Intrinsic
..............

     IAbs(A)

IAbs: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

A: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Archaic form of @{b}ABS()@{ub} that is specific to one type for A.  See
@{"Abs Intrinsic" link "Abs Intrinsic"}.

@endnode

@node "IAChar Intrinsic" "g77.guide/IAChar Intrinsic"
@next "IAnd Intrinsic"
@prev "IAbs Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

IAChar Intrinsic
................

     IAChar(C)

IAChar: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

C: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}f2c@{ub}, @{b}f90@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns the code for the ASCII character in the first character
position of C.

   See @{"AChar Intrinsic" link "AChar Intrinsic"}, for the inverse of this function.

   See @{"IChar Intrinsic" link "IChar Intrinsic"}, for the function corresponding to the system's
native character set.

@endnode

@node "IAnd Intrinsic" "g77.guide/IAnd Intrinsic"
@next "IArgC Intrinsic"
@prev "IAChar Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

IAnd Intrinsic
..............

     IAnd(I, J)

IAnd: @{b}INTEGER@{ub} function, the exact type being the result of
cross-promoting the types of all the arguments.

I: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

J: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}mil@{ub}, @{b}f90@{ub}, @{b}vxt@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns value resulting from boolean AND of pair of bits in each of
I and J.

@endnode

@node "IArgC Intrinsic" "g77.guide/IArgC Intrinsic"
@next "IBClr Intrinsic"
@prev "IAnd Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

IArgC Intrinsic
...............

     IArgC()

IArgC: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns the number of command-line arguments.

   This count does not include the specification of the program name
itself.

@endnode

@node "IBClr Intrinsic" "g77.guide/IBClr Intrinsic"
@next "IBits Intrinsic"
@prev "IArgC Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

IBClr Intrinsic
...............

     IBClr(I, POS)

IBClr: @{b}INTEGER@{ub} function, the @{b}KIND=@{ub} value of the type being that of
argument I.

I: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

POS: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}mil@{ub}, @{b}f90@{ub}, @{b}vxt@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns the value of I with bit POS cleared (set to zero).  See
@{"BTest Intrinsic" link "BTest Intrinsic"}, for information on bit positions.

@endnode

@node "IBits Intrinsic" "g77.guide/IBits Intrinsic"
@next "IBSet Intrinsic"
@prev "IBClr Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

IBits Intrinsic
...............

     IBits(I, POS, LEN)

IBits: @{b}INTEGER@{ub} function, the @{b}KIND=@{ub} value of the type being that of
argument I.

I: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

POS: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

LEN: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}mil@{ub}, @{b}f90@{ub}, @{b}vxt@{ub}.

Description:

   Extracts a subfield of length LEN from I, starting from bit position
POS and extending left for LEN bits.  The result is right-justified and
the remaining bits are zeroed.  The value of @{b}POS+LEN@{ub} must be less than
or equal to the value @{b}BIT_SIZE(I)@{ub}.  See @{"Bit_Size Intrinsic" link "Bit_Size Intrinsic"}.

@endnode

@node "IBSet Intrinsic" "g77.guide/IBSet Intrinsic"
@next "IChar Intrinsic"
@prev "IBits Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

IBSet Intrinsic
...............

     IBSet(I, POS)

IBSet: @{b}INTEGER@{ub} function, the @{b}KIND=@{ub} value of the type being that of
argument I.

I: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

POS: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}mil@{ub}, @{b}f90@{ub}, @{b}vxt@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns the value of I with bit POS set (to one).  See
@{"BTest Intrinsic" link "BTest Intrinsic"}, for information on bit positions.

@endnode

@node "IChar Intrinsic" "g77.guide/IChar Intrinsic"
@next "IDate Intrinsic (UNIX)"
@prev "IBSet Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

IChar Intrinsic
...............

     IChar(C)

IChar: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

C: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Returns the code for the character in the first character position
of C.

   Because the system's native character set is used, the
correspondence between character and their codes is not necessarily the
same between GNU Fortran implementations.

   Note that no intrinsic exists to convert a printable character
string to a numerical value.  For example, there is no intrinsic that,
given the @{b}CHARACTER@{ub} value @{b}'154'@{ub}, returns an @{b}INTEGER@{ub} or @{b}REAL@{ub} value with
the value @{b}154@{ub}.

   Instead, you can use internal-file I/O to do this kind of conversion.
For example:

     INTEGER VALUE
     CHARACTER*10 STRING
     STRING = '154'
     READ (STRING, '(I10)'), VALUE
     PRINT *, VALUE
     END

   The above program, when run, prints:

      154

   See @{"Char Intrinsic" link "Char Intrinsic"}, for the inverse of the @{b}ICHAR@{ub} function.

   See @{"IAChar Intrinsic" link "IAChar Intrinsic"}, for the function corresponding to the ASCII
character set.

@endnode

@node "IDate Intrinsic (UNIX)" "g77.guide/IDate Intrinsic (UNIX)"
@next "IDiM Intrinsic"
@prev "IChar Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

IDate Intrinsic (UNIX)
......................

     CALL IDate(TARRAY)

TARRAY: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; DIMENSION(3); INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Fills TARRAY with the numerical values at the current local time.
The day (in the range 1-31), month (in the range 1-12), and year appear
in elements 1, 2, and 3 of TARRAY, respectively.  The year has four
significant digits.

   Programs making use of this intrinsic might not be Year 10000 (Y10K)
compliant.  For example, the date might appear, to such programs, to
wrap around (change from a larger value to a smaller one) as of the
Year 10000.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"IDate Intrinsic (VXT)" link "IDate Intrinsic (VXT)"}.

@endnode

@node "IDiM Intrinsic" "g77.guide/IDiM Intrinsic"
@next "IDInt Intrinsic"
@prev "IDate Intrinsic (UNIX)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

IDiM Intrinsic
..............

     IDiM(X, Y)

IDiM: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

X: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Y: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Archaic form of @{b}DIM()@{ub} that is specific to one type for X and Y.  See
@{"DiM Intrinsic" link "DiM Intrinsic"}.

@endnode

