@next "Imag Intrinsic"
@prev "IErrNo Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

IFix Intrinsic
..............

     IFix(A)

IFix: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

A: @{b}REAL(KIND=1)@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Archaic form of @{b}INT()@{ub} that is specific to one type for A.  See
@{"Int Intrinsic" link "Int Intrinsic"}.

@endnode

@node "Imag Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Imag Intrinsic"
@next "ImagPart Intrinsic"
@prev "IFix Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Imag Intrinsic
..............

     Imag(Z)

Imag: @{b}REAL@{ub} function, the @{b}KIND=@{ub} value of the type being that of argument
Z.

Z: @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}f2c@{ub}.

Description:

   The imaginary part of Z is returned, without conversion.

   @{i}Note:@{ui} The way to do this in standard Fortran 90 is @{b}AIMAG(Z)@{ub}.
However, when, for example, Z is @{b}DOUBLE COMPLEX@{ub}, @{b}AIMAG(Z)@{ub} means
something different for some compilers that are not true Fortran 90
compilers but offer some extensions standardized by Fortran 90 (such as
the @{b}DOUBLE COMPLEX@{ub} type, also known as @{b}COMPLEX(KIND=2)@{ub}).

   The advantage of @{b}IMAG()@{ub} is that, while not necessarily more or less
portable than @{b}AIMAG()@{ub}, it is more likely to cause a compiler that
doesn't support it to produce a diagnostic than generate incorrect code.

   See @{"REAL() and AIMAG() of Complex" link "REAL() and AIMAG() of Complex"}, for more information.

@endnode

@node "ImagPart Intrinsic" "g77.guide/ImagPart Intrinsic"
@next "Index Intrinsic"
@prev "Imag Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

ImagPart Intrinsic
..................

     ImagPart(Z)

ImagPart: @{b}REAL@{ub} function, the @{b}KIND=@{ub} value of the type being that of
argument Z.

Z: @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}gnu@{ub}.

Description:

   The imaginary part of Z is returned, without conversion.

   @{i}Note:@{ui} The way to do this in standard Fortran 90 is @{b}AIMAG(Z)@{ub}.
However, when, for example, Z is @{b}DOUBLE COMPLEX@{ub}, @{b}AIMAG(Z)@{ub} means
something different for some compilers that are not true Fortran 90
compilers but offer some extensions standardized by Fortran 90 (such as
the @{b}DOUBLE COMPLEX@{ub} type, also known as @{b}COMPLEX(KIND=2)@{ub}).

   The advantage of @{b}IMAGPART()@{ub} is that, while not necessarily more or
less portable than @{b}AIMAG()@{ub}, it is more likely to cause a compiler that
doesn't support it to produce a diagnostic than generate incorrect code.

   See @{"REAL() and AIMAG() of Complex" link "REAL() and AIMAG() of Complex"}, for more information.

@endnode

@node "Index Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Index Intrinsic"
@next "Int Intrinsic"
@prev "ImagPart Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Index Intrinsic
...............

     Index(STRING, SUBSTRING)

Index: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

STRING: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

SUBSTRING: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Returns the position of the start of the first occurrence of string
SUBSTRING as a substring in STRING, counting from one.  If SUBSTRING
doesn't occur in STRING, zero is returned.

@endnode

@node "Int Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Int Intrinsic"
@next "Int2 Intrinsic"
@prev "Index Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Int Intrinsic
.............

     Int(A)

Int: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

A: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}, @{b}REAL@{ub}, or @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Returns A with the fractional portion of its magnitude truncated and
its sign preserved, converted to type @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}.

   If A is type @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}, its real part is truncated and converted, and
its imaginary part is disregarded.

   See @{"NInt Intrinsic" link "NInt Intrinsic"}, for how to convert, rounded to nearest whole
number.

   See @{"AInt Intrinsic" link "AInt Intrinsic"}, for how to truncate to whole number without
converting.

@endnode

@node "Int2 Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Int2 Intrinsic"
@next "Int8 Intrinsic"
@prev "Int Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Int2 Intrinsic
..............

     Int2(A)

Int2: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=6)@{ub} function.

A: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}, @{b}REAL@{ub}, or @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}gnu@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns A with the fractional portion of its magnitude truncated and
its sign preserved, converted to type @{b}INTEGER(KIND=6)@{ub}.

   If A is type @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}, its real part is truncated and converted, and
its imaginary part is disregarded.

   See @{"Int Intrinsic" link "Int Intrinsic"}.

   The precise meaning of this intrinsic might change in a future
version of the GNU Fortran language, as more is learned about how it is
used.

@endnode

@node "Int8 Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Int8 Intrinsic"
@next "IOr Intrinsic"
@prev "Int2 Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Int8 Intrinsic
..............

     Int8(A)

Int8: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=2)@{ub} function.

A: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}, @{b}REAL@{ub}, or @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}gnu@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns A with the fractional portion of its magnitude truncated and
its sign preserved, converted to type @{b}INTEGER(KIND=2)@{ub}.

   If A is type @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}, its real part is truncated and converted, and
its imaginary part is disregarded.

   See @{"Int Intrinsic" link "Int Intrinsic"}.

   The precise meaning of this intrinsic might change in a future
version of the GNU Fortran language, as more is learned about how it is
used.

@endnode

@node "IOr Intrinsic" "g77.guide/IOr Intrinsic"
@next "IRand Intrinsic"
@prev "Int8 Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

IOr Intrinsic
.............

     IOr(I, J)

IOr: @{b}INTEGER@{ub} function, the exact type being the result of
cross-promoting the types of all the arguments.

I: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

J: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}mil@{ub}, @{b}f90@{ub}, @{b}vxt@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns value resulting from boolean OR of pair of bits in each of I
and J.

@endnode

@node "IRand Intrinsic" "g77.guide/IRand Intrinsic"
@next "IsaTty Intrinsic"
@prev "IOr Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

IRand Intrinsic
...............

     IRand(FLAG)

IRand: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

FLAG: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; OPTIONAL; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns a uniform quasi-random number up to a system-dependent limit.
If FLAG is 0, the next number in sequence is returned; if FLAG is 1,
the generator is restarted by calling the UNIX function @{b}srand(0)@{ub}; if
FLAG has any other value, it is used as a new seed with @{b}srand()@{ub}.

   See @{"SRand Intrinsic" link "SRand Intrinsic"}.

   @{i}Note:@{ui} As typically implemented (by the routine of the same name in
the C library), this random number generator is a very poor one, though
the BSD and GNU libraries provide a much better implementation than the
`traditional' one.  On a different system you almost certainly want to
use something better.

@endnode

@node "IsaTty Intrinsic" "g77.guide/IsaTty Intrinsic"
@next "IShft Intrinsic"
@prev "IRand Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

IsaTty Intrinsic
................

     IsaTty(UNIT)

IsaTty: @{b}LOGICAL(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

UNIT: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns @{b}.TRUE.@{ub} if and only if the Fortran I/O unit specified by UNIT
is connected to a terminal device.  See @{b}isatty(3)@{ub}.

@endnode

@node "IShft Intrinsic" "g77.guide/IShft Intrinsic"
@next "IShftC Intrinsic"
@prev "IsaTty Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

IShft Intrinsic
...............

     IShft(I, SHIFT)

IShft: @{b}INTEGER@{ub} function, the @{b}KIND=@{ub} value of the type being that of
argument I.

I: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

SHIFT: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}mil@{ub}, @{b}f90@{ub}, @{b}vxt@{ub}.

Description:

   All bits representing I are shifted SHIFT places.  @{b}SHIFT.GT.0@{ub}
indicates a left shift, @{b}SHIFT.EQ.0@{ub} indicates no shift and @{b}SHIFT.LT.0@{ub}
indicates a right shift.  If the absolute value of the shift count is
greater than @{b}BIT_SIZE(I)@{ub}, the result is undefined.  Bits shifted out
from the left end or the right end are lost.  Zeros are shifted in from
the opposite end.

   See @{"IShftC Intrinsic" link "IShftC Intrinsic"}, for the circular-shift equivalent.

@endnode

@node "IShftC Intrinsic" "g77.guide/IShftC Intrinsic"
@next "ISign Intrinsic"
@prev "IShft Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

IShftC Intrinsic
................

     IShftC(I, SHIFT, SIZE)

IShftC: @{b}INTEGER@{ub} function, the @{b}KIND=@{ub} value of the type being that of
argument I.

I: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

SHIFT: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

SIZE: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}mil@{ub}, @{b}f90@{ub}, @{b}vxt@{ub}.

Description:

   The rightmost SIZE bits of the argument I are shifted circularly
SHIFT places, i.e. the bits shifted out of one end are shifted into the
opposite end.  No bits are lost.  The unshifted bits of the result are
the same as the unshifted bits of I.  The  absolute value of the
argument SHIFT must be less than or equal to SIZE.  The value of SIZE
must be greater than or equal to one and less than or equal to
@{b}BIT_SIZE(I)@{ub}.

   See @{"IShft Intrinsic" link "IShft Intrinsic"}, for the logical shift equivalent.

@endnode

@node "ISign Intrinsic" "g77.guide/ISign Intrinsic"
@next "ITime Intrinsic"
@prev "IShftC Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

ISign Intrinsic
...............

     ISign(A, B)

ISign: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

A: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

B: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Archaic form of @{b}SIGN()@{ub} that is specific to one type for A and B.
See @{"Sign Intrinsic" link "Sign Intrinsic"}.

@endnode

@node "ITime Intrinsic" "g77.guide/ITime Intrinsic"
@next "Kill Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@prev "ISign Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

ITime Intrinsic
...............

     CALL ITime(TARRAY)

TARRAY: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; DIMENSION(3); INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns the current local time hour, minutes, and seconds in elements
1, 2, and 3 of TARRAY, respectively.

@endnode

@node "Kill Intrinsic (subroutine)" "g77.guide/Kill Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@next "Kind Intrinsic"
@prev "ITime Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Kill Intrinsic (subroutine)
...........................

     CALL Kill(PID, SIGNAL, STATUS)

PID: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

SIGNAL: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

STATUS: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; OPTIONAL; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Sends the signal specified by SIGNAL to the process PID.  If the
STATUS argument is supplied, it contains 0 on success or a nonzero
error code upon return.  See @{b}kill(2)@{ub}.

   Some non-GNU implementations of Fortran provide this intrinsic as
only a function, not as a subroutine, or do not support the (optional)
STATUS argument.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"Kill Intrinsic (function)" link "Kill Intrinsic (function)"}.

@endnode

@node "Kind Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Kind Intrinsic"
@next "LBound Intrinsic"
@prev "Kill Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Kind Intrinsic
..............

This intrinsic is not yet implemented.  The name is, however, reserved
as an intrinsic.  Use @{b}EXTERNAL Kind@{ub} to use this name for an external
procedure.

@endnode

@node "LBound Intrinsic" "g77.guide/LBound Intrinsic"
@next "Len Intrinsic"
@prev "Kind Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

LBound Intrinsic
................

This intrinsic is not yet implemented.  The name is, however, reserved
as an intrinsic.  Use @{b}EXTERNAL LBound@{ub} to use this name for an external
procedure.

@endnode

@node "Len Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Len Intrinsic"
@next "Len_Trim Intrinsic"
@prev "LBound Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Len Intrinsic
.............

     Len(STRING)

Len: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

STRING: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar.

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Returns the length of STRING.

   If STRING is an array, the length of an element of STRING is
returned.

   Note that STRING need not be defined when this intrinsic is invoked,
since only the length, not the content, of STRING is needed.

   See @{"Bit_Size Intrinsic" link "Bit_Size Intrinsic"}, for the function that determines the size
of its argument in bits.

@endnode

@node "Len_Trim Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Len_Trim Intrinsic"
@next "LGe Intrinsic"
@prev "Len Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Len_Trim Intrinsic
..................

     Len_Trim(STRING)

Len_Trim: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

STRING: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}f90@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns the index of the last non-blank character in STRING.  @{b}LNBLNK@{ub}
and @{b}LEN_TRIM@{ub} are equivalent.

@endnode

@node "LGe Intrinsic" "g77.guide/LGe Intrinsic"
@next "LGt Intrinsic"
@prev "Len_Trim Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

LGe Intrinsic
.............

     LGe(STRING_A, STRING_B)

LGe: @{b}LOGICAL(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

STRING_A: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

STRING_B: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Returns @{b}.TRUE.@{ub} if @{b}STRING_A.GE.STRING_B@{ub}, @{b}.FALSE.@{ub} otherwise.  STRING_A
and STRING_B are interpreted as containing ASCII character codes.  If
either value contains a character not in the ASCII character set, the
result is processor dependent.

   If the STRING_A and STRING_B are not the same length, the shorter is
compared as if spaces were appended to it to form a value that has the
same length as the longer.

   The lexical comparison intrinsics @{b}LGe@{ub}, @{b}LGt@{ub}, @{b}LLe@{ub}, and @{b}LLt@{ub} differ from
the corresponding intrinsic operators @{b}.GE.@{ub}, @{b}.GT.@{ub}, @{b}.LE.@{ub}, @{b}.LT.@{ub}.  Because
the ASCII collating sequence is assumed, the following expressions
always return @{b}.TRUE.@{ub}:

     LGE ('0', ' ')
     LGE ('A', '0')
     LGE ('a', 'A')

   The following related expressions do @{i}not@{ui} always return @{b}.TRUE.@{ub}, as
they are not necessarily evaluated assuming the arguments use ASCII
encoding:

     '0' .GE. ' '
     'A' .GE. '0'
     'a' .GE. 'A'

   The same difference exists between @{b}LGt@{ub} and @{b}.GT.@{ub}; between @{b}LLe@{ub} and
@{b}.LE.@{ub}; and between @{b}LLt@{ub} and @{b}.LT.@{ub}.

@endnode

@node "LGt Intrinsic" "g77.guide/LGt Intrinsic"
@next "Link Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@prev "LGe Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

LGt Intrinsic
.............

     LGt(STRING_A, STRING_B)

LGt: @{b}LOGICAL(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

STRING_A: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

STRING_B: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Returns @{b}.TRUE.@{ub} if @{b}STRING_A.GT.STRING_B@{ub}, @{b}.FALSE.@{ub} otherwise.  STRING_A
and STRING_B are interpreted as containing ASCII character codes.  If
either value contains a character not in the ASCII character set, the
result is processor dependent.

   If the STRING_A and STRING_B are not the same length, the shorter is
compared as if spaces were appended to it to form a value that has the
same length as the longer.

   See @{"LGe Intrinsic" link "LGe Intrinsic"}, for information on the distinction between the
@{b}LGT@{ub} intrinsic and the @{b}.GT.@{ub} operator.

@endnode

@node "Link Intrinsic (subroutine)" "g77.guide/Link Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@next "LLe Intrinsic"
@prev "LGt Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Link Intrinsic (subroutine)
...........................

     CALL Link(PATH1, PATH2, STATUS)

PATH1: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

PATH2: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

STATUS: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; OPTIONAL; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Makes a (hard) link from file PATH1 to PATH2.  A null character
(@{b}CHAR(0)@{ub}) marks the end of the names in PATH1 and PATH2--otherwise,
trailing blanks in PATH1 and PATH2 are ignored.  If the STATUS argument
is supplied, it contains 0 on success or a nonzero error code upon
return.  See @{b}link(2)@{ub}.

   Some non-GNU implementations of Fortran provide this intrinsic as
only a function, not as a subroutine, or do not support the (optional)
STATUS argument.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"Link Intrinsic (function)" link "Link Intrinsic (function)"}.

@endnode

@node "LLe Intrinsic" "g77.guide/LLe Intrinsic"
@next "LLt Intrinsic"
@prev "Link Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

LLe Intrinsic
.............

     LLe(STRING_A, STRING_B)

LLe: @{b}LOGICAL(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

STRING_A: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

STRING_B: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Returns @{b}.TRUE.@{ub} if @{b}STRING_A.LE.STRING_B@{ub}, @{b}.FALSE.@{ub} otherwise.  STRING_A
and STRING_B are interpreted as containing ASCII character codes.  If
either value contains a character not in the ASCII character set, the
result is processor dependent.

   If the STRING_A and STRING_B are not the same length, the shorter is
compared as if spaces were appended to it to form a value that has the
same length as the longer.

   See @{"LGe Intrinsic" link "LGe Intrinsic"}, for information on the distinction between the
@{b}LLE@{ub} intrinsic and the @{b}.LE.@{ub} operator.

@endnode

@node "LLt Intrinsic" "g77.guide/LLt Intrinsic"
@next "LnBlnk Intrinsic"
@prev "LLe Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

LLt Intrinsic
.............

     LLt(STRING_A, STRING_B)

LLt: @{b}LOGICAL(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

STRING_A: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

STRING_B: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Returns @{b}.TRUE.@{ub} if @{b}STRING_A.LT.STRING_B@{ub}, @{b}.FALSE.@{ub} otherwise.  STRING_A
and STRING_B are interpreted as containing ASCII character codes.  If
either value contains a character not in the ASCII character set, the
result is processor dependent.

   If the STRING_A and STRING_B are not the same length, the shorter is
compared as if spaces were appended to it to form a value that has the
same length as the longer.

   See @{"LGe Intrinsic" link "LGe Intrinsic"}, for information on the distinction between the
@{b}LLT@{ub} intrinsic and the @{b}.LT.@{ub} operator.

@endnode

@node "LnBlnk Intrinsic" "g77.guide/LnBlnk Intrinsic"
@next "Loc Intrinsic"
@prev "LLt Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

LnBlnk Intrinsic
................

     LnBlnk(STRING)

LnBlnk: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

STRING: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns the index of the last non-blank character in STRING.  @{b}LNBLNK@{ub}
and @{b}LEN_TRIM@{ub} are equivalent.

@endnode

@node "Loc Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Loc Intrinsic"
@next "Log Intrinsic"
@prev "LnBlnk Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Loc Intrinsic
.............

     Loc(ENTITY)

Loc: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=7)@{ub} function.

ENTITY: Any type; cannot be a constant or expression.

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   The @{b}LOC()@{ub} intrinsic works the same way as the @{b}%LOC()@{ub} construct.  See
@{"The `%LOC()' Construct" link "%LOC()"}, for more information.

@endnode

@node "Log Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Log Intrinsic"
@next "Log10 Intrinsic"
@prev "Loc Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Log Intrinsic
.............

     Log(X)

Log: @{b}REAL@{ub} or @{b}COMPLEX@{ub} function, the exact type being that of argument X.

X: @{b}REAL@{ub} or @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Returns the natural logarithm of X, which must be greater than zero
or, if type @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}, must not be zero.

   See @{"Exp Intrinsic" link "Exp Intrinsic"}, for the inverse of this function.

   See @{"Log10 Intrinsic" link "Log10 Intrinsic"}, for the `common' (base-10) logarithm function.

@endnode

@node "Log10 Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Log10 Intrinsic"
@next "Logical Intrinsic"
@prev "Log Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Log10 Intrinsic
...............

     Log10(X)

Log10: @{b}REAL@{ub} function, the @{b}KIND=@{ub} value of the type being that of
argument X.

X: @{b}REAL@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Returns the common logarithm (base 10) of X, which must be greater
than zero.

   The inverse of this function is @{b}10. ** LOG10(X)@{ub}.

   See @{"Log Intrinsic" link "Log Intrinsic"}, for the natural logarithm function.

@endnode

@node "Logical Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Logical Intrinsic"
@next "Long Intrinsic"
@prev "Log10 Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Logical Intrinsic
.................

This intrinsic is not yet implemented.  The name is, however, reserved
as an intrinsic.  Use @{b}EXTERNAL Logical@{ub} to use this name for an external
procedure.

@endnode

@node "Long Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Long Intrinsic"
@next "LShift Intrinsic"
@prev "Logical Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Long Intrinsic
..............

     Long(A)

Long: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

A: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=6)@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Archaic form of @{b}INT()@{ub} that is specific to one type for A.  See
@{"Int Intrinsic" link "Int Intrinsic"}.

   The precise meaning of this intrinsic might change in a future
version of the GNU Fortran language, as more is learned about how it is
used.

@endnode

@node "LShift Intrinsic" "g77.guide/LShift Intrinsic"
@next "LStat Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@prev "Long Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

LShift Intrinsic
................

     LShift(I, SHIFT)

LShift: @{b}INTEGER@{ub} function, the @{b}KIND=@{ub} value of the type being that of
argument I.

I: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

SHIFT: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}f2c@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns I shifted to the left SHIFT bits.

   Although similar to the expression @{b}I*(2**SHIFT)@{ub}, there are important
differences.  For example, the sign of the result is not necessarily
the same as the sign of I.

   Currently this intrinsic is defined assuming the underlying
representation of I is as a two's-complement integer.  It is unclear at
this point whether that definition will apply when a different
representation is involved.

   See @{"LShift Intrinsic" link "LShift Intrinsic"}, for the inverse of this function.

   See @{"IShft Intrinsic" link "IShft Intrinsic"}, for information on a more widely available
left-shifting intrinsic that is also more precisely defined.

@endnode

@node "LStat Intrinsic (subroutine)" "g77.guide/LStat Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@next "LStat Intrinsic (function)"
@prev "LShift Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

LStat Intrinsic (subroutine)
............................

     CALL LStat(FILE, SARRAY, STATUS)

FILE: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

SARRAY: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; DIMENSION(13); INTENT(OUT).

STATUS: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; OPTIONAL; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Obtains data about the given file FILE and places them in the array
SARRAY.  A null character (@{b}CHAR(0)@{ub}) marks the end of the name in
FILE--otherwise, trailing blanks in FILE are ignored.  If FILE is a
symbolic link it returns data on the link itself, so the routine is
available only on systems that support symbolic links.  The values in
this array are extracted from the @{b}stat@{ub} structure as returned by
@{b}fstat(2)@{ub} q.v., as follows:

  1. Device ID

  2. Inode number

  3. File mode

  4. Number of links

  5. Owner's uid

  6. Owner's gid

  7. ID of device containing directory entry for file (0 if not
     available)

  8. File size (bytes)

  9. Last access time

 10. Last modification time

 11. Last file status change time

 12. Preferred I/O block size (-1 if not available)

 13. Number of blocks allocated (-1 if not available)

   Not all these elements are relevant on all systems.  If an element
is not relevant, it is returned as 0.

   If the STATUS argument is supplied, it contains 0 on success or a
nonzero error code upon return (@{b}ENOSYS@{ub} if the system does not provide
@{b}lstat(2)@{ub}).

   Some non-GNU implementations of Fortran provide this intrinsic as
only a function, not as a subroutine, or do not support the (optional)
STATUS argument.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"LStat Intrinsic (function)" link "LStat Intrinsic (function)"}.

@endnode

@node "LStat Intrinsic (function)" "g77.guide/LStat Intrinsic (function)"
@next "LTime Intrinsic"
@prev "LStat Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

LStat Intrinsic (function)
..........................

     LStat(FILE, SARRAY)

LStat: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

FILE: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

SARRAY: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; DIMENSION(13); INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Obtains data about the given file FILE and places them in the array
SARRAY.  A null character (@{b}CHAR(0)@{ub}) marks the end of the name in
FILE--otherwise, trailing blanks in FILE are ignored.  If FILE is a
symbolic link it returns data on the link itself, so the routine is
available only on systems that support symbolic links.  The values in
this array are extracted from the @{b}stat@{ub} structure as returned by
@{b}fstat(2)@{ub} q.v., as follows:

  1. Device ID

  2. Inode number

  3. File mode

  4. Number of links

  5. Owner's uid

  6. Owner's gid

  7. ID of device containing directory entry for file (0 if not
     available)

  8. File size (bytes)

  9. Last access time

 10. Last modification time

 11. Last file status change time

 12. Preferred I/O block size (-1 if not available)

 13. Number of blocks allocated (-1 if not available)

   Not all these elements are relevant on all systems.  If an element
is not relevant, it is returned as 0.

   Returns 0 on success or a nonzero error code (@{b}ENOSYS@{ub} if the system
does not provide @{b}lstat(2)@{ub}).

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"LStat Intrinsic (subroutine)" link "LStat Intrinsic (subroutine)"}.

@endnode

@node "LTime Intrinsic" "g77.guide/LTime Intrinsic"
@next "MatMul Intrinsic"
@prev "LStat Intrinsic (function)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

LTime Intrinsic
...............

     CALL LTime(STIME, TARRAY)

STIME: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

TARRAY: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; DIMENSION(9); INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Given a system time value STIME, fills TARRAY with values extracted
from it appropriate to the GMT time zone using @{b}localtime(3)@{ub}.

   The array elements are as follows:

  1. Seconds after the minute, range 0-59 or 0-61 to allow for leap
     seconds

  2. Minutes after the hour, range 0-59

  3. Hours past midnight, range 0-23

  4. Day of month, range 0-31

  5. Number of months since January, range 0-12

  6. Years since 1900

  7. Number of days since Sunday, range 0-6

  8. Days since January 1

  9. Daylight savings indicator: positive if daylight savings is in
     effect, zero if not, and negative if the information isn't
     available.

@endnode

@node "MatMul Intrinsic" "g77.guide/MatMul Intrinsic"
@next "Max Intrinsic"
@prev "LTime Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

MatMul Intrinsic
................

This intrinsic is not yet implemented.  The name is, however, reserved
as an intrinsic.  Use @{b}EXTERNAL MatMul@{ub} to use this name for an external
procedure.

@endnode

@node "Max Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Max Intrinsic"
@next "Max0 Intrinsic"
@prev "MatMul Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Max Intrinsic
.............

     Max(A-1, A-2, ..., A-n)

Max: @{b}INTEGER@{ub} or @{b}REAL@{ub} function, the exact type being the result of
cross-promoting the types of all the arguments.

A: @{b}INTEGER@{ub} or @{b}REAL@{ub}; at least two such arguments must be provided;
scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Returns the argument with the largest value.

   See @{"Min Intrinsic" link "Min Intrinsic"}, for the opposite function.

@endnode

@node "Max0 Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Max0 Intrinsic"
@next "Max1 Intrinsic"
@prev "Max Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Max0 Intrinsic
..............

     Max0(A-1, A-2, ..., A-n)

Max0: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

A: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; at least two such arguments must be provided;
scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Archaic form of @{b}MAX()@{ub} that is specific to one type for A.  See
@{"Max Intrinsic" link "Max Intrinsic"}.

@endnode

@node "Max1 Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Max1 Intrinsic"
@next "MaxExponent Intrinsic"
@prev "Max0 Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Max1 Intrinsic
..............

     Max1(A-1, A-2, ..., A-n)

Max1: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

A: @{b}REAL(KIND=1)@{ub}; at least two such arguments must be provided; scalar;
INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Archaic form of @{b}MAX()@{ub} that is specific to one type for A and a
different return type.  See @{"Max Intrinsic" link "Max Intrinsic"}.

@endnode

