@node "Real Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Real Intrinsic"
@next "RealPart Intrinsic"
@prev "Range Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Real Intrinsic
..............

     Real(A)

Real: @{b}REAL@{ub} function.  The exact type is @{b}REAL(KIND=1)@{ub} when argument A is
any type other than @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}, or when it is @{b}COMPLEX(KIND=1)@{ub}.  When A is
any @{b}COMPLEX@{ub} type other than @{b}COMPLEX(KIND=1)@{ub}, this intrinsic is valid
only when used as the argument to @{b}REAL()@{ub}, as explained below.

A: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}, @{b}REAL@{ub}, or @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Converts A to @{b}REAL(KIND=1)@{ub}.

   Use of @{b}REAL()@{ub} with a @{b}COMPLEX@{ub} argument (other than @{b}COMPLEX(KIND=1)@{ub})
is restricted to the following case:

     REAL(REAL(A))

This expression converts the real part of A to @{b}REAL(KIND=1)@{ub}.

   See @{"RealPart Intrinsic" link "RealPart Intrinsic"}, for information on a GNU Fortran intrinsic
that extracts the real part of an arbitrary @{b}COMPLEX@{ub} value.

   See @{"REAL() and AIMAG() of Complex" link "REAL() and AIMAG() of Complex"}, for more information.

@endnode

@node "RealPart Intrinsic" "g77.guide/RealPart Intrinsic"
@next "Rename Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@prev "Real Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

RealPart Intrinsic
..................

     RealPart(Z)

RealPart: @{b}REAL@{ub} function, the @{b}KIND=@{ub} value of the type being that of
argument Z.

Z: @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}gnu@{ub}.

Description:

   The real part of Z is returned, without conversion.

   @{i}Note:@{ui} The way to do this in standard Fortran 90 is @{b}REAL(Z)@{ub}.
However, when, for example, Z is @{b}COMPLEX(KIND=2)@{ub}, @{b}REAL(Z)@{ub} means
something different for some compilers that are not true Fortran 90
compilers but offer some extensions standardized by Fortran 90 (such as
the @{b}DOUBLE COMPLEX@{ub} type, also known as @{b}COMPLEX(KIND=2)@{ub}).

   The advantage of @{b}REALPART()@{ub} is that, while not necessarily more or
less portable than @{b}REAL()@{ub}, it is more likely to cause a compiler that
doesn't support it to produce a diagnostic than generate incorrect code.

   See @{"REAL() and AIMAG() of Complex" link "REAL() and AIMAG() of Complex"}, for more information.

@endnode

@node "Rename Intrinsic (subroutine)" "g77.guide/Rename Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@next "Repeat Intrinsic"
@prev "RealPart Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Rename Intrinsic (subroutine)
.............................

     CALL Rename(PATH1, PATH2, STATUS)

PATH1: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

PATH2: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

STATUS: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; OPTIONAL; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Renames the file PATH1 to PATH2.  A null character (@{b}CHAR(0)@{ub}) marks
the end of the names in PATH1 and PATH2--otherwise, trailing blanks in
PATH1 and PATH2 are ignored.  See @{b}rename(2)@{ub}.  If the STATUS argument is
supplied, it contains 0 on success or a nonzero error code upon return.

   Some non-GNU implementations of Fortran provide this intrinsic as
only a function, not as a subroutine, or do not support the (optional)
STATUS argument.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"Rename Intrinsic (function)" link "Rename Intrinsic (function)"}.

@endnode

