@node "Second Intrinsic (function)" "g77.guide/Second Intrinsic (function)"
@next "Second Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@prev "Scan Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Second Intrinsic (function)
...........................

     Second()

Second: @{b}REAL(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns the process's runtime in seconds--the same value as the UNIX
function @{b}etime@{ub} returns.

   On some systems, the underlying timings are represented using types
with sufficiently small limits that overflows (wraparounds) are
possible, such as 32-bit types.  Therefore, the values returned by this
intrinsic might be, or become, negative, or numerically less than
previous values, during a single run of the compiled program.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"Second Intrinsic (subroutine)" link "Second Intrinsic (subroutine)"}.

@endnode

@node "Second Intrinsic (subroutine)" "g77.guide/Second Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@next "Selected_Int_Kind Intrinsic"
@prev "Second Intrinsic (function)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Second Intrinsic (subroutine)
.............................

     CALL Second(SECONDS)

SECONDS: @{b}REAL@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns the process's runtime in seconds in SECONDS--the same value
as the UNIX function @{b}etime@{ub} returns.

   On some systems, the underlying timings are represented using types
with sufficiently small limits that overflows (wraparounds) are
possible, such as 32-bit types.  Therefore, the values returned by this
intrinsic might be, or become, negative, or numerically less than
previous values, during a single run of the compiled program.

   This routine is known from Cray Fortran.  See @{"CPU_Time Intrinsic" link "CPU_Time Intrinsic"},
for a standard equivalent.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"Second Intrinsic (function)" link "Second Intrinsic (function)"}.

@endnode

