@node "Short Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Short Intrinsic"
@next "Sign Intrinsic"
@prev "Shape Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Short Intrinsic
...............

     Short(A)

Short: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=6)@{ub} function.

A: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns A with the fractional portion of its magnitude truncated and
its sign preserved, converted to type @{b}INTEGER(KIND=6)@{ub}.

   If A is type @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}, its real part is truncated and converted, and
its imaginary part is disregarded.

   See @{"Int Intrinsic" link "Int Intrinsic"}.

   The precise meaning of this intrinsic might change in a future
version of the GNU Fortran language, as more is learned about how it is
used.

@endnode

@node "Sign Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Sign Intrinsic"
@next "Signal Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@prev "Short Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Sign Intrinsic
..............

     Sign(A, B)

Sign: @{b}INTEGER@{ub} or @{b}REAL@{ub} function, the exact type being the result of
cross-promoting the types of all the arguments.

A: @{b}INTEGER@{ub} or @{b}REAL@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

B: @{b}INTEGER@{ub} or @{b}REAL@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Returns @{b}ABS(A)*S@{ub}, where S is +1 if @{b}B.GE.0@{ub}, -1 otherwise.

   See @{"Abs Intrinsic" link "Abs Intrinsic"}, for the function that returns the magnitude of a
value.

@endnode

@node "Signal Intrinsic (subroutine)" "g77.guide/Signal Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@next "Sin Intrinsic"
@prev "Sign Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Signal Intrinsic (subroutine)
.............................

     CALL Signal(NUMBER, HANDLER, STATUS)

NUMBER: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

HANDLER: Signal handler (@{b}INTEGER FUNCTION@{ub} or @{b}SUBROUTINE@{ub}) or
dummy/global @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} scalar.

STATUS: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=7)@{ub}; OPTIONAL; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   If HANDLER is a an @{b}EXTERNAL@{ub} routine, arranges for it to be invoked
with a single integer argument (of system-dependent length) when signal
NUMBER occurs.  If HANDLER is an integer, it can be used to turn off
handling of signal NUMBER or revert to its default action.  See
@{b}signal(2)@{ub}.

   Note that HANDLER will be called using C conventions, so the value
of its argument in Fortran terms Fortran terms is obtained by applying
@{b}%LOC()@{ub} (or @{b}LOC()@{ub}) to it.

   The value returned by @{b}signal(2)@{ub} is written to STATUS, if that
argument is supplied.  Otherwise the return value is ignored.

   Some non-GNU implementations of Fortran provide this intrinsic as
only a function, not as a subroutine, or do not support the (optional)
STATUS argument.

   @{i}Warning:@{ui} Use of the @{b}libf2c@{ub} run-time library function @{b}signal_@{ub} directly
(such as via @{b}EXTERNAL SIGNAL@{ub}) requires use of the @{b}%VAL()@{ub} construct to
pass an @{b}INTEGER@{ub} value (such as @{b}SIG_IGN@{ub} or @{b}SIG_DFL@{ub}) for the HANDLER
argument.

   However, while @{b}CALL SIGNAL(SIGNUM, %VAL(SIG_IGN))@{ub} works when @{b}SIGNAL@{ub}
is treated as an external procedure (and resolves, at link time, to
@{b}libf2c@{ub}'s @{b}signal_@{ub} routine), this construct is not valid when @{b}SIGNAL@{ub} is
recognized as the intrinsic of that name.

   Therefore, for maximum portability and reliability, code such
references to the @{b}SIGNAL@{ub} facility as follows:

     INTRINSIC SIGNAL
     ...
     CALL SIGNAL(SIGNUM, SIG_IGN)

   @{b}g77@{ub} will compile such a call correctly, while other compilers will
generally either do so as well or reject the @{b}INTRINSIC SIGNAL@{ub} statement
via a diagnostic, allowing you to take appropriate action.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"Signal Intrinsic (function)" link "Signal Intrinsic (function)"}.

@endnode

@node "Sin Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Sin Intrinsic"
@next "SinH Intrinsic"
@prev "Signal Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Sin Intrinsic
.............

     Sin(X)

Sin: @{b}REAL@{ub} or @{b}COMPLEX@{ub} function, the exact type being that of argument X.

X: @{b}REAL@{ub} or @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Returns the sine of X, an angle measured in radians.

   See @{"ASin Intrinsic" link "ASin Intrinsic"}, for the inverse of this function.

@endnode

@node "SinH Intrinsic" "g77.guide/SinH Intrinsic"
@next "Sleep Intrinsic"
@prev "Sin Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

SinH Intrinsic
..............

     SinH(X)

SinH: @{b}REAL@{ub} function, the @{b}KIND=@{ub} value of the type being that of argument
X.

X: @{b}REAL@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Returns the hyperbolic sine of X.

@endnode

@node "Sleep Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Sleep Intrinsic"
@next "Sngl Intrinsic"
@prev "SinH Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Sleep Intrinsic
...............

     CALL Sleep(SECONDS)

SECONDS: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Causes the process to pause for SECONDS seconds.  See @{b}sleep(2)@{ub}.

@endnode

