@node "SqRt Intrinsic" "g77.guide/SqRt Intrinsic"
@next "SRand Intrinsic"
@prev "Spread Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

SqRt Intrinsic
..............

     SqRt(X)

SqRt: @{b}REAL@{ub} or @{b}COMPLEX@{ub} function, the exact type being that of argument X.

X: @{b}REAL@{ub} or @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Returns the square root of X, which must not be negative.

   To calculate and represent the square root of a negative number,
complex arithmetic must be used.  For example, @{b}SQRT(COMPLEX(X))@{ub}.

   The inverse of this function is @{b}SQRT(X) * SQRT(X)@{ub}.

@endnode

@node "SRand Intrinsic" "g77.guide/SRand Intrinsic"
@next "Stat Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@prev "SqRt Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

SRand Intrinsic
...............

     CALL SRand(SEED)

SEED: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Reinitializes the generator with the seed in SEED.  See
@{"IRand Intrinsic" link "IRand Intrinsic"}.  See @{"Rand Intrinsic" link "Rand Intrinsic"}.

@endnode

@node "Stat Intrinsic (subroutine)" "g77.guide/Stat Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@next "Stat Intrinsic (function)"
@prev "SRand Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Stat Intrinsic (subroutine)
...........................

     CALL Stat(FILE, SARRAY, STATUS)

FILE: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

SARRAY: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; DIMENSION(13); INTENT(OUT).

STATUS: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; OPTIONAL; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Obtains data about the given file FILE and places them in the array
SARRAY.  A null character (@{b}CHAR(0)@{ub}) marks the end of the name in
FILE--otherwise, trailing blanks in FILE are ignored.  The values in
this array are extracted from the @{b}stat@{ub} structure as returned by
@{b}fstat(2)@{ub} q.v., as follows:

  1. Device ID

  2. Inode number

  3. File mode

  4. Number of links

  5. Owner's uid

  6. Owner's gid

  7. ID of device containing directory entry for file (0 if not
     available)

  8. File size (bytes)

  9. Last access time

 10. Last modification time

 11. Last file status change time

 12. Preferred I/O block size (-1 if not available)

 13. Number of blocks allocated (-1 if not available)

   Not all these elements are relevant on all systems.  If an element
is not relevant, it is returned as 0.

   If the STATUS argument is supplied, it contains 0 on success or a
nonzero error code upon return.

   Some non-GNU implementations of Fortran provide this intrinsic as
only a function, not as a subroutine, or do not support the (optional)
STATUS argument.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"Stat Intrinsic (function)" link "Stat Intrinsic (function)"}.

@endnode

@node "Stat Intrinsic (function)" "g77.guide/Stat Intrinsic (function)"
@next "Sum Intrinsic"
@prev "Stat Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Stat Intrinsic (function)
.........................

     Stat(FILE, SARRAY)

Stat: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

FILE: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

SARRAY: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; DIMENSION(13); INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Obtains data about the given file FILE and places them in the array
SARRAY.  A null character (@{b}CHAR(0)@{ub}) marks the end of the name in
FILE--otherwise, trailing blanks in FILE are ignored.  The values in
this array are extracted from the @{b}stat@{ub} structure as returned by
@{b}fstat(2)@{ub} q.v., as follows:

  1. Device ID

  2. Inode number

  3. File mode

  4. Number of links

  5. Owner's uid

  6. Owner's gid

  7. ID of device containing directory entry for file (0 if not
     available)

  8. File size (bytes)

  9. Last access time

 10. Last modification time

 11. Last file status change time

 12. Preferred I/O block size (-1 if not available)

 13. Number of blocks allocated (-1 if not available)

   Not all these elements are relevant on all systems.  If an element
is not relevant, it is returned as 0.

   Returns 0 on success or a nonzero error code.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"Stat Intrinsic (subroutine)" link "Stat Intrinsic (subroutine)"}.

@endnode

@node "Sum Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Sum Intrinsic"
@next "SymLnk Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@prev "Stat Intrinsic (function)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Sum Intrinsic
.............

This intrinsic is not yet implemented.  The name is, however, reserved
as an intrinsic.  Use @{b}EXTERNAL Sum@{ub} to use this name for an external
