@endnode

@node "SymLnk Intrinsic (subroutine)" "g77.guide/SymLnk Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@next "System Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@prev "Sum Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

SymLnk Intrinsic (subroutine)
.............................

     CALL SymLnk(PATH1, PATH2, STATUS)

PATH1: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

PATH2: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

STATUS: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; OPTIONAL; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Makes a symbolic link from file PATH1 to PATH2.  A null character
(@{b}CHAR(0)@{ub}) marks the end of the names in PATH1 and PATH2--otherwise,
trailing blanks in PATH1 and PATH2 are ignored.  If the STATUS argument
is supplied, it contains 0 on success or a nonzero error code upon
return (@{b}ENOSYS@{ub} if the system does not provide @{b}symlink(2)@{ub}).

   Some non-GNU implementations of Fortran provide this intrinsic as
only a function, not as a subroutine, or do not support the (optional)
STATUS argument.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"SymLnk Intrinsic (function)" link "SymLnk Intrinsic (function)"}.

@endnode

@node "System Intrinsic (subroutine)" "g77.guide/System Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@next "System_Clock Intrinsic"
@prev "SymLnk Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

System Intrinsic (subroutine)
.............................

     CALL System(COMMAND, STATUS)

COMMAND: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

STATUS: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; OPTIONAL; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Passes the command COMMAND to a shell (see @{b}system(3)@{ub}).  If argument
STATUS is present, it contains the value returned by @{b}system(3)@{ub},
presumably 0 if the shell command succeeded.  Note that which shell is
used to invoke the command is system-dependent and
environment-dependent.

   Some non-GNU implementations of Fortran provide this intrinsic as
only a function, not as a subroutine, or do not support the (optional)
STATUS argument.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"System Intrinsic (function)" link "System Intrinsic (function)"}.

@endnode

@node "System_Clock Intrinsic" "g77.guide/System_Clock Intrinsic"
@next "Tan Intrinsic"
@prev "System Intrinsic (subroutine)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

System_Clock Intrinsic
......................

     CALL System_Clock(COUNT, RATE, MAX)

COUNT: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

RATE: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; OPTIONAL; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

MAX: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}; OPTIONAL; scalar; INTENT(OUT).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}f90@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns in COUNT the current value of the system clock; this is the
value returned by the UNIX function @{b}times(2)@{ub} in this implementation, but
isn't in general.  RATE is the number of clock ticks per second and MAX
is the maximum value this can take, which isn't very useful in this
implementation since it's just the maximum C @{b}unsigned int@{ub} value.

   On some systems, the underlying timings are represented using types
with sufficiently small limits that overflows (wraparounds) are
possible, such as 32-bit types.  Therefore, the values returned by this
intrinsic might be, or become, negative, or numerically less than
previous values, during a single run of the compiled program.

@endnode

@node "Tan Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Tan Intrinsic"
@next "TanH Intrinsic"
@prev "System_Clock Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Tan Intrinsic
.............

     Tan(X)

Tan: @{b}REAL@{ub} function, the @{b}KIND=@{ub} value of the type being that of argument
X.

X: @{b}REAL@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Returns the tangent of X, an angle measured in radians.

   See @{"ATan Intrinsic" link "ATan Intrinsic"}, for the inverse of this function.

@endnode

@node "TanH Intrinsic" "g77.guide/TanH Intrinsic"
