     TanH(X)

TanH: @{b}REAL@{ub} function, the @{b}KIND=@{ub} value of the type being that of argument
X.

X: @{b}REAL@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: (standard FORTRAN 77).

Description:

   Returns the hyperbolic tangent of X.

@endnode

@node "Time Intrinsic (UNIX)" "g77.guide/Time Intrinsic (UNIX)"
@next "Time8 Intrinsic"
@prev "TanH Intrinsic"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Time Intrinsic (UNIX)
.....................

     Time()

Time: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns the current time encoded as an integer (in the manner of the
UNIX function @{b}time(3)@{ub}).  This value is suitable for passing to @{b}CTIME@{ub},
@{b}GMTIME@{ub}, and @{b}LTIME@{ub}.

   This intrinsic is not fully portable, such as to systems with 32-bit
@{b}INTEGER@{ub} types but supporting times wider than 32 bits.  Therefore, the
values returned by this intrinsic might be, or become, negative, or
numerically less than previous values, during a single run of the
compiled program.

   See @{"Time8 Intrinsic" link "Time8 Intrinsic"}, for information on a similar intrinsic that
might be portable to more GNU Fortran implementations, though to fewer
Fortran compilers.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"Time Intrinsic (VXT)" link "Time Intrinsic (VXT)"}.

@endnode

@node "Time8 Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Time8 Intrinsic"
@next "Tiny Intrinsic"
@prev "Time Intrinsic (UNIX)"
@toc "Table of Intrinsic Functions"

Time8 Intrinsic
...............

     Time8()

Time8: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=2)@{ub} function.

Intrinsic groups: @{b}unix@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns the current time encoded as a long integer (in the manner of
the UNIX function @{b}time(3)@{ub}).  This value is suitable for passing to
@{b}CTIME@{ub}, @{b}GMTIME@{ub}, and @{b}LTIME@{ub}.

   @{i}Warning:@{ui} this intrinsic does not increase the range of the timing
values over that returned by @{b}time(3)@{ub}.  On a system with a 32-bit
@{b}time(3)@{ub}, @{b}TIME8@{ub} will return a 32-bit value, even though converted to an
@{b}INTEGER(KIND=2)@{ub} value.  That means overflows of the 32-bit value can
still occur.  Therefore, the values returned by this intrinsic might
be, or become, negative, or numerically less than previous values,
during a single run of the compiled program.

   No Fortran implementations other than GNU Fortran are known to
support this intrinsic at the time of this writing.  See
@{"Time Intrinsic (UNIX)" link "Time Intrinsic (UNIX)"}, for information on a similar intrinsic that
might be portable to more Fortran compilers, though to fewer GNU
Fortran implementations.

@endnode

