@node "DCmplx Intrinsic" "g77.guide/DCmplx Intrinsic"
@next "DConjg Intrinsic"
@prev "DbleQ Intrinsic"
@toc "Other Intrinsics"

DCmplx Intrinsic
................

     DCmplx(X, Y)

DCmplx: @{b}COMPLEX(KIND=2)@{ub} function.

X: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}, @{b}REAL@{ub}, or @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Y: @{b}INTEGER@{ub} or @{b}REAL@{ub}; OPTIONAL (must be omitted if X is @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}); scalar;
INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}f2c@{ub}, @{b}vxt@{ub}.

Description:

   If X is not type @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}, constructs a value of type @{b}COMPLEX(KIND=2)@{ub}
from the real and imaginary values specified by X and Y, respectively.
If Y is omitted, @{b}0D0@{ub} is assumed.

   If X is type @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}, converts it to type @{b}COMPLEX(KIND=2)@{ub}.

   Although this intrinsic is not standard Fortran, it is a popular
extension offered by many compilers that support @{b}DOUBLE COMPLEX@{ub}, since
it offers the easiest way to convert to @{b}DOUBLE COMPLEX@{ub} without using
Fortran 90 features (such as the @{b}KIND=@{ub} argument to the @{b}CMPLX()@{ub}
intrinsic).

   (@{b}CMPLX(0D0, 0D0)@{ub} returns a single-precision @{b}COMPLEX@{ub} result, as
required by standard FORTRAN 77.  That's why so many compilers provide
@{b}DCMPLX()@{ub}, since @{b}DCMPLX(0D0, 0D0)@{ub} returns a @{b}DOUBLE COMPLEX@{ub} result.
Still, @{b}DCMPLX()@{ub} converts even @{b}REAL*16@{ub} arguments to their @{b}REAL*8@{ub}
equivalents in most dialects of Fortran, so neither it nor @{b}CMPLX()@{ub}
allow easy construction of arbitrary-precision values without
potentially forcing a conversion involving extending or reducing
precision.  GNU Fortran provides such an intrinsic, called @{b}COMPLEX()@{ub}.)

   See @{"Complex Intrinsic" link "Complex Intrinsic"}, for information on easily constructing a
@{b}COMPLEX@{ub} value of arbitrary precision from @{b}REAL@{ub} arguments.

@endnode

