@node "DReal Intrinsic" "g77.guide/DReal Intrinsic"
@next "DSinD Intrinsic"
@prev "DImag Intrinsic"
@toc "Other Intrinsics"

DReal Intrinsic
...............

     DReal(A)

DReal: @{b}REAL(KIND=2)@{ub} function.

A: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}, @{b}REAL@{ub}, or @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}vxt@{ub}.

Description:

   Converts A to @{b}REAL(KIND=2)@{ub}.

   If A is type @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}, its real part is converted (if necessary) to
@{b}REAL(KIND=2)@{ub}, and its imaginary part is disregarded.

   Although this intrinsic is not standard Fortran, it is a popular
extension offered by many compilers that support @{b}DOUBLE COMPLEX@{ub}, since
it offers the easiest way to extract the real part of a @{b}DOUBLE COMPLEX@{ub}
value without using the Fortran 90 @{b}REAL()@{ub} intrinsic in a way that
produces a return value inconsistent with the way many FORTRAN 77
compilers handle @{b}REAL()@{ub} of a @{b}DOUBLE COMPLEX@{ub} value.

   See @{"RealPart Intrinsic" link "RealPart Intrinsic"}, for information on a GNU Fortran intrinsic
that avoids these areas of confusion.

   See @{"Dble Intrinsic" link "Dble Intrinsic"}, for information on the standard FORTRAN 77
replacement for @{b}DREAL()@{ub}.

   See @{"REAL() and AIMAG() of Complex" link "REAL() and AIMAG() of Complex"}, for more information on this
issue.

@endnode

