@node "Rename Intrinsic (function)" "g77.guide/Rename Intrinsic (function)"
@next "Secnds Intrinsic"
@prev "QTanH Intrinsic"
@toc "Other Intrinsics"

Rename Intrinsic (function)
...........................

     Rename(PATH1, PATH2)

Rename: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

PATH1: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

PATH2: @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}badu77@{ub}.

Description:

   Renames the file PATH1 to PATH2.  A null character (@{b}CHAR(0)@{ub}) marks
the end of the names in PATH1 and PATH2--otherwise, trailing blanks in
PATH1 and PATH2 are ignored.  See @{b}rename(2)@{ub}.  Returns 0 on success or a
nonzero error code.

   Due to the side effects performed by this intrinsic, the function
form is not recommended.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"Rename Intrinsic (subroutine)" link "Rename Intrinsic (subroutine)"}.

@endnode

@node "Secnds Intrinsic" "g77.guide/Secnds Intrinsic"
@next "Signal Intrinsic (function)"
@prev "Rename Intrinsic (function)"
@toc "Other Intrinsics"

Secnds Intrinsic
................

     Secnds(T)

Secnds: @{b}REAL(KIND=1)@{ub} function.

T: @{b}REAL(KIND=1)@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

Intrinsic groups: @{b}vxt@{ub}.

Description:

   Returns the local time in seconds since midnight minus the value T.

   This values returned by this intrinsic become numerically less than
previous values (they wrap around) during a single run of the compiler
program, under normal circumstances (such as running through the
midnight hour).

@endnode

@node "Signal Intrinsic (function)" "g77.guide/Signal Intrinsic (function)"
@next "SinD Intrinsic"
@prev "Secnds Intrinsic"
@toc "Other Intrinsics"

Signal Intrinsic (function)
...........................

     Signal(NUMBER, HANDLER)

Signal: @{b}INTEGER(KIND=7)@{ub} function.

NUMBER: @{b}INTEGER@{ub}; scalar; INTENT(IN).

HANDLER: Signal handler (@{b}INTEGER FUNCTION@{ub} or @{b}SUBROUTINE@{ub}) or
dummy/global @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub} scalar.

Intrinsic groups: @{b}badu77@{ub}.

Description:

   If HANDLER is a an @{b}EXTERNAL@{ub} routine, arranges for it to be invoked
with a single integer argument (of system-dependent length) when signal
NUMBER occurs.  If HANDLER is an integer, it can be used to turn off
handling of signal NUMBER or revert to its default action.  See
@{b}signal(2)@{ub}.

   Note that HANDLER will be called using C conventions, so the value
of its argument in Fortran terms is obtained by applying @{b}%LOC()@{ub} (or
@{b}LOC()@{ub}) to it.

   The value returned by @{b}signal(2)@{ub} is returned.

   Due to the side effects performed by this intrinsic, the function
form is not recommended.

   @{i}Warning:@{ui} If the returned value is stored in an @{b}INTEGER(KIND=1)@{ub}
(default @{b}INTEGER@{ub}) argument, truncation of the original return value
occurs on some systems (such as Alphas, which have 64-bit pointers but
32-bit default integers), with no warning issued by @{b}g77@{ub} under normal
circumstances.

   Therefore, the following code fragment might silently fail on some
systems:

     INTEGER RTN
     EXTERNAL MYHNDL
     RTN = SIGNAL(SIGNUM, MYHNDL)
     ...
     ! Restore original handler:
     RTN = SIGNAL(SIGNUM, RTN)

   The reason for the failure is that @{b}RTN@{ub} might not hold all the
information on the original handler for the signal, thus restoring an
invalid handler.  This bug could manifest itself as a spurious run-time
failure at an arbitrary point later during the program's execution, for
example.

   @{i}Warning:@{ui} Use of the @{b}libf2c@{ub} run-time library function @{b}signal_@{ub} directly
(such as via @{b}EXTERNAL SIGNAL@{ub}) requires use of the @{b}%VAL()@{ub} construct to
pass an @{b}INTEGER@{ub} value (such as @{b}SIG_IGN@{ub} or @{b}SIG_DFL@{ub}) for the HANDLER
argument.

   However, while @{b}RTN = SIGNAL(SIGNUM, %VAL(SIG_IGN))@{ub} works when @{b}SIGNAL@{ub}
is treated as an external procedure (and resolves, at link time, to
@{b}libf2c@{ub}'s @{b}signal_@{ub} routine), this construct is not valid when @{b}SIGNAL@{ub} is
recognized as the intrinsic of that name.

   Therefore, for maximum portability and reliability, code such
references to the @{b}SIGNAL@{ub} facility as follows:

     INTRINSIC SIGNAL
     ...
     RTN = SIGNAL(SIGNUM, SIG_IGN)

   @{b}g77@{ub} will compile such a call correctly, while other compilers will
generally either do so as well or reject the @{b}INTRINSIC SIGNAL@{ub} statement
via a diagnostic, allowing you to take appropriate action.

   For information on other intrinsics with the same name: See
@{"Signal Intrinsic (subroutine)" link "Signal Intrinsic (subroutine)"}.

@endnode

