@node "Better Source Model" "g77.guide/Better Source Model"
@next "Fortran 90 Support"
@toc "Missing Features"

Better Source Model
-------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} needs to provide, as the default source-line model, a "pure visual"
mode, where the interpretation of a source program in this mode can be
accurately determined by a user looking at a traditionally displayed
rendition of the program (assuming the user knows whether the program
is fixed or free form).

   The design should assume the user cannot tell tabs from spaces and
cannot see trailing spaces on lines, but has canonical tab stops and,
for fixed-form source, has the ability to always know exactly where
column 72 is (since the Fortran standard itself requires this for
fixed-form source).

   This would change the default treatment of fixed-form source to not
treat lines with tabs as if they were infinitely long--instead, they
would end at column 72 just as if the tabs were replaced by spaces in
the canonical way.

   As part of this, provide common alternate models (Digital, @{b}f2c@{ub}, and
so on) via command-line options.  This includes allowing arbitrarily
long lines for free-form source as well as fixed-form source and
providing various limits and diagnostics as appropriate.

   Also, @{b}g77@{ub} should offer, perhaps even default to, warnings when
characters beyond the last valid column are anything other than spaces.
This would mean code with "sequence numbers" in columns 73 through 80
would be rejected, and there's a lot of that kind of code around, but
one of the most frequent bugs encountered by new users is accidentally
writing fixed-form source code into and beyond column 73.  So, maybe
the users of old code would be able to more easily handle having to
specify, say, a @{b}-Wno-col73to80@{ub} option.

@endnode

@node "Fortran 90 Support" "g77.guide/Fortran 90 Support"
@next "Intrinsics in PARAMETER Statements"
@prev "Better Source Model"
@toc "Missing Features"

Fortran 90 Support
------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} does not support many of the features that distinguish Fortran 90
(and, now, Fortran 95) from ANSI FORTRAN 77.

   Some Fortran 90 features are supported, because they make sense to
offer even to die-hard users of F77.  For example, many of them codify
various ways F77 has been extended to meet users' needs during its
tenure, so @{b}g77@{ub} might as well offer them as the primary way to meet
those same needs, even if it offers compatibility with one or more of
the ways those needs were met by other F77 compilers in the industry.

   Still, many important F90 features are not supported, because no
attempt has been made to research each and every feature and assess its
viability in @{b}g77@{ub}.  In the meantime, users who need those features must
use Fortran 90 compilers anyway, and the best approach to adding some
F90 features to GNU Fortran might well be to fund a comprehensive
project to create GNU Fortran 95.

@endnode

@node "Intrinsics in PARAMETER Statements" "g77.guide/Intrinsics in PARAMETER Statements"
@next "Arbitrary Concatenation"
@prev "Fortran 90 Support"
@toc "Missing Features"

Intrinsics in @{b}PARAMETER@{ub} Statements
----------------------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} doesn't allow intrinsics in @{b}PARAMETER@{ub} statements.

   Related to this, @{b}g77@{ub} doesn't allow non-integral exponentiation in
@{b}PARAMETER@{ub} statements, such as @{b}PARAMETER (R=2**.25)@{ub}.  It is unlikely @{b}g77@{ub}
will ever support this feature, as doing it properly requires complete
emulation of a target computer's floating-point facilities when
building @{b}g77@{ub} as a cross-compiler.  But, if the @{b}gcc@{ub} back end is enhanced
to provide such a facility, @{b}g77@{ub} will likely use that facility in
implementing this feature soon afterwards.

@endnode

@node "Arbitrary Concatenation" "g77.guide/Arbitrary Concatenation"
@next "SELECT CASE on CHARACTER Type"
@prev "Intrinsics in PARAMETER Statements"
@toc "Missing Features"

Arbitrary Concatenation
-----------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} doesn't support arbitrary operands for concatenation in contexts
where run-time allocation is required.  For example:

     SUBROUTINE X(A)
     CHARACTER*(*) A
     CALL FOO(A // 'suffix')

@endnode

@node "SELECT CASE on CHARACTER Type" "g77.guide/SELECT CASE on CHARACTER Type"
@next "RECURSIVE Keyword"
@prev "Arbitrary Concatenation"
@toc "Missing Features"

@{b}SELECT CASE@{ub} on @{b}CHARACTER@{ub} Type
-----------------------------

Character-type selector/cases for @{b}SELECT CASE@{ub} currently are not
supported.

@endnode

@node "RECURSIVE Keyword" "g77.guide/RECURSIVE Keyword"
@next "Popular Non-standard Types"
@prev "SELECT CASE on CHARACTER Type"
@toc "Missing Features"

@{b}RECURSIVE@{ub} Keyword
-----------------

@{b}g77@{ub} doesn't support the @{b}RECURSIVE@{ub} keyword that F90 compilers do.  Nor
does it provide any means for compiling procedures designed to do
recursion.

   All recursive code can be rewritten to not use recursion, but the
result is not pretty.

@endnode

@node "Increasing Precision-Range" "g77.guide/Increasing Precision-Range"
@next "Enabling Debug Lines"
@prev "Support for Threads"
@toc "Missing Features"

Increasing Precision/Range
--------------------------

Some compilers, such as @{b}f2c@{ub}, have an option (@{b}-r8@{ub}, @{b}-qrealsize=8@{ub} or
similar) that provides automatic treatment of @{b}REAL@{ub} entities such that
they have twice the storage size, and a corresponding increase in the
range and precision, of what would normally be the @{b}REAL(KIND=1)@{ub}
(default @{b}REAL@{ub}) type.  (This affects @{b}COMPLEX@{ub} the same way.)

   They also typically offer another option (@{b}-i8@{ub}) to increase @{b}INTEGER@{ub}
entities so they are twice as large (with roughly twice as much range).

   (There are potential pitfalls in using these options.)

   @{b}g77@{ub} does not yet offer any option that performs these kinds of
transformations.  Part of the problem is the lack of detailed
specifications regarding exactly how these options affect the
interpretation of constants, intrinsics, and so on.

   Until @{b}g77@{ub} addresses this need, programmers could improve the
portability of their code by modifying it to not require compile-time
options to produce correct results.  Some free tools are available
which may help, specifically in Toolpack (which one would expect to be
sound) and the @{b}fortran@{ub} section of the Netlib repository.

   Use of preprocessors can provide a fairly portable means to work
around the lack of widely portable methods in the Fortran language
itself (though increasing acceptance of Fortran 90 would alleviate this
problem).

@endnode

@node "Popular Non-standard Types" "g77.guide/Popular Non-standard Types"
@next "Full Support for Compiler Types"
@prev "RECURSIVE Keyword"
@toc "Missing Features"

Popular Non-standard Types
--------------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} doesn't fully support @{b}INTEGER*2@{ub}, @{b}LOGICAL*1@{ub}, and similar.  In the
meantime, version 0.5.18 provides rudimentary support for them.

@endnode

@node "Full Support for Compiler Types" "g77.guide/Full Support for Compiler Types"
@next "Array Bounds Expressions"
@prev "Popular Non-standard Types"
@toc "Missing Features"

Full Support for Compiler Types
-------------------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} doesn't support @{b}INTEGER@{ub}, @{b}REAL@{ub}, and @{b}COMPLEX@{ub} equivalents for @{i}all@{ui}
applicable back-end-supported types (@{b}char@{ub}, @{b}short int@{ub}, @{b}int@{ub}, @{b}long int@{ub},
@{b}long long int@{ub}, and @{b}long double@{ub}).  This means providing intrinsic
support, and maybe constant support (using F90 syntax) as well, and,
for most machines will result in automatic support of @{b}INTEGER*1@{ub},
@{b}INTEGER*2@{ub}, @{b}INTEGER*8@{ub}, maybe even @{b}REAL*16@{ub}, and so on.

@endnode

@node "Array Bounds Expressions" "g77.guide/Array Bounds Expressions"
@next "POINTER Statements"
@prev "Full Support for Compiler Types"
@toc "Missing Features"

Array Bounds Expressions
------------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} doesn't support more general expressions to dimension arrays, such
as array element references, function references, etc.

   For example, @{b}g77@{ub} currently does not accept the following:

     SUBROUTINE X(M, N)
     INTEGER N(10), M(N(2), N(1))

@endnode

@node "POINTER Statements" "g77.guide/POINTER Statements"
@next "Sensible Non-standard Constructs"
@prev "Array Bounds Expressions"
@toc "Missing Features"

POINTER Statements
------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} doesn't support pointers or allocatable objects (other than
automatic arrays).  This set of features is probably considered just
behind intrinsics in @{b}PARAMETER@{ub} statements on the list of large,
important things to add to @{b}g77@{ub}.

   In the meantime, consider using the @{b}INTEGER(KIND=7)@{ub} declaration to
specify that a variable must be able to hold a pointer.  This construct
is not portable to other non-GNU compilers, but it is portable to all
machines GNU Fortran supports when @{b}g77@{ub} is used.

   See @{"Functions and Subroutines" link "Functions and Subroutines"}, for information on @{b}%VAL()@{ub}, @{b}%REF()@{ub},
and @{b}%DESCR()@{ub} constructs, which are useful for passing pointers to
procedures written in languages other than Fortran.

@endnode

@node "Sensible Non-standard Constructs" "g77.guide/Sensible Non-standard Constructs"
@next "READONLY Keyword"
@prev "POINTER Statements"
@toc "Missing Features"

Sensible Non-standard Constructs
--------------------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} rejects things other compilers accept, like @{b}INTRINSIC SQRT,SQRT@{ub}.
As time permits in the future, some of these things that are easy for
humans to read and write and unlikely to be intended to mean something
else will be accepted by @{b}g77@{ub} (though @{b}-fpedantic@{ub} should trigger warnings
about such non-standard constructs).

   Until @{b}g77@{ub} no longer gratuitously rejects sensible code, you might as
well fix your code to be more standard-conforming and portable.

   The kind of case that is important to except from the recommendation
to change your code is one where following good coding rules would
force you to write non-standard code that nevertheless has a clear
meaning.

   For example, when writing an @{b}INCLUDE@{ub} file that defines a common
block, it might be appropriate to include a @{b}SAVE@{ub} statement for the
common block (such as @{b}SAVE /CBLOCK/@{ub}), so that variables defined in the
common block retain their values even when all procedures declaring the
common block become inactive (return to their callers).

   However, putting @{b}SAVE@{ub} statements in an @{b}INCLUDE@{ub} file would prevent
otherwise standard-conforming code from also specifying the @{b}SAVE@{ub}
statement, by itself, to indicate that all local variables and arrays
are to have the @{b}SAVE@{ub} attribute.

   For this reason, @{b}g77@{ub} already has been changed to allow this
combination, because although the general problem of gratuitously
rejecting unambiguous and "safe" constructs still exists in @{b}g77@{ub}, this
particular construct was deemed useful enough that it was worth fixing
@{b}g77@{ub} for just this case.

   So, while there is no need to change your code to avoid using this
particular construct, there might be other, equally appropriate but
non-standard constructs, that you shouldn't have to stop using just
because @{b}g77@{ub} (or any other compiler) gratuitously rejects it.

   Until the general problem is solved, if you have any such construct
you believe is worthwhile using (e.g. not just an arbitrary, redundant
specification of an attribute), please submit a bug report with an
explanation, so we can consider fixing @{b}g77@{ub} just for cases like yours.

@endnode

@node "READONLY Keyword" "g77.guide/READONLY Keyword"
@next "FLUSH Statement"
@prev "Sensible Non-standard Constructs"
@toc "Missing Features"

@{b}READONLY@{ub} Keyword
----------------

Support for @{b}READONLY@{ub}, in @{b}OPEN@{ub} statements, requires @{b}libg2c@{ub} support, to
make sure that @{b}CLOSE(...,STATUS='DELETE')@{ub} does not delete a file opened
on a unit with the @{b}READONLY@{ub} keyword, and perhaps to trigger a fatal
diagnostic if a @{b}WRITE@{ub} or @{b}PRINT@{ub} to such a unit is attempted.

   @{i}Note:@{ui} It is not sufficient for @{b}g77@{ub} and @{b}libg2c@{ub} (its version of @{b}libf2c@{ub})
to assume that @{b}READONLY@{ub} does not need some kind of explicit support at
run time, due to UNIX systems not (generally) needing it.  @{b}g77@{ub} is not
just a UNIX-based compiler!

   Further, mounting of non-UNIX filesystems on UNIX systems (such as
via NFS) might require proper @{b}READONLY@{ub} support.

   (Similar issues might be involved with supporting the @{b}SHARED@{ub}
keyword.)

@endnode

@node "FLUSH Statement" "g77.guide/FLUSH Statement"
@next "Expressions in FORMAT Statements"
@prev "READONLY Keyword"
@toc "Missing Features"

@{b}FLUSH@{ub} Statement
---------------

@{b}g77@{ub} could perhaps use a @{b}FLUSH@{ub} statement that does what @{b}CALL FLUSH@{ub} does,
but that supports @{b}*@{ub} as the unit designator (same unit as for @{b}PRINT@{ub}) and
accepts @{b}ERR=@{ub} and/or @{b}IOSTAT=@{ub} specifiers.

@endnode

@node "Expressions in FORMAT Statements" "g77.guide/Expressions in FORMAT Statements"
@next "Explicit Assembler Code"
@prev "FLUSH Statement"
@toc "Missing Features"

Expressions in @{b}FORMAT@{ub} Statements
--------------------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} doesn't support @{b}FORMAT(I<J>)@{ub} and the like.  Supporting this
requires a significant redesign or replacement of @{b}libg2c@{ub}.

   However, @{b}g77@{ub} does support this construct when the expression is
constant (as of version 0.5.22).  For example:

           PARAMETER (IWIDTH = 12)
     10    FORMAT (I<IWIDTH>)

   Otherwise, at least for output (@{b}PRINT@{ub} and @{b}WRITE@{ub}), Fortran code
making use of this feature can be rewritten to avoid it by constructing
the @{b}FORMAT@{ub} string in a @{b}CHARACTER@{ub} variable or array, then using that
variable or array in place of the @{b}FORMAT@{ub} statement label to do the
original @{b}PRINT@{ub} or @{b}WRITE@{ub}.

   Many uses of this feature on input can be rewritten this way as
well, but not all can.  For example, this can be rewritten:

           READ 20, I
     20    FORMAT (I<J>)

   However, this cannot, in general, be rewritten, especially when @{b}ERR=@{ub}
and @{b}END=@{ub} constructs are employed:

           READ 30, J, I
     30    FORMAT (I<J>)

@endnode

@node "Explicit Assembler Code" "g77.guide/Explicit Assembler Code"
@next "Q Edit Descriptor"
@prev "Expressions in FORMAT Statements"
@toc "Missing Features"

Explicit Assembler Code
-----------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} needs to provide some way, a la @{b}gcc@{ub}, for @{b}g77@{ub} code to specify
explicit assembler code.

@endnode

@node "Q Edit Descriptor" "g77.guide/Q Edit Descriptor"
@next "Old-style PARAMETER Statements"
@prev "Explicit Assembler Code"
@toc "Missing Features"

Q Edit Descriptor
-----------------

The @{b}Q@{ub} edit descriptor in @{b}FORMAT@{ub}s isn't supported.  (This is meant to
get the number of characters remaining in an input record.)  Supporting
this requires a significant redesign or replacement of @{b}libg2c@{ub}.

   A workaround might be using internal I/O or the stream-based
intrinsics.  See @{"FGetC Intrinsic (subroutine)" link "FGetC Intrinsic (subroutine)"}.

@endnode

@node "Old-style PARAMETER Statements" "g77.guide/Old-style PARAMETER Statements"
@next "TYPE and ACCEPT I-O Statements"
@prev "Q Edit Descriptor"
@toc "Missing Features"

Old-style PARAMETER Statements
------------------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} doesn't accept @{b}PARAMETER I=1@{ub}.  Supporting this obsolete form of the
@{b}PARAMETER@{ub} statement would not be particularly hard, as most of the
parsing code is already in place and working.

   Until time/money is spent implementing it, you might as well fix
your code to use the standard form, @{b}PARAMETER (I=1)@{ub} (possibly needing
@{b}INTEGER I@{ub} preceding the @{b}PARAMETER@{ub} statement as well, otherwise, in the
obsolete form of @{b}PARAMETER@{ub}, the type of the variable is set from the
type of the constant being assigned to it).

@endnode

@node "TYPE and ACCEPT I-O Statements" "g77.guide/TYPE and ACCEPT I-O Statements"
@next "STRUCTURE UNION RECORD MAP"
@prev "Old-style PARAMETER Statements"
@toc "Missing Features"

@{b}TYPE@{ub} and @{b}ACCEPT@{ub} I/O Statements
------------------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} doesn't support the I/O statements @{b}TYPE@{ub} and @{b}ACCEPT@{ub}.  These are
common extensions that should be easy to support, but also are fairly
easy to work around in user code.

   Generally, any @{b}TYPE fmt,list@{ub} I/O statement can be replaced by @{b}PRINT
fmt,list@{ub}.  And, any @{b}ACCEPT fmt,list@{ub} statement can be replaced by @{b}READ
fmt,list@{ub}.

@endnode

@node "STRUCTURE UNION RECORD MAP" "g77.guide/STRUCTURE UNION RECORD MAP"
@next "OPEN CLOSE and INQUIRE Keywords"
@prev "TYPE and ACCEPT I-O Statements"
@toc "Missing Features"

@{b}STRUCTURE@{ub}, @{b}UNION@{ub}, @{b}RECORD@{ub}, @{b}MAP@{ub}
-----------------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} doesn't support @{b}STRUCTURE@{ub}, @{b}UNION@{ub}, @{b}RECORD@{ub}, @{b}MAP@{ub}.  This set of
extensions is quite a bit lower on the list of large, important things
to add to @{b}g77@{ub}, partly because it requires a great deal of work either
upgrading or replacing @{b}libg2c@{ub}.

@endnode

@node "OPEN CLOSE and INQUIRE Keywords" "g77.guide/OPEN CLOSE and INQUIRE Keywords"
@next "ENCODE and DECODE"
@prev "STRUCTURE UNION RECORD MAP"
@toc "Missing Features"

@{b}OPEN@{ub}, @{b}CLOSE@{ub}, and @{b}INQUIRE@{ub} Keywords
---------------------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} doesn't have support for keywords such as @{b}DISP='DELETE'@{ub} in the
@{b}OPEN@{ub}, @{b}CLOSE@{ub}, and @{b}INQUIRE@{ub} statements.  These extensions are easy to add
to @{b}g77@{ub} itself, but require much more work on @{b}libg2c@{ub}.

   @{b}g77@{ub} doesn't support @{b}FORM='PRINT'@{ub} or an equivalent to translate the
traditional `carriage control' characters in column 1 of output to use
backspaces, carriage returns and the like.  However programs exist to
translate them in output files (or standard output).  These are
typically called either @{b}fpr@{ub} or @{b}asa@{ub}.  You can get a version of @{b}asa@{ub} from
`ftp://sunsite.unc.edu/pub/Linux/devel/lang/fortran' for GNU systems
which will probably build easily on other systems.  Alternatively, @{b}fpr@{ub}
is in BSD distributions in various archive sites.

@endnode

@node "ENCODE and DECODE" "g77.guide/ENCODE and DECODE"
@next "AUTOMATIC Statement"
@prev "OPEN CLOSE and INQUIRE Keywords"
@toc "Missing Features"

@{b}ENCODE@{ub} and @{b}DECODE@{ub}
-----------------

@{b}g77@{ub} doesn't support @{b}ENCODE@{ub} or @{b}DECODE@{ub}.

   These statements are best replaced by READ and WRITE statements
involving internal files (CHARACTER variables and arrays).

   For example, replace a code fragment like

           INTEGER*1 LINE(80)
     ...
           DECODE (80, 9000, LINE) A, B, C
     ...
     9000  FORMAT (1X, 3(F10.5))

with:

           CHARACTER*80 LINE
     ...
           READ (UNIT=LINE, FMT=9000) A, B, C
     ...
     9000  FORMAT (1X, 3(F10.5))

   Similarly, replace a code fragment like

           INTEGER*1 LINE(80)
     ...
           ENCODE (80, 9000, LINE) A, B, C
     ...
     9000  FORMAT (1X, 'OUTPUT IS ', 3(F10.5))

with:

           CHARACTER*80 LINE
     ...
           WRITE (UNIT=LINE, FMT=9000) A, B, C
     ...
     9000  FORMAT (1X, 'OUTPUT IS ', 3(F10.5))

   It is entirely possible that @{b}ENCODE@{ub} and @{b}DECODE@{ub} will be supported by
a future version of @{b}g77@{ub}.

@endnode

@node "AUTOMATIC Statement" "g77.guide/AUTOMATIC Statement"
@next "Suppressing Space Padding"
@prev "ENCODE and DECODE"
@toc "Missing Features"

@{b}AUTOMATIC@{ub} Statement
-------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} doesn't support the @{b}AUTOMATIC@{ub} statement that @{b}f2c@{ub} does.

   @{b}AUTOMATIC@{ub} would identify a variable or array as not being @{b}SAVE@{ub}'d,
which is normally the default, but which would be especially useful for
code that, @{i}generally@{ui}, needed to be compiled with the @{b}-fno-automatic@{ub}
option.

   @{b}AUTOMATIC@{ub} also would serve as a hint to the compiler that placing
the variable or array--even a very large array-on the stack is
acceptable.

   @{b}AUTOMATIC@{ub} would not, by itself, designate the containing procedure
as recursive.

   @{b}AUTOMATIC@{ub} should work syntactically like @{b}SAVE@{ub}, in that @{b}AUTOMATIC@{ub}
with no variables listed should apply to all pertinent variables and
arrays (which would not include common blocks or their members).

   Variables and arrays denoted as @{b}AUTOMATIC@{ub} would not be permitted to
be initialized via @{b}DATA@{ub} or other specification of any initial values,
requiring explicit initialization, such as via assignment statements.

   Perhaps @{b}UNSAVE@{ub} and @{b}STATIC@{ub}, as strict semantic opposites to @{b}SAVE@{ub} and
@{b}AUTOMATIC@{ub}, should be provided as well.

@endnode

@node "Suppressing Space Padding" "g77.guide/Suppressing Space Padding"
@next "Fortran Preprocessor"
@prev "AUTOMATIC Statement"
@toc "Missing Features"

Suppressing Space Padding of Source Lines
-----------------------------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} should offer VXT-Fortran-style suppression of virtual spaces at the
end of a source line if an appropriate command-line option is specified.

   This affects cases where a character constant is continued onto the
next line in a fixed-form source file, as in the following example:

     10    PRINT *,'HOW MANY
          1 SPACES?'

@{b}g77@{ub}, and many other compilers, virtually extend the continued line
through column 72 with spaces that become part of the character
constant, but Digital Fortran normally didn't, leaving only one space
between @{b}MANY@{ub} and @{b}SPACES?@{ub} in the output of the above statement.

   Fairly recently, at least one version of Digital Fortran was
enhanced to provide the other behavior when a command-line option is
specified, apparently due to demand from readers of the USENET group
@{b}comp.lang.fortran@{ub} to offer conformance to this widespread practice in
the industry.  @{b}g77@{ub} should return the favor by offering conformance to
Digital's approach to handling the above example.

@endnode

@node "Fortran Preprocessor" "g77.guide/Fortran Preprocessor"
@next "Bit Operations on Floating-point Data"
@prev "Suppressing Space Padding"
@toc "Missing Features"

Fortran Preprocessor
--------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} should offer a preprocessor designed specifically for Fortran to
replace @{b}cpp -traditional@{ub}.  There are several out there worth
evaluating, at least.

   Such a preprocessor would recognize Hollerith constants, properly
parse comments and character constants, and so on.  It might also
recognize, process, and thus preprocess files included via the @{b}INCLUDE@{ub}
directive.

@endnode

@node "Bit Operations on Floating-point Data" "g77.guide/Bit Operations on Floating-point Data"
@next "Really Ugly Character Assignments"
@prev "Fortran Preprocessor"
@toc "Missing Features"

Bit Operations on Floating-point Data
-------------------------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} does not allow @{b}REAL@{ub} and other non-integral types for arguments to
intrinsics like @{b}And@{ub}, @{b}Or@{ub}, and @{b}Shift@{ub}.

   For example, this program is rejected by @{b}g77@{ub}, because the intrinsic
@{b}Iand@{ub} does not accept @{b}REAL@{ub} arguments:

     DATA A/7.54/, B/9.112/
     PRINT *, IAND(A, B)
     END

@endnode

@node "Really Ugly Character Assignments" "g77.guide/Really Ugly Character Assignments"
@next "POSIX Standard"
@prev "Bit Operations on Floating-point Data"
@toc "Missing Features"

Really Ugly Character Assignments
---------------------------------

An option such as @{b}-fugly-char@{ub} should be provided to allow

     REAL*8 A1
     DATA A1 / '12345678' /

   and:

     REAL*8 A1
     A1 = 'ABCDEFGH'

@endnode

@node "POSIX Standard" "g77.guide/POSIX Standard"
@next "Floating-point Exception Handling"
@prev "Really Ugly Character Assignments"
@toc "Missing Features"

@{b}POSIX@{ub} Standard
--------------

@{b}g77@{ub} should support the POSIX standard for Fortran.

@endnode

@node "Floating-point Exception Handling" "g77.guide/Floating-point Exception Handling"
@next "Nonportable Conversions"
@prev "POSIX Standard"
@toc "Missing Features"

Floating-point Exception Handling
---------------------------------

The @{b}gcc@{ub} backend and, consequently, @{b}g77@{ub}, currently provides no general
control over whether or not floating-point exceptions are trapped or
ignored.  (Ignoring them typically results in NaN values being
propagated in systems that conform to IEEE 754.)  The behavior is
normally inherited from the system-dependent startup code, though some
targets, such as the Alpha, have code generation options which change
the behavior.

   Most systems provide some C-callable mechanism to change this; this
can be invoked at startup using @{b}gcc@{ub}'s @{b}constructor@{ub} attribute.  For
example, just compiling and linking the following C code with your
program will turn on exception trapping for the "common" exceptions on
a GNU system using glibc 2.2 or newer:

     #define _GNU_SOURCE 1
     #include <fenv.h>
     static void __attribute__ ((constructor))
     trapfpe ()
     {
       /* Enable some exceptions.  At startup all exceptions are masked.  */
     
       feenableexcept (FE_INVALID|FE_DIVBYZERO|FE_OVERFLOW);
     }

   A convenient trick is to compile this something like:
     gcc -o libtrapfpe.a trapfpe.c
   and then use it by adding @{b}-trapfpe@{ub} to the @{b}g77@{ub} command line when
linking.

@endnode

@node "Nonportable Conversions" "g77.guide/Nonportable Conversions"
@next "Large Automatic Arrays"
@prev "Floating-point Exception Handling"
@toc "Missing Features"

Nonportable Conversions
-----------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} doesn't accept some particularly nonportable, silent data-type
conversions such as @{b}LOGICAL@{ub} to @{b}REAL@{ub} (as in @{b}A=.FALSE.@{ub}, where @{b}A@{ub} is type
@{b}REAL@{ub}), that other compilers might quietly accept.

   Some of these conversions are accepted by @{b}g77@{ub} when the @{b}-fugly-logint@{ub}
option is specified.  Perhaps it should accept more or all of them.

@endnode

@node "Large Automatic Arrays" "g77.guide/Large Automatic Arrays"
@next "Support for Threads"
@prev "Nonportable Conversions"
@toc "Missing Features"

Large Automatic Arrays
----------------------

Currently, automatic arrays always are allocated on the stack.  For
situations where the stack cannot be made large enough, @{b}g77@{ub} should
offer a compiler option that specifies allocation of automatic arrays
in heap storage.

@endnode

@node "Support for Threads" "g77.guide/Support for Threads"
@next "Increasing Precision-Range"
@prev "Large Automatic Arrays"
@toc "Missing Features"

Support for Threads
-------------------

Neither the code produced by @{b}g77@{ub} nor the @{b}libg2c@{ub} library are
thread-safe, nor does @{b}g77@{ub} have support for parallel processing (other
than the instruction-level parallelism available on some processors).
A package such as PVM might help here.

@endnode

@node "Enabling Debug Lines" "g77.guide/Enabling Debug Lines"
@next "Better Warnings"
@prev "Increasing Precision-Range"
@toc "Missing Features"

Enabling Debug Lines
--------------------

An option such as @{b}-fdebug-lines@{ub} should be provided to turn fixed-form
lines beginning with @{b}D@{ub} to be treated as if they began with a space,
instead of as if they began with a @{b}C@{ub} (as comment lines).

@endnode

@node "Better Warnings" "g77.guide/Better Warnings"
@next "Gracefully Handle Sensible Bad Code"
@prev "Enabling Debug Lines"
@toc "Missing Features"

Better Warnings
---------------

Because of how @{b}g77@{ub} generates code via the back end, it doesn't always
provide warnings the user wants.  Consider:

     PROGRAM X
     PRINT *, A
     END

   Currently, the above is not flagged as a case of using an
uninitialized variable, because @{b}g77@{ub} generates a run-time library call
that looks, to the GBE, like it might actually @{i}modify@{ui} @{b}A@{ub} at run time.
(And, in fact, depending on the previous run-time library call, it
would!)

   Fixing this requires one of the following:

   * Switch to new library, @{b}libg77@{ub}, that provides a more "clean"
     interface, vis-a-vis input, output, and modified arguments, so the
     GBE can tell what's going on.

     This would provide a pretty big performance improvement, at least
     theoretically, and, ultimately, in practice, for some types of
     code.

   * Have @{b}g77@{ub} pass a pointer to a temporary containing a copy of @{b}A@{ub},
     instead of to @{b}A@{ub} itself.  The GBE would then complain about the
     copy operation involving a potentially uninitialized variable.

     This might also provide a performance boost for some code, because
     @{b}A@{ub} might then end up living in a register, which could help with
     inner loops.

   * Have @{b}g77@{ub} use a GBE construct similar to @{b}ADDR_EXPR@{ub} but with extra
     information on the fact that the item pointed to won't be modified
     (a la @{b}const@{ub} in C).

     Probably the best solution for now, but not quite trivial to
     implement in the general case.

@endnode

@node "Gracefully Handle Sensible Bad Code" "g77.guide/Gracefully Handle Sensible Bad Code"
@next "Non-standard Conversions"
@prev "Better Warnings"
@toc "Missing Features"

Gracefully Handle Sensible Bad Code
-----------------------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} generally should continue processing for warnings and recoverable
(user) errors whenever possible--that is, it shouldn't gratuitously
make bad or useless code.

   For example:

     INTRINSIC ZABS
     CALL FOO(ZABS)
     END

When compiling the above with @{b}-ff2c-intrinsics-disable@{ub}, @{b}g77@{ub} should
indeed complain about passing @{b}ZABS@{ub}, but it still should compile,
instead of rejecting the entire @{b}CALL@{ub} statement.  (Some of this is
related to improving the compiler internals to improve how statements
are analyzed.)

@endnode

@node "Non-standard Conversions" "g77.guide/Non-standard Conversions"
@next "Non-standard Intrinsics"
@prev "Gracefully Handle Sensible Bad Code"
@toc "Missing Features"

Non-standard Conversions
------------------------

@{b}-Wconversion@{ub} and related should flag places where non-standard
conversions are found.  Perhaps much of this would be part of @{b}-Wugly*@{ub}.

@endnode

@node "Non-standard Intrinsics" "g77.guide/Non-standard Intrinsics"
@next "Modifying DO Variable"
@prev "Non-standard Conversions"
@toc "Missing Features"

Non-standard Intrinsics
-----------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} needs a new option, like @{b}-Wintrinsics@{ub}, to warn about use of
non-standard intrinsics without explicit @{b}INTRINSIC@{ub} statements for them.
This would help find code that might fail silently when ported to
another compiler.

@endnode

@node "Modifying DO Variable" "g77.guide/Modifying DO Variable"
@next "Better Pedantic Compilation"
@prev "Non-standard Intrinsics"
@toc "Missing Features"

Modifying @{b}DO@{ub} Variable
---------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} should warn about modifying @{b}DO@{ub} variables via @{b}EQUIVALENCE@{ub}.  (The
internal information gathered to produce this warning might also be
useful in setting the internal "doiter" flag for a variable or even
array reference within a loop, since that might produce faster code
someday.)

   For example, this code is invalid, so @{b}g77@{ub} should warn about the
invalid assignment to @{b}NOTHER@{ub}:

     EQUIVALENCE (I, NOTHER)
     DO I = 1, 100
        IF (I.EQ. 10) NOTHER = 20
     END DO

@endnode

@node "Better Pedantic Compilation" "g77.guide/Better Pedantic Compilation"
@next "Warn About Implicit Conversions"
@prev "Modifying DO Variable"
@toc "Missing Features"

Better Pedantic Compilation
---------------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} needs to support @{b}-fpedantic@{ub} more thoroughly, and use it only to
generate warnings instead of rejecting constructs outright.  Have it
warn: if a variable that dimensions an array is not a dummy or placed
explicitly in @{b}COMMON@{ub} (F77 does not allow it to be placed in @{b}COMMON@{ub} via
@{b}EQUIVALENCE@{ub}); if specification statements follow
statement-function-definition statements; about all sorts of syntactic
extensions.

@endnode

@node "Warn About Implicit Conversions" "g77.guide/Warn About Implicit Conversions"
@next "Invalid Use of Hollerith Constant"
@prev "Better Pedantic Compilation"
@toc "Missing Features"

Warn About Implicit Conversions
-------------------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} needs a @{b}-Wpromotions@{ub} option to warn if source code appears to
expect automatic, silent, and somewhat dangerous compiler-assisted
conversion of @{b}REAL(KIND=1)@{ub} constants to @{b}REAL(KIND=2)@{ub} based on context.

   For example, it would warn about cases like this:

     DOUBLE PRECISION FOO
     PARAMETER (TZPHI = 9.435784839284958)
     FOO = TZPHI * 3D0

@endnode

@node "Invalid Use of Hollerith Constant" "g77.guide/Invalid Use of Hollerith Constant"
@next "Dummy Array Without Dimensioning Dummy"
@prev "Warn About Implicit Conversions"
@toc "Missing Features"

Invalid Use of Hollerith Constant
---------------------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} should disallow statements like @{b}RETURN 2HAB@{ub}, which are invalid in
both source forms (unlike @{b}RETURN (2HAB)@{ub}, which probably still makes no
sense but at least can be reliably parsed).  Fixed-form processing
rejects it, but not free-form, except in a way that is a bit difficult
to understand.

@endnode

@node "Dummy Array Without Dimensioning Dummy" "g77.guide/Dummy Array Without Dimensioning Dummy"
@next "Invalid FORMAT Specifiers"
@prev "Invalid Use of Hollerith Constant"
@toc "Missing Features"

Dummy Array Without Dimensioning Dummy
--------------------------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} should complain when a list of dummy arguments containing an
adjustable dummy array does not also contain every variable listed in
the dimension list of the adjustable array.

   Currently, @{b}g77@{ub} does complain about a variable that dimensions an
array but doesn't appear in any dummy list or @{b}COMMON@{ub} area, but this
needs to be extended to catch cases where it doesn't appear in every
dummy list that also lists any arrays it dimensions.

   For example, @{b}g77@{ub} should warn about the entry point @{b}ALT@{ub} below, since
it includes @{b}ARRAY@{ub} but not @{b}ISIZE@{ub} in its list of arguments:

     SUBROUTINE PRIMARY(ARRAY, ISIZE)
     REAL ARRAY(ISIZE)
     ENTRY ALT(ARRAY)

@endnode

@node "Invalid FORMAT Specifiers" "g77.guide/Invalid FORMAT Specifiers"
@next "Ambiguous Dialects"
@prev "Dummy Array Without Dimensioning Dummy"
@toc "Missing Features"

Invalid FORMAT Specifiers
-------------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} should check @{b}FORMAT@{ub} specifiers for validity as it does @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
statements.

   For example, a diagnostic would be produced for:

     PRINT 'HI THERE!'  !User meant PRINT *, 'HI THERE!'

@endnode

@node "Ambiguous Dialects" "g77.guide/Ambiguous Dialects"
@next "Unused Labels"
@prev "Invalid FORMAT Specifiers"
@toc "Missing Features"

Ambiguous Dialects
------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} needs a set of options such as @{b}-Wugly*@{ub}, @{b}-Wautomatic@{ub}, @{b}-Wvxt@{ub}, @{b}-Wf90@{ub},
and so on.  These would warn about places in the user's source where
ambiguities are found, helpful in resolving ambiguities in the program's
dialect or dialects.

@endnode

@node "Unused Labels" "g77.guide/Unused Labels"
@next "Informational Messages"
@prev "Ambiguous Dialects"
@toc "Missing Features"

Unused Labels
-------------

@{b}g77@{ub} should warn about unused labels when @{b}-Wunused@{ub} is in effect.

@endnode

@node "Informational Messages" "g77.guide/Informational Messages"
@next "Uninitialized Variables at Run Time"
@prev "Unused Labels"
@toc "Missing Features"

Informational Messages
----------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} needs an option to suppress information messages (notes).  @{b}-w@{ub} does
this but also suppresses warnings.  The default should be to suppress
info messages.

   Perhaps info messages should simply be eliminated.

@endnode

@node "Uninitialized Variables at Run Time" "g77.guide/Uninitialized Variables at Run Time"
@next "Portable Unformatted Files"
@prev "Informational Messages"
@toc "Missing Features"

Uninitialized Variables at Run Time
-----------------------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} needs an option to initialize everything (not otherwise explicitly
initialized) to "weird" (machine-dependent) values, e.g. NaNs, bad
(non-@{b}NULL@{ub}) pointers, and largest-magnitude integers, would help track
down references to some kinds of uninitialized variables at run time.

   Note that use of the options @{b}-O -Wuninitialized@{ub} can catch many such
bugs at compile time.

@endnode

@node "Portable Unformatted Files" "g77.guide/Portable Unformatted Files"
@next "Better List-directed I-O"
@prev "Uninitialized Variables at Run Time"
@toc "Missing Features"

Portable Unformatted Files
--------------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} has no facility for exchanging unformatted files with systems using
different number formats--even differing only in endianness (byte
order)--or written by other compilers.  Some compilers provide
facilities at least for doing byte-swapping during unformatted I/O.

   It is unrealistic to expect to cope with exchanging unformatted files
with arbitrary other compiler runtimes, but the @{b}g77@{ub} runtime should at
least be able to read files written by @{b}g77@{ub} on systems with different
number formats, particularly if they differ only in byte order.

   In case you do need to write a program to translate to or from @{b}g77@{ub}
(@{b}libf2c@{ub}) unformatted files, they are written as follows:
Sequential
     Unformatted sequential records consist of
       1. A number giving the length of the record contents;

       2. the length of record contents again (for backspace).

     The record length is of C type @{b}long@{ub}; this means that it is 8 bytes
     on 64-bit systems such as Alpha GNU/Linux and 4 bytes on other
     systems, such as x86 GNU/Linux.  Consequently such files cannot be
     exchanged between 64-bit and 32-bit systems, even with the same
     basic number format.

Direct access
     Unformatted direct access files form a byte stream of length
     RECORDS*RECL bytes, where RECORDS is the maximum record number
     (@{b}REC=RECORDS@{ub}) written and RECL is the record length in bytes
     specified in the @{b}OPEN@{ub} statement (@{b}RECL=RECL@{ub}).  Data appear in the
     records as determined by the relevant @{b}WRITE@{ub} statement.  Dummy
     records with arbitrary contents appear in the file in place of
     records which haven't been written.

   Thus for exchanging a sequential or direct access unformatted file
between big- and little-endian 32-bit systems using IEEE 754 floating
point it would be sufficient to reverse the bytes in consecutive words
in the file if, and @{i}only@{ui} if, only @{b}REAL*4@{ub}, @{b}COMPLEX@{ub}, @{b}INTEGER*4@{ub} and/or
@{b}LOGICAL*4@{ub} data have been written to it by @{b}g77@{ub}.

   If necessary, it is possible to do byte-oriented i/o with @{b}g77@{ub}'s
@{b}FGETC@{ub} and @{b}FPUTC@{ub} intrinsics.  Byte-swapping can be done in Fortran by
equivalencing larger sized variables to an @{b}INTEGER*1@{ub} array or a set of
scalars.

   If you need to exchange binary data between arbitrary system and
compiler variations, we recommend using a portable binary format with
Fortran bindings, such as NCSA's HDF (`http://hdf.ncsa.uiuc.edu/') or
PACT's PDB(1) (`http://www.llnl.gov/def_sci/pact/pact_homepage.html').
(Unlike, say, CDF or XDR, HDF-like systems write in the native number
formats and only incur overhead when they are read on a system with a
different format.)  A future @{b}g77@{ub} runtime library should use such
techniques.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1) No, not @{i}that@{ui} one.

@endnode

@node "Better List-directed I-O" "g77.guide/Better List-directed I-O"
@next "Default to Console I-O"
@prev "Portable Unformatted Files"
@toc "Missing Features"

Better List-directed I/O
------------------------

Values output using list-directed I/O (@{b}PRINT *, R, D@{ub}) should be written
with a field width, precision, and so on appropriate for the type
(precision) of each value.

   (Currently, no distinction is made between single-precision and
double-precision values by @{b}libf2c@{ub}.)

   It is likely this item will require the @{b}libg77@{ub} project to be
undertaken.

   In the meantime, use of formatted I/O is recommended.  While it
might be of little consolation, @{b}g77@{ub} does support @{b}FORMAT(F<WIDTH>.4)@{ub},
for example, as long as @{b}WIDTH@{ub} is defined as a named constant (via
@{b}PARAMETER@{ub}).  That at least allows some compile-time specification of
the precision of a data type, perhaps controlled by preprocessing
directives.

@endnode

@node "Default to Console I-O" "g77.guide/Default to Console I-O"
@next "Labels Visible to Debugger"
@prev "Better List-directed I-O"
@toc "Missing Features"

Default to Console I/O
----------------------

The default I/O units, specified by @{b}READ FMT@{ub}, @{b}READ (UNIT=*)@{ub}, @{b}WRITE
(UNIT=*)@{ub}, and @{b}PRINT FMT@{ub}, should not be units 5 (input) and 6 (output),
but, rather, unit numbers not normally available for use in statements
such as @{b}OPEN@{ub} and @{b}CLOSE@{ub}.

   Changing this would allow a program to connect units 5 and 6 to
files via @{b}OPEN@{ub}, but still use @{b}READ (UNIT=*)@{ub} and @{b}PRINT@{ub} to do I/O to the
"console".

   This change probably requires the @{b}libg77@{ub} project.

@endnode

@node "Labels Visible to Debugger" "g77.guide/Labels Visible to Debugger"
@prev "Default to Console I-O"
@toc "Missing Features"

Labels Visible to Debugger
--------------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} should output debugging information for statements labels, for use
by debuggers that know how to support them.  Same with weirder things
like construct names.  It is not yet known if any debug formats or
debuggers support these.

@endnode

@node "Disappointments" "g77.guide/Disappointments"
@next "Non-bugs"
@prev "Missing Features"
@toc "Trouble"

Disappointments and Misunderstandings
=====================================

These problems are perhaps regrettable, but we don't know any practical
way around them for now.


 @{" Mangling of Names                      " link "Mangling of Names"}  @{b}SUBROUTINE FOO@{ub} is given
                                              external name @{b}foo_@{ub}.
 @{" Multiple Definitions of External Names " link "Multiple Definitions of External Names"}  No doing both @{b}COMMON /FOO/@{ub}
                                              and @{b}SUBROUTINE FOO@{ub}.
 @{" Limitation on Implicit Declarations    " link "Limitation on Implicit Declarations"}  No @{b}IMPLICIT CHARACTER*(*)@{ub}.

@endnode

@node "Mangling of Names" "g77.guide/Mangling of Names"
@next "Multiple Definitions of External Names"
@toc "Disappointments"

Mangling of Names in Source Code
--------------------------------

The current external-interface design, which includes naming of
external procedures, COMMON blocks, and the library interface, has
various usability problems, including things like adding underscores
where not really necessary (and preventing easier inter-language
operability) and yet not providing complete namespace freedom for user
C code linked with Fortran apps (due to the naming of functions in the
library, among other things).

   Project GNU should at least get all this "right" for systems it
fully controls, such as the Hurd, and provide defaults and options for
compatibility with existing systems and interoperability with popular
existing compilers.

@endnode

@node "Multiple Definitions of External Names" "g77.guide/Multiple Definitions of External Names"
@next "Limitation on Implicit Declarations"
@prev "Mangling of Names"
@toc "Disappointments"

Multiple Definitions of External Names
--------------------------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} doesn't allow a common block and an external procedure or @{b}BLOCK
DATA@{ub} to have the same name.  Some systems allow this, but @{b}g77@{ub} does not,
to be compatible with @{b}f2c@{ub}.

   @{b}g77@{ub} could special-case the way it handles @{b}BLOCK DATA@{ub}, since it is
not compatible with @{b}f2c@{ub} in this particular area (necessarily, since @{b}g77@{ub}
offers an important feature here), but it is likely that such
special-casing would be very annoying to people with programs that use
@{b}EXTERNAL FOO@{ub}, with no other mention of @{b}FOO@{ub} in the same program unit, to
refer to external procedures, since the result would be that @{b}g77@{ub} would
treat these references as requests to force-load BLOCK DATA program
units.

   In that case, if @{b}g77@{ub} modified names of @{b}BLOCK DATA@{ub} so they could have
the same names as @{b}COMMON@{ub}, users would find that their programs wouldn't
link because the @{b}FOO@{ub} procedure didn't have its name translated the same
way.

   (Strictly speaking, @{b}g77@{ub} could emit a null-but-externally-satisfying
definition of @{b}FOO@{ub} with its name transformed as if it had been a @{b}BLOCK
DATA@{ub}, but that probably invites more trouble than it's worth.)

@endnode

@node "Limitation on Implicit Declarations" "g77.guide/Limitation on Implicit Declarations"
@prev "Multiple Definitions of External Names"
@toc "Disappointments"

Limitation on Implicit Declarations
-----------------------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} disallows @{b}IMPLICIT CHARACTER*(*)@{ub}.  This is not standard-conforming.

@endnode

@node "Non-bugs" "g77.guide/Non-bugs"
@next "Warnings and Errors"
@prev "Disappointments"
@toc "Trouble"

Certain Changes We Don't Want to Make
=====================================

This section lists changes that people frequently request, but which we
do not make because we think GNU Fortran is better without them.


 @{" Backslash in Constants          " link "Backslash in Constants"}  Why @{b}'\\\\'@{ub} is a constant that
                                       is one, not two, characters long.
 @{" Initializing Before Specifying  " link "Initializing Before Specifying"}  Why @{b}DATA VAR/1/@{ub} can't precede
                                       @{b}COMMON VAR@{ub}.
 @{" Context-Sensitive Intrinsicness " link "Context-Sensitive Intrinsicness"}  Why @{b}CALL SQRT@{ub} won't work.
 @{" Context-Sensitive Constants     " link "Context-Sensitive Constants"}  Why @{b}9.435784839284958@{ub} is a
                                       single-precision constant,
                                       and might be interpreted as
                                       @{b}9.435785@{ub} or similar.
 @{" Equivalence Versus Equality     " link "Equivalence Versus Equality"}  Why @{b}.TRUE. .EQ. .TRUE.@{ub} won't work.
 @{" Order of Side Effects           " link "Order of Side Effects"}  Why @{b}J = IFUNC() - IFUNC()@{ub} might
                                       not behave as expected.

@endnode

@node "Backslash in Constants" "g77.guide/Backslash in Constants"
@next "Initializing Before Specifying"
@toc "Non-bugs"

Backslash in Constants
----------------------

In the opinion of many experienced Fortran users, @{b}-fno-backslash@{ub} should
be the default, not @{b}-fbackslash@{ub}, as currently set by @{b}g77@{ub}.

   First of all, you can always specify @{b}-fno-backslash@{ub} to turn off this
processing.

   Despite not being within the spirit (though apparently within the
letter) of the ANSI FORTRAN 77 standard, @{b}g77@{ub} defaults to @{b}-fbackslash@{ub}
because that is what most UNIX @{b}f77@{ub} commands default to, and apparently
lots of code depends on this feature.

   This is a particularly troubling issue.  The use of a C construct in
the midst of Fortran code is bad enough, worse when it makes existing
Fortran programs stop working (as happens when programs written for
non-UNIX systems are ported to UNIX systems with compilers that provide
the @{b}-fbackslash@{ub} feature as the default--sometimes with no option to
turn it off).

   The author of GNU Fortran wished, for reasons of linguistic purity,
to make @{b}-fno-backslash@{ub} the default for GNU Fortran and thus require
users of UNIX @{b}f77@{ub} and @{b}f2c@{ub} to specify @{b}-fbackslash@{ub} to get the UNIX
behavior.

   However, the realization that @{b}g77@{ub} is intended as a replacement for
@{i}UNIX@{ui} @{b}f77@{ub}, caused the author to choose to make @{b}g77@{ub} as compatible with
@{b}f77@{ub} as feasible, which meant making @{b}-fbackslash@{ub} the default.

   The primary focus on compatibility is at the source-code level, and
the question became "What will users expect a replacement for @{b}f77@{ub} to
do, by default?"  Although at least one UNIX @{b}f77@{ub} does not provide
@{b}-fbackslash@{ub} as a default, it appears that the majority of them do,
which suggests that the majority of code that is compiled by UNIX @{b}f77@{ub}
compilers expects @{b}-fbackslash@{ub} to be the default.

   It is probably the case that more code exists that would @{i}not@{ui} work
with @{b}-fbackslash@{ub} in force than code that requires it be in force.

   However, most of @{i}that@{ui} code is not being compiled with @{b}f77@{ub}, and when
it is, new build procedures (shell scripts, makefiles, and so on) must
be set up anyway so that they work under UNIX.  That makes a much more
natural and safe opportunity for non-UNIX users to adapt their build
procedures for @{b}g77@{ub}'s default of @{b}-fbackslash@{ub} than would exist for the
majority of UNIX @{b}f77@{ub} users who would have to modify existing, working
build procedures to explicitly specify @{b}-fbackslash@{ub} if that was not the
default.

   One suggestion has been to configure the default for @{b}-fbackslash@{ub}
(and perhaps other options as well) based on the configuration of @{b}g77@{ub}.

   This is technically quite straightforward, but will be avoided even
in cases where not configuring defaults to be dependent on a particular
configuration greatly inconveniences some users of legacy code.

   Many users appreciate the GNU compilers because they provide an
environment that is uniform across machines.  These users would be
inconvenienced if the compiler treated things like the format of the
source code differently on certain machines.

   Occasionally users write programs intended only for a particular
machine type.  On these occasions, the users would benefit if the GNU
Fortran compiler were to support by default the same dialect as the
other compilers on that machine.  But such applications are rare.  And
users writing a program to run on more than one type of machine cannot
possibly benefit from this kind of compatibility.  (This is consistent
with the design goals for @{b}gcc@{ub}.  To change them for @{b}g77@{ub}, you must first
change them for @{b}gcc@{ub}.  Do not ask the maintainers of @{b}g77@{ub} to do this for
you, or to disassociate @{b}g77@{ub} from the widely understood, if not widely
agreed-upon, goals for GNU compilers in general.)

   This is why GNU Fortran does and will treat backslashes in the same
fashion on all types of machines (by default).  See
@{"Direction of Language Development" link "Direction of Language Development"}, for more information on this
overall philosophy guiding the development of the GNU Fortran language.

   Of course, users strongly concerned about portability should indicate
explicitly in their build procedures which options are expected by
their source code, or write source code that has as few such
expectations as possible.

   For example, avoid writing code that depends on backslash (@{b}\\ @{ub})
being interpreted either way in particular, such as by starting a
program unit with:

     CHARACTER BACKSL
     PARAMETER (BACKSL = '\\\\')

Then, use concatenation of @{b}BACKSL@{ub} anyplace a backslash is desired.  In
this way, users can write programs which have the same meaning in many
Fortran dialects.

   (However, this technique does not work for Hollerith constants--which
is just as well, since the only generally portable uses for Hollerith
constants are in places where character constants can and should be
used instead, for readability.)

@endnode

@node "Initializing Before Specifying" "g77.guide/Initializing Before Specifying"
@next "Context-Sensitive Intrinsicness"
@prev "Backslash in Constants"
@toc "Non-bugs"

Initializing Before Specifying
------------------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} does not allow @{b}DATA VAR/1/@{ub} to appear in the source code before
@{b}COMMON VAR@{ub}, @{b}DIMENSION VAR(10)@{ub}, @{b}INTEGER VAR@{ub}, and so on.  In general, @{b}g77@{ub}
requires initialization of a variable or array to be specified @{i}after@{ui}
all other specifications of attributes (type, size, placement, and so
on) of that variable or array are specified (though @{i}confirmation@{ui} of
data type is permitted).

   It is @{i}possible@{ui} @{b}g77@{ub} will someday allow all of this, even though it is
not allowed by the FORTRAN 77 standard.

   Then again, maybe it is better to have @{b}g77@{ub} always require placement
of @{b}DATA@{ub} so that it can possibly immediately write constants to the
output file, thus saving time and space.

   That is, @{b}DATA A/1000000*1/@{ub} should perhaps always be immediately
writable to canonical assembler, unless it's already known to be in a
@{b}COMMON@{ub} area following as-yet-uninitialized stuff, and to do this it
cannot be followed by @{b}COMMON A@{ub}.

@endnode

@node "Context-Sensitive Intrinsicness" "g77.guide/Context-Sensitive Intrinsicness"
@next "Context-Sensitive Constants"
@prev "Initializing Before Specifying"
@toc "Non-bugs"

Context-Sensitive Intrinsicness
-------------------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} treats procedure references to @{i}possible@{ui} intrinsic names as always
enabling their intrinsic nature, regardless of whether the @{i}form@{ui} of the
reference is valid for that intrinsic.

   For example, @{b}CALL SQRT@{ub} is interpreted by @{b}g77@{ub} as an invalid reference
to the @{b}SQRT@{ub} intrinsic function, because the reference is a subroutine
invocation.

   First, @{b}g77@{ub} recognizes the statement @{b}CALL SQRT@{ub} as a reference to a
@{i}procedure@{ui} named @{b}SQRT@{ub}, not to a @{i}variable@{ui} with that name (as it would for
a statement such as @{b}V = SQRT@{ub}).

   Next, @{b}g77@{ub} establishes that, in the program unit being compiled, @{b}SQRT@{ub}
is an intrinsic--not a subroutine that happens to have the same name as
an intrinsic (as would be the case if, for example, @{b}EXTERNAL SQRT@{ub} was
present).

   Finally, @{b}g77@{ub} recognizes that the @{i}form@{ui} of the reference is invalid
for that particular intrinsic.  That is, it recognizes that it is
invalid for an intrinsic @{i}function@{ui}, such as @{b}SQRT@{ub}, to be invoked as a
@{i}subroutine@{ui}.

   At that point, @{b}g77@{ub} issues a diagnostic.

   Some users claim that it is "obvious" that @{b}CALL SQRT@{ub} references an
external subroutine of their own, not an intrinsic function.

   However, @{b}g77@{ub} knows about intrinsic subroutines, not just functions,
and is able to support both having the same names, for example.

   As a result of this, @{b}g77@{ub} rejects calls to intrinsics that are not
subroutines, and function invocations of intrinsics that are not
functions, just as it (and most compilers) rejects invocations of
intrinsics with the wrong number (or types) of arguments.

   So, use the @{b}EXTERNAL SQRT@{ub} statement in a program unit that calls a
user-written subroutine named @{b}SQRT@{ub}.

@endnode

@node "Context-Sensitive Constants" "g77.guide/Context-Sensitive Constants"
@next "Equivalence Versus Equality"
@prev "Context-Sensitive Intrinsicness"
@toc "Non-bugs"

Context-Sensitive Constants
---------------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} does not use context to determine the types of constants or named
constants (@{b}PARAMETER@{ub}), except for (non-standard) typeless constants
such as @{b}'123'O@{ub}.

   For example, consider the following statement:

     PRINT *, 9.435784839284958 * 2D0

@{b}g77@{ub} will interpret the (truncated) constant @{b}9.435784839284958@{ub} as a
@{b}REAL(KIND=1)@{ub}, not @{b}REAL(KIND=2)@{ub}, constant, because the suffix @{b}D0@{ub} is not
specified.

   As a result, the output of the above statement when compiled by @{b}g77@{ub}
will appear to have "less precision" than when compiled by other
compilers.

   In these and other cases, some compilers detect the fact that a
single-precision constant is used in a double-precision context and
therefore interpret the single-precision constant as if it was
@{i}explicitly@{ui} specified as a double-precision constant.  (This has the
effect of appending @{i}decimal@{ui}, not @{i}binary@{ui}, zeros to the fractional part
of the number--producing different computational results.)

   The reason this misfeature is dangerous is that a slight, apparently
innocuous change to the source code can change the computational
results.  Consider:

     REAL ALMOST, CLOSE
     DOUBLE PRECISION FIVE
     PARAMETER (ALMOST = 5.000000000001)
     FIVE = 5
     CLOSE = 5.000000000001
     PRINT *, 5.000000000001 - FIVE
     PRINT *, ALMOST - FIVE
     PRINT *, CLOSE - FIVE
     END

Running the above program should result in the same value being printed
three times.  With @{b}g77@{ub} as the compiler, it does.

   However, compiled by many other compilers, running the above program
would print two or three distinct values, because in two or three of
the statements, the constant @{b}5.000000000001@{ub}, which on most systems is
exactly equal to @{b}5.@{ub} when interpreted as a single-precision constant, is
instead interpreted as a double-precision constant, preserving the
represented precision.  However, this "clever" promotion of type does
not extend to variables or, in some compilers, to named constants.

   Since programmers often are encouraged to replace manifest constants
or permanently-assigned variables with named constants (@{b}PARAMETER@{ub} in
Fortran), and might need to replace some constants with variables
having the same values for pertinent portions of code, it is important
that compilers treat code so modified in the same way so that the
results of such programs are the same.  @{b}g77@{ub} helps in this regard by
treating constants just the same as variables in terms of determining
their types in a context-independent way.

   Still, there is a lot of existing Fortran code that has been written
to depend on the way other compilers freely interpret constants' types
based on context, so anything @{b}g77@{ub} can do to help flag cases of this in
such code could be very helpful.

@endnode

@node "Equivalence Versus Equality" "g77.guide/Equivalence Versus Equality"
@next "Order of Side Effects"
@prev "Context-Sensitive Constants"
@toc "Non-bugs"

Equivalence Versus Equality
---------------------------

Use of @{b}.EQ.@{ub} and @{b}.NE.@{ub} on @{b}LOGICAL@{ub} operands is not supported, except via
@{b}-fugly-logint@{ub}, which is not recommended except for legacy code (where
the behavior expected by the @{i}code@{ui} is assumed).

   Legacy code should be changed, as resources permit, to use @{b}.EQV.@{ub} and
@{b}.NEQV.@{ub} instead, as these are permitted by the various Fortran standards.

   New code should never be written expecting @{b}.EQ.@{ub} or @{b}.NE.@{ub} to work if
either of its operands is @{b}LOGICAL@{ub}.

   The problem with supporting this "feature" is that there is unlikely
to be consensus on how it works, as illustrated by the following sample
program:

     LOGICAL L,M,N
     DATA L,M,N /3*.FALSE./
     IF (L.AND.M.EQ.N) PRINT *,'L.AND.M.EQ.N'
     END

   The issue raised by the above sample program is: what is the
precedence of @{b}.EQ.@{ub} (and @{b}.NE.@{ub}) when applied to @{b}LOGICAL@{ub} operands?

   Some programmers will argue that it is the same as the precedence
for @{b}.EQ.@{ub} when applied to numeric (such as @{b}INTEGER@{ub}) operands.  By this
interpretation, the subexpression @{b}M.EQ.N@{ub} must be evaluated first in the
above program, resulting in a program that, when run, does not execute
the @{b}PRINT@{ub} statement.

   Other programmers will argue that the precedence is the same as the
precedence for @{b}.EQV.@{ub}, which is restricted by the standards to @{b}LOGICAL@{ub}
operands.  By this interpretation, the subexpression @{b}L.AND.M@{ub} must be
evaluated first, resulting in a program that @{i}does@{ui} execute the @{b}PRINT@{ub}
statement.

   Assigning arbitrary semantic interpretations to syntactic expressions
that might legitimately have more than one "obvious" interpretation is
generally unwise.

   The creators of the various Fortran standards have done a good job
in this case, requiring a distinct set of operators (which have their
own distinct precedence) to compare @{b}LOGICAL@{ub} operands.  This requirement
results in expression syntax with more certain precedence (without
requiring substantial context), making it easier for programmers to
read existing code.  @{b}g77@{ub} will avoid muddying up elements of the Fortran
language that were well-designed in the first place.

   (Ask C programmers about the precedence of expressions such as @{b}(a) &
(b)@{ub} and @{b}(a) - (b)@{ub}--they cannot even tell you, without knowing more
context, whether the @{b}&@{ub} and @{b}-@{ub} operators are infix (binary) or unary!)

   Most dangerous of all is the fact that, even assuming consensus on
its meaning, an expression like @{b}L.AND.M.EQ.N@{ub}, if it is the result of a
typographical error, doesn't @{i}look@{ui} like it has such a typo.  Even
experienced Fortran programmers would not likely notice that
@{b}L.AND.M.EQV.N@{ub} was, in fact, intended.

   So, this is a prime example of a circumstance in which a quality
compiler diagnoses the code, instead of leaving it up to someone
debugging it to know to turn on special compiler options that might
diagnose it.

@endnode

@node "Order of Side Effects" "g77.guide/Order of Side Effects"
@prev "Equivalence Versus Equality"
@toc "Non-bugs"

Order of Side Effects
---------------------

@{b}g77@{ub} does not necessarily produce code that, when run, performs side
effects (such as those performed by function invocations) in the same
order as in some other compiler--or even in the same order as another
version, port, or invocation (using different command-line options) of
@{b}g77@{ub}.

   It is never safe to depend on the order of evaluation of side
effects.  For example, an expression like this may very well behave
differently from one compiler to another:

     J = IFUNC() - IFUNC()

There is no guarantee that @{b}IFUNC@{ub} will be evaluated in any particular
order.  Either invocation might happen first.  If @{b}IFUNC@{ub} returns 5 the
first time it is invoked, and returns 12 the second time, @{b}J@{ub} might end
up with the value @{b}7@{ub}, or it might end up with @{b}-7@{ub}.

   Generally, in Fortran, procedures with side-effects intended to be
visible to the caller are best designed as @{i}subroutines@{ui}, not functions.
Examples of such side-effects include:

   * The generation of random numbers that are intended to influence
     return values.

   * Performing I/O (other than internal I/O to local variables).

   * Updating information in common blocks.

   An example of a side-effect that is not intended to be visible to
the caller is a function that maintains a cache of recently calculated
results, intended solely to speed repeated invocations of the function
with identical arguments.  Such a function can be safely used in
expressions, because if the compiler optimizes away one or more calls
to the function, operation of the program is unaffected (aside from
being speeded up).

@endnode

@node "Warnings and Errors" "g77.guide/Warnings and Errors"
@prev "Non-bugs"
@toc "Trouble"

Warning Messages and Error Messages
===================================

The GNU compiler can produce two kinds of diagnostics: errors and
warnings.  Each kind has a different purpose:

    @{i} Errors@{ui} report problems that make it impossible to compile your
     program.  GNU Fortran reports errors with the source file name,
     line number, and column within the line where the problem is
     apparent.

    @{i} Warnings@{ui} report other unusual conditions in your code that @{i}might@{ui}
     indicate a problem, although compilation can (and does) proceed.
     Warning messages also report the source file name, line number,
     and column information, but include the text @{b}warning:@{ub} to
     distinguish them from error messages.

   Warnings might indicate danger points where you should check to make
sure that your program really does what you intend; or the use of
obsolete features; or the use of nonstandard features of GNU Fortran.
Many warnings are issued only if you ask for them, with one of the @{b}-W@{ub}
options (for instance, @{b}-Wall@{ub} requests a variety of useful warnings).

   @{i}Note:@{ui} Currently, the text of the line and a pointer to the column is
printed in most @{b}g77@{ub} diagnostics.

   See @{"Options to Request or Suppress Warnings" link "Warning Options"}, for more detail on
these and related command-line options.

@endnode

@node "Open Questions" "g77.guide/Open Questions"
@next "Bugs"
@prev "Trouble"
@toc "Main"

Open Questions
**************

Please consider offering useful answers to these questions!

   * @{b}LOC()@{ub} and other intrinsics are probably somewhat misclassified.
     Is the a need for more precise classification of intrinsics, and
     if so, what are the appropriate groupings?  Is there a need to
     individually enable/disable/delete/hide intrinsics from the
     command line?

@endnode

@node "Bugs" "g77.guide/Bugs"
@next "Service"
@prev "Open Questions"
@toc "Main"

Reporting Bugs
**************

Your bug reports play an essential role in making GNU Fortran reliable.

   When you encounter a problem, the first thing to do is to see if it
is already known.  See @{"Trouble" link "Trouble"}.  If it isn't known, then you should
report the problem.


 @{" Criteria                " link "Bug Criteria"}  Have you really found a bug?
 @{" Reporting               " link "Bug Reporting"}  How to report a bug effectively.

   See @{"Known Causes of Trouble with GNU Fortran" link "Trouble"}, for information on
problems we already know about.

   See @{"How To Get Help with GNU Fortran" link "Service"}, for information on where to
ask for help.

@endnode

@node "Bug Criteria" "g77.guide/Bug Criteria"
@next "Bug Reporting"
@toc "Bugs"

Have You Found a Bug?
=====================

If you are not sure whether you have found a bug, here are some
guidelines:

   * If the compiler gets a fatal signal, for any input whatever, that
     is a compiler bug.  Reliable compilers never crash--they just
     remain obsolete.

   * If the compiler produces invalid assembly code, for any input
     whatever, that is a compiler bug, unless the compiler reports
     errors (not just warnings) which would ordinarily prevent the
     assembler from being run.

   * If the compiler produces valid assembly code that does not
     correctly execute the input source code, that is a compiler bug.

     However, you must double-check to make sure, because you might
     have run into an incompatibility between GNU Fortran and
     traditional Fortran.  These incompatibilities might be considered
     bugs, but they are inescapable consequences of valuable features.

     Or you might have a program whose behavior is undefined, which
     happened by chance to give the desired results with another
     Fortran compiler.  It is best to check the relevant Fortran
     standard thoroughly if it is possible that the program indeed does
     something undefined.

     After you have localized the error to a single source line, it
     should be easy to check for these things.  If your program is
     correct and well defined, you have found a compiler bug.

     It might help if, in your submission, you identified the specific
     language in the relevant Fortran standard that specifies the
     desired behavior, if it isn't likely to be obvious and agreed-upon
     by all Fortran users.

   * If the compiler produces an error message for valid input, that is
     a compiler bug.

   * If the compiler does not produce an error message for invalid
     input, that is a compiler bug.  However, you should note that your
     idea of "invalid input" might be someone else's idea of "an
     extension" or "support for traditional practice".

   * If you are an experienced user of Fortran compilers, your
     suggestions for improvement of GNU Fortran are welcome in any case.

   Many, perhaps most, bug reports against @{b}g77@{ub} turn out to be bugs in
the user's code.  While we find such bug reports educational, they
sometimes take a considerable amount of time to track down or at least
respond to--time we could be spending making @{b}g77@{ub}, not some user's code,
better.

   Some steps you can take to verify that the bug is not certainly in
the code you're compiling with @{b}g77@{ub}:

   * Compile your code using the @{b}g77@{ub} options @{b}-W -Wall -O@{ub}.  These
     options enable many useful warning; the @{b}-O@{ub} option enables flow
     analysis that enables the uninitialized-variable warning.

     If you investigate the warnings and find evidence of possible bugs
     in your code, fix them first and retry @{b}g77@{ub}.

   * Compile your code using the @{b}g77@{ub} options @{b}-finit-local-zero@{ub},
     @{b}-fno-automatic@{ub}, @{b}-ffloat-store@{ub}, and various combinations thereof.

     If your code works with any of these combinations, that is not
     proof that the bug isn't in @{b}g77@{ub}--a @{b}g77@{ub} bug exposed by your code
     might simply be avoided, or have a different, more subtle effect,
     when different options are used--but it can be a strong indicator
     that your code is making unwarranted assumptions about the Fortran
     dialect and/or underlying machine it is being compiled and run on.

     See @{"Overly Convenient Command-Line Options" link "Overly Convenient Options"}, for information on
     the @{b}-fno-automatic@{ub} and @{b}-finit-local-zero@{ub} options and how to convert
     their use into selective changes in your own code.

   * Validate your code with @{b}ftnchek@{ub} or a similar code-checking tool.
     @{b}ftnchek@{ub} can be found at `ftp://ftp.netlib.org/fortran' or
     `ftp://ftp.dsm.fordham.edu'.

     Here are some sample @{b}Makefile@{ub} rules using @{b}ftnchek@{ub} "project" files
     to do cross-file checking and @{b}sfmakedepend@{ub} (from
     `ftp://ahab.rutgers.edu/pub/perl/sfmakedepend') to maintain
     dependencies automatically.  These assume the use of GNU @{b}make@{ub}.

          # Dummy suffix for ftnchek targets:
          .SUFFIXES: .chek
          .PHONY: chekall
          
          # How to compile .f files (for implicit rule):
          FC = g77
          # Assume `include' directory:
          FFLAGS = -Iinclude -g -O -Wall
          
          # Flags for ftnchek:
          CHEK1 = -array=0 -include=includes -noarray
          CHEK2 = -nonovice -usage=1 -notruncation
          CHEKFLAGS = $(CHEK1) $(CHEK2)
          
          # Run ftnchek with all the .prj files except the one corresponding
          # to the target's root:
          %.chek : %.f ; \\
            ftnchek $(filter-out $*.prj,$(PRJS)) $(CHEKFLAGS) \\
              -noextern -library $<
          
          # Derive a project file from a source file:
          %.prj : %.f ; \\
            ftnchek $(CHEKFLAGS) -noextern -project -library $<
          
          # The list of objects is assumed to be in variable OBJS.
          # Sources corresponding to the objects:
          SRCS = $(OBJS:%.o=%.f)
          # ftnchek project files:
          PRJS = $(OBJS:%.o=%.prj)
          
          # Build the program
          prog: $(OBJS) ; \\
            $(FC) -o $ $(OBJS)
          
          chekall: $(PRJS) ; \\
            ftnchek $(CHEKFLAGS) $(PRJS)
          
          prjs: $(PRJS)
          
          # For Emacs M-x find-tag:
          TAGS: $(SRCS) ; \\
            etags $(SRCS)
          
          # Rebuild dependencies:
          depend: ; \\
            sfmakedepend -I $(PLTLIBDIR) -I includes -a prj $(SRCS1)

   * Try your code out using other Fortran compilers, such as @{b}f2c@{ub}.  If
     it does not work on at least one other compiler (assuming the
     compiler supports the features the code needs), that is a strong
     indicator of a bug in the code.

     However, even if your code works on many compilers @{i}except@{ui} @{b}g77@{ub},
     that does @{i}not@{ui} mean the bug is in @{b}g77@{ub}.  It might mean the bug is in
     your code, and that @{b}g77@{ub} simply exposes it more readily than other
     compilers.

@endnode

@node "Bug Reporting" "g77.guide/Bug Reporting"
@prev "Bug Criteria"
@toc "Bugs"

How to Report Bugs
==================

Bugs should be reported to our bug database.  Please refer to
`http://gcc.gnu.org/bugs.html' for up-to-date instructions how to
submit bug reports.  Copies of this file in HTML (@{b}bugs.html@{ub}) and plain
text (@{b}BUGS@{ub}) are also part of GCC releases.

@endnode

@node "Service" "g77.guide/Service"
@next "Adding Options"
@prev "Bugs"
@toc "Main"

How To Get Help with GNU Fortran
********************************

If you need help installing, using or changing GNU Fortran, there are
two ways to find it:

   * Look in the service directory for someone who might help you for a
     fee.  The service directory is found in the file named @{b}SERVICE@{ub} in
     the GCC distribution.

   * Send a message to <gcc-help\@gcc.gnu.org>.

@endnode

@node "Adding Options" "g77.guide/Adding Options"
@next "Projects"
@prev "Service"
@toc "Main"

Adding Options
**************

To add a new command-line option to @{b}g77@{ub}, first decide what kind of
option you wish to add.  Search the @{b}g77@{ub} and @{b}gcc@{ub} documentation for one
or more options that is most closely like the one you want to add (in
terms of what kind of effect it has, and so on) to help clarify its
nature.

   * @{i}Fortran options@{ui} are options that apply only when compiling Fortran
     programs.  They are accepted by @{b}g77@{ub} and @{b}gcc@{ub}, but they apply only
     when compiling Fortran programs.

   * @{i}Compiler options@{ui} are options that apply when compiling most any
     kind of program.

   @{i}Fortran options@{ui} are listed in the file @{b}gcc/gcc/f/lang-options.h@{ub},
which is used during the build of @{b}gcc@{ub} to build a list of all options
that are accepted by at least one language's compiler.  This list goes
into the @{b}documented_lang_options@{ub} array in @{b}gcc/toplev.c@{ub}, which uses this
array to determine whether a particular option should be offered to the
linked-in front end for processing by calling @{b}lang_option_decode@{ub},
which, for @{b}g77@{ub}, is in @{b}gcc/gcc/f/com.c@{ub} and just calls @{b}ffe_decode_option@{ub}.

   If the linked-in front end "rejects" a particular option passed to
it, @{b}toplev.c@{ub} just ignores the option, because @{i}some@{ui} language's compiler
is willing to accept it.

   This allows commands like @{b}gcc -fno-asm foo.c bar.f@{ub} to work, even
though Fortran compilation does not currently support the @{b}-fno-asm@{ub}
option; even though the @{b}f771@{ub} version of @{b}lang_decode_option@{ub} rejects
@{b}-fno-asm@{ub}, @{b}toplev.c@{ub} doesn't produce a diagnostic because some other
language (C) does accept it.

   This also means that commands like @{b}g77 -fno-asm foo.f@{ub} yield no
diagnostics, despite the fact that no phase of the command was able to
recognize and process @{b}-fno-asm@{ub}--perhaps a warning about this would be
helpful if it were possible.

   Code that processes Fortran options is found in @{b}gcc/gcc/f/top.c@{ub},
function @{b}ffe_decode_option@{ub}.  This code needs to check positive and
negative forms of each option.

   The defaults for Fortran options are set in their global
definitions, also found in @{b}gcc/gcc/f/top.c@{ub}.  Many of these defaults are
actually macros defined in @{b}gcc/gcc/f/target.h@{ub}, since they might be
machine-specific.  However, since, in practice, GNU compilers should
behave the same way on all configurations (especially when it comes to
language constructs), the practice of setting defaults in @{b}target.h@{ub} is
likely to be deprecated and, ultimately, stopped in future versions of
@{b}g77@{ub}.

   Accessor macros for Fortran options, used by code in the @{b}g77@{ub} FFE,
are defined in @{b}gcc/gcc/f/top.h@{ub}.

   @{i}Compiler options@{ui} are listed in @{b}gcc/toplev.c@{ub} in the array @{b}f_options@{ub}.
An option not listed in @{b}lang_options@{ub} is looked up in @{b}f_options@{ub} and
handled from there.

   The defaults for compiler options are set in the global definitions
for the corresponding variables, some of which are in @{b}gcc/toplev.c@{ub}.

   You can set different defaults for @{i}Fortran-oriented@{ui} or
@{i}Fortran-reticent@{ui} compiler options by changing the source code of @{b}g77@{ub}
and rebuilding.  How to do this depends on the version of @{b}g77@{ub}:

@{b}G77 0.5.24 (EGCS 1.1)@{ub}
@{b}G77 0.5.25 (EGCS 1.2 - which became GCC 2.95)@{ub}
     Change the @{b}lang_init_options@{ub} routine in @{b}gcc/gcc/f/com.c@{ub}.

     (Note that these versions of @{b}g77@{ub} perform internal consistency
     checking automatically when the @{b}-fversion@{ub} option is specified.)

@{b}G77 0.5.23@{ub}
@{b}G77 0.5.24 (EGCS 1.0)@{ub}
     Change the way @{b}f771@{ub} handles the @{b}-fset-g77-defaults@{ub} option, which
     is always provided as the first option when called by @{b}g77@{ub} or @{b}gcc@{ub}.

     This code is in @{b}ffe_decode_options@{ub} in @{b}gcc/gcc/f/top.c@{ub}.  Have it
     change just the variables that you want to default to a different
     setting for Fortran compiles compared to compiles of other
     languages.

     The @{b}-fset-g77-defaults@{ub} option is passed to @{b}f771@{ub} automatically
     because of the specification information kept in
     @{b}gcc/gcc/f/lang-specs.h@{ub}.  This file tells the @{b}gcc@{ub} command how to
     recognize, in this case, Fortran source files (those to be
     preprocessed, and those that are not), and further, how to invoke
     the appropriate programs (including @{b}f771@{ub}) to process those source
     files.

     It is in @{b}gcc/gcc/f/lang-specs.h@{ub} that @{b}-fset-g77-defaults@{ub},
     @{b}-fversion@{ub}, and other options are passed, as appropriate, even when
     the user has not explicitly specified them.  Other "internal"
     options such as @{b}-quiet@{ub} also are passed via this mechanism.

@endnode

@node "Projects" "g77.guide/Projects"
@next "Front End"
@prev "Adding Options"
@toc "Main"

Projects
********

If you want to contribute to @{b}g77@{ub} by doing research, design,
specification, documentation, coding, or testing, the following
information should give you some ideas.


 @{" Efficiency              " link "Efficiency"}  Make @{b}g77@{ub} itself compile code faster.
 @{" Better Optimization     " link "Better Optimization"}  Teach @{b}g77@{ub} to generate faster code.
 @{" Simplify Porting        " link "Simplify Porting"}  Make @{b}g77@{ub} easier to configure, build,
                             and install.
 @{" More Extensions         " link "More Extensions"}  Features many users won't know to ask for.
 @{" Machine Model           " link "Machine Model"}  @{b}g77@{ub} should better leverage @{b}gcc@{ub}.
 @{" Internals Documentation " link "Internals Documentation"}  Make maintenance easier.
 @{" Internals Improvements  " link "Internals Improvements"}  Make internals more robust.
 @{" Better Diagnostics      " link "Better Diagnostics"}  Make using @{b}g77@{ub} on new code easier.

@endnode

@node "Efficiency" "g77.guide/Efficiency"
@next "Better Optimization"
@toc "Projects"

Improve Efficiency
==================

Don't bother doing any performance analysis until most of the following
items are taken care of, because there's no question they represent
serious space/time problems, although some of them show up only given
certain kinds of (popular) input.

   * Improve @{b}malloc@{ub} package and its uses to specify more info about
     memory pools and, where feasible, use obstacks to implement them.

   * Skip over uninitialized portions of aggregate areas (arrays,
     @{b}COMMON@{ub} areas, @{b}EQUIVALENCE@{ub} areas) so zeros need not be output.
     This would reduce memory usage for large initialized aggregate
     areas, even ones with only one initialized element.

     As of version 0.5.18, a portion of this item has already been
     accomplished.

   * Prescan the statement (in @{b}sta.c@{ub}) so that the nature of the
     statement is determined as much as possible by looking entirely at
     its form, and not looking at any context (previous statements,
     including types of symbols).  This would allow ripping out of the
     statement-confirmation, symbol retraction/confirmation, and
     diagnostic inhibition mechanisms.  Plus, it would result in
     much-improved diagnostics.  For example, @{b}CALL some-intrinsic(...)@{ub},
     where the intrinsic is not a subroutine intrinsic, would result
     actual error instead of the unimplemented-statement catch-all.

   * Throughout @{b}g77@{ub}, don't pass line/column pairs where a simple
     @{b}ffewhere@{ub} type, which points to the error as much as is desired by
     the configuration, will do, and don't pass @{b}ffelexToken@{ub} types where
     a simple @{b}ffewhere@{ub} type will do.  Then, allow new default
     configuration of @{b}ffewhere@{ub} such that the source line text is not
     preserved, and leave it to things like Emacs' next-error function
     to point to them (now that @{b}next-error@{ub} supports column, or,
     perhaps, character-offset, numbers).  The change in calling
     sequences should improve performance somewhat, as should not
     having to save source lines.  (Whether this whole item will
     improve performance is questionable, but it should improve
     maintainability.)

   * Handle @{b}DATA (A(I),I=1,1000000)/1000000*2/@{ub} more efficiently,
     especially as regards the assembly output.  Some of this might
     require improving the back end, but lots of improvement in
     space/time required in @{b}g77@{ub} itself can be fairly easily obtained
     without touching the back end.  Maybe type-conversion, where
     necessary, can be speeded up as well in cases like the one shown
     (converting the @{b}2@{ub} into @{b}2.@{ub}).

   * If analysis shows it to be worthwhile, optimize @{b}lex.c@{ub}.

   * Consider redesigning @{b}lex.c@{ub} to not need any feedback during
     tokenization, by keeping track of enough parse state on its own.

@endnode

@node "Better Optimization" "g77.guide/Better Optimization"
@next "Simplify Porting"
@prev "Efficiency"
@toc "Projects"

Better Optimization
===================

Much of this work should be put off until after @{b}g77@{ub} has all the
features necessary for its widespread acceptance as a useful F77
compiler.  However, perhaps this work can be done in parallel during
the feature-adding work.

   * Do the equivalent of the trick of putting @{b}extern inline@{ub} in front
     of every function definition in @{b}libg2c@{ub} and #include'ing the
     resulting file in @{b}f2c@{ub}+@{b}gcc@{ub}--that is, inline all run-time-library
     functions that are at all worth inlining.  (Some of this has
     already been done, such as for integral exponentiation.)

   * When doing @{b}CHAR_VAR = CHAR_FUNC(...)@{ub}, and it's clear that types
     line up and @{b}CHAR_VAR@{ub} is addressable or not a @{b}VAR_DECL@{ub}, make
     @{b}CHAR_VAR@{ub}, not a temporary, be the receiver for @{b}CHAR_FUNC@{ub}.  (This
     is now done for @{b}COMPLEX@{ub} variables.)

   * Design and implement Fortran-specific optimizations that don't
     really belong in the back end, or where the front end needs to
     give the back end more info than it currently does.

   * Design and implement a new run-time library interface, with the
     code going into @{b}libgcc@{ub} so no special linking is required to link
     Fortran programs using standard language features.  This library
     would speed up lots of things, from I/O (using precompiled formats,
     doing just one, or, at most, very few, calls for arrays or array
     sections, and so on) to general computing (array/section
     implementations of various intrinsics, implementation of commonly
     performed loops that aren't likely to be optimally compiled
     otherwise, etc.).

     Among the important things the library would do are:

        * Be a one-stop-shop-type library, hence shareable and usable
          by all, in that what are now library-build-time options in
          @{b}libg2c@{ub} would be moved at least to the @{b}g77@{ub} compile phase, if
          not to finer grains (such as choosing how list-directed I/O
          formatting is done by default at @{b}OPEN@{ub} time, for preconnected
          units via options or even statements in the main program
          unit, maybe even on a per-I/O basis with appropriate
          pragma-like devices).

   * Probably requiring the new library design, change interface to
     normally have @{b}COMPLEX@{ub} functions return their values in the way @{b}gcc@{ub}
     would if they were declared @{b}__complex__ float@{ub}, rather than using
     the mechanism currently used by @{b}CHARACTER@{ub} functions (whereby the
     functions are compiled as returning void and their first arg is a
     pointer to where to store the result).  (Don't append underscores
     to external names for @{b}COMPLEX@{ub} functions in some cases once @{b}g77@{ub} uses
     @{b}gcc@{ub} rather than @{b}f2c@{ub} calling conventions.)

   * Do something useful with @{b}doiter@{ub} references where possible.  For
     example, @{b}CALL FOO(I)@{ub} cannot modify @{b}I@{ub} if within a @{b}DO@{ub} loop that uses
     @{b}I@{ub} as the iteration variable, and the back end might find that info
     useful in determining whether it needs to read @{b}I@{ub} back into a
     register after the call.  (It normally has to do that, unless it
     knows @{b}FOO@{ub} never modifies its passed-by-reference argument, which
     is rarely the case for Fortran-77 code.)

@endnode

@node "Simplify Porting" "g77.guide/Simplify Porting"
@next "More Extensions"
@prev "Better Optimization"
@toc "Projects"

Simplify Porting
================

Making @{b}g77@{ub} easier to configure, port, build, and install, either as a
single-system compiler or as a cross-compiler, would be very useful.

   * A new library (replacing @{b}libg2c@{ub}) should improve portability as
     well as produce more optimal code.  Further, @{b}g77@{ub} and the new
     library should conspire to simplify naming of externals, such as
     by removing unnecessarily added underscores, and to
     reduce/eliminate the possibility of naming conflicts, while making
     debugger more straightforward.

     Also, it should make multi-language applications more feasible,
     such as by providing Fortran intrinsics that get Fortran unit
     numbers given C @{b}FILE *@{ub} descriptors.

   * Possibly related to a new library, @{b}g77@{ub} should produce the
     equivalent of a @{b}gcc@{ub} @{b}main(argc, argv)@{ub} function when it compiles a
     main program unit, instead of compiling something that must be
     called by a library implementation of @{b}main()@{ub}.

     This would do many useful things such as provide more flexibility
     in terms of setting up exception handling, not requiring
     programmers to start their debugging sessions with @{b}breakpoint
     MAIN__@{ub} followed by @{b}run@{ub}, and so on.

   * The GBE needs to understand the difference between alignment
     requirements and desires.  For example, on Intel x86 machines, @{b}g77@{ub}
     currently imposes overly strict alignment requirements, due to the
     back end, but it would be useful for Fortran and C programmers to
     be able to override these @{i}recommendations@{ui} as long as they don't
     violate the actual processor @{i}requirements@{ui}.

@endnode

@node "More Extensions" "g77.guide/More Extensions"
@next "Machine Model"
@prev "Simplify Porting"
@toc "Projects"

More Extensions
===============

These extensions are not the sort of things users ask for "by name",
but they might improve the usability of @{b}g77@{ub}, and Fortran in general, in
the long run.  Some of these items really pertain to improving @{b}g77@{ub}
internals so that some popular extensions can be more easily supported.

   * Look through all the documentation on the GNU Fortran language,
     dialects, compiler, missing features, bugs, and so on.  Many
     mentions of incomplete or missing features are sprinkled
     throughout.  It is not worth repeating them here.

   * Consider adding a @{b}NUMERIC@{ub} type to designate typeless numeric
     constants, named and unnamed.  The idea is to provide a
     forward-looking, effective replacement for things like the
     old-style @{b}PARAMETER@{ub} statement when people really need typelessness
     in a maintainable, portable, clearly documented way.  Maybe
     @{b}TYPELESS@{ub} would include @{b}CHARACTER@{ub}, @{b}POINTER@{ub}, and whatever else might
     come along.  (This is not really a call for polymorphism per se,
     just an ability to express limited, syntactic polymorphism.)

   * Support @{b}OPEN(...,KEY=(...),...)@{ub}.

   * Support arbitrary file unit numbers, instead of limiting them to 0
     through @{b}MXUNIT-1@{ub}.  (This is a @{b}libg2c@{ub} issue.)

   * @{b}OPEN(NOSPANBLOCKS,...)@{ub} is treated as @{b}OPEN(UNIT=NOSPANBLOCKS,...)@{ub},
     so a later @{b}UNIT=@{ub} in the first example is invalid.  Make sure this
     is what users of this feature would expect.

   * Currently @{b}g77@{ub} disallows @{b}READ(1'10)@{ub} since it is an obnoxious
     syntax, but supporting it might be pretty easy if needed.  More
     details are needed, such as whether general expressions separated
     by an apostrophe are supported, or maybe the record number can be
     a general expression, and so on.

   * Support @{b}STRUCTURE@{ub}, @{b}UNION@{ub}, @{b}MAP@{ub}, and @{b}RECORD@{ub} fully.  Currently there
     is no support at all for @{b}%FILL@{ub} in @{b}STRUCTURE@{ub} and related syntax,
     whereas the rest of the stuff has at least some parsing support.
     This requires either major changes to @{b}libg2c@{ub} or its replacement.

   * F90 and @{b}g77@{ub} probably disagree about label scoping relative to
     @{b}INTERFACE@{ub} and @{b}END INTERFACE@{ub}, and their contained procedure
     interface bodies (blocks?).

   * @{b}ENTRY@{ub} doesn't support F90 @{b}RESULT()@{ub} yet, since that was added after
     S8.112.

   * Empty-statement handling (10 ;;CONTINUE;;) probably isn't
     consistent with the final form of the standard (it was vague at
     S8.112).

   * It seems to be an "open" question whether a file, immediately
     after being @{b}OPEN@{ub}ed,is positioned at the beginning, the end, or
     wherever--it might be nice to offer an option of opening to
     "undefined" status, requiring an explicit absolute-positioning
     operation to be performed before any other (besides @{b}CLOSE@{ub}) to
     assist in making applications port to systems (some IBM?) that
     @{b}OPEN@{ub} to the end of a file or some such thing.

@endnode

@node "Machine Model" "g77.guide/Machine Model"
@next "Internals Documentation"
@prev "More Extensions"
@toc "Projects"

Machine Model
=============

This items pertain to generalizing @{b}g77@{ub}'s view of the machine model to
more fully accept whatever the GBE provides it via its configuration.

   * Switch to using @{b}REAL_VALUE_TYPE@{ub} to represent floating-point
     constants exclusively so the target float format need not be
     required.  This means changing the way @{b}g77@{ub} handles initialization
     of aggregate areas having more than one type, such as @{b}REAL@{ub} and
     @{b}INTEGER@{ub}, because currently it initializes them as if they were
     arrays of @{b}char@{ub} and uses the bit patterns of the constants of the
     various types in them to determine what to stuff in elements of
     the arrays.

   * Rely more and more on back-end info and capabilities, especially
     in the area of constants (where having the @{b}g77@{ub} front-end's IL just
     store the appropriate tree nodes containing constants might be
     best).

   * Suite of C and Fortran programs that a user/administrator can run
     on a machine to help determine the configuration for @{b}g77@{ub} before
     building and help determine if the compiler works (especially with
     whatever libraries are installed) after building.

@endnode

@node "Internals Documentation" "g77.guide/Internals Documentation"
@next "Internals Improvements"
@prev "Machine Model"
@toc "Projects"

Internals Documentation
=======================

Better info on how @{b}g77@{ub} works and how to port it is needed.

   See @{"Front End" link "Front End"}, which contains some information on @{b}g77@{ub} internals.

@endnode

@node "Internals Improvements" "g77.guide/Internals Improvements"
@next "Better Diagnostics"
@prev "Internals Documentation"
@toc "Projects"

Internals Improvements
======================

Some more items that would make @{b}g77@{ub} more reliable and easier to
maintain:

   * Generally make expression handling focus more on critical syntax
     stuff, leaving semantics to callers.  For example, anything a
     caller can check, semantically, let it do so, rather than having
     @{b}expr.c@{ub} do it.  (Exceptions might include things like diagnosing
     @{b}FOO(I--K:)=BAR@{ub} where @{b}FOO@{ub} is a @{b}PARAMETER@{ub}--if it seems important to
     preserve the left-to-right-in-source order of production of
     diagnostics.)

   * Come up with better naming conventions for @{b}-D@{ub} to establish
     requirements to achieve desired implementation dialect via @{b}proj.h@{ub}.

   * Clean up used tokens and @{b}ffewhere@{ub}s in @{b}ffeglobal_terminate_1@{ub}.

   * Replace @{b}sta.c@{ub} @{b}outpooldisp@{ub} mechanism with @{b}malloc_pool_use@{ub}.

   * Check for @{b}opANY@{ub} in more places in @{b}com.c@{ub}, @{b}std.c@{ub}, and @{b}ste.c@{ub}, and get
     rid of the @{b}opCONVERT(opANY)@{ub} kludge (after determining if there is
     indeed no real need for it).

   * Utility to read and check @{b}bad.def@{ub} messages and their references in
     the code, to make sure calls are consistent with message templates.

   * Search and fix @{b}&ffe...@{ub} and similar so that @{b}ffe...ptr...@{ub} macros are
     available instead (a good argument for wishing this could have
     written all this stuff in C++, perhaps).  On the other hand, it's
     questionable whether this sort of improvement is really necessary,
     given the availability of tools such as Emacs and Perl, which make
     finding any address-taking of structure members easy enough?

   * Some modules truly export the member names of their structures
     (and the structures themselves), maybe fix this, and fix other
     modules that just appear to as well (by appending @{b}_@{ub}, though it'd
     be ugly and probably not worth the time).

   * Implement C macros @{b}RETURNS(value)@{ub} and @{b}SETS(something,value)@{ub} in
     @{b}proj.h@{ub} and use them throughout @{b}g77@{ub} source code (especially in the
     definitions of access macros in @{b}.h@{ub} files) so they can be tailored
     to catch code writing into a @{b}RETURNS()@{ub} or reading from a @{b}SETS()@{ub}.

   * Decorate throughout with @{b}const@{ub} and other such stuff.

   * All F90 notational derivations in the source code are still based
     on the S8.112 version of the draft standard.  Probably should
     update to the official standard, or put documentation of the rules
     as used in the code...uh...in the code.

   * Some @{b}ffebld_new@{ub} calls (those outside of @{b}ffeexpr.c@{ub} or inside but
     invoked via paths not involving @{b}ffeexpr_lhs@{ub} or @{b}ffeexpr_rhs@{ub}) might
     be creating things in improper pools, leading to such things
     staying around too long or (doubtful, but possible and dangerous)
     not long enough.

   * Some @{b}ffebld_list_new@{ub} (or whatever) calls might not be matched by
     @{b}ffebld_list_bottom@{ub} (or whatever) calls, which might someday matter.
     (It definitely is not a problem just yet.)

   * Probably not doing clean things when we fail to @{b}EQUIVALENCE@{ub}
     something due to alignment/mismatch or other problems--they end up
     without @{b}ffestorag@{ub} objects, so maybe the backend (and other parts
     of the front end) can notice that and handle like an @{b}opANY@{ub} (do
     what it wants, just don't complain or crash).  Most of this seems
     to have been addressed by now, but a code review wouldn't hurt.

@endnode

@node "Better Diagnostics" "g77.guide/Better Diagnostics"
@prev "Internals Improvements"
@toc "Projects"

Better Diagnostics
==================

These are things users might not ask about, or that need to be looked
into, before worrying about.  Also here are items that involve reducing
unnecessary diagnostic clutter.

   * When @{b}FUNCTION@{ub} and @{b}ENTRY@{ub} point types disagree (@{b}CHARACTER@{ub} lengths,
     type classes, and so on), @{b}ANY@{ub}-ize the offending @{b}ENTRY@{ub} point and
     any @{i}new@{ui} dummies it specifies.

   * Speed up and improve error handling for data when repeat-count is
     specified.  For example, don't output 20 unnecessary messages
     after the first necessary one for:

          INTEGER X(20)
          CONTINUE
          DATA (X(I), J= 1, 20) /20*5/
          END

     (The @{b}CONTINUE@{ub} statement ensures the @{b}DATA@{ub} statement is processed in
     the context of executable, not specification, statements.)

@endnode

@node "Front End" "g77.guide/Front End"
@next "Diagnostics"
@prev "Projects"
@toc "Main"

Front End
*********

This chapter describes some aspects of the design and implementation of
the @{b}g77@{ub} front end.

   To find about things that are "To Be Determined" or "To Be Done",
search for the string TBD.  If you want to help by working on one or
more of these items, email <gcc\@gcc.gnu.org>.  If you're planning to do
more than just research issues and offer comments, see
`http://gcc.gnu.org/contribute.html' for steps you might need to take
first.


 @{" Overview of Sources " link "Overview of Sources"}  
 @{" Overview of Translation Process " link "Overview of Translation Process"}  
 @{" Philosophy of Code Generation " link "Philosophy of Code Generation"}  
 @{" Two-pass Design   " link "Two-pass Design"}  
 @{" Challenges Posed  " link "Challenges Posed"}  
 @{" Transforming Statements " link "Transforming Statements"}  
 @{" Transforming Expressions " link "Transforming Expressions"}  
 @{" Internal Naming Conventions " link "Internal Naming Conventions"}

@endnode

@node "Overview of Sources" "g77.guide/Overview of Sources"
@next "Overview of Translation Process"
@toc "Front End"

Overview of Sources
===================

The current directory layout includes the following:

@{b}SRCDIR/gcc/@{ub}
     Non-g77 files in gcc

@{b}SRCDIR/gcc/f/@{ub}
     GNU Fortran front end sources

@{b}SRCDIR/libf2c/@{ub}
     @{b}libg2c@{ub} configuration and @{b}g2c.h@{ub} file generation

@{b}SRCDIR/libf2c/libF77/@{ub}
     General support and math portion of @{b}libg2c@{ub}

@{b}SRCDIR/libf2c/libI77/@{ub}
     I/O portion of @{b}libg2c@{ub}

@{b}SRCDIR/libf2c/libU77/@{ub}
     Additional interfaces to Unix @{b}libc@{ub} for @{b}libg2c@{ub}

   Components of note in @{b}g77@{ub} are described below.

   @{b}f/@{ub} as a whole contains the source for @{b}g77@{ub}, while @{b}libf2c/@{ub} contains a
portion of the separate program @{b}f2c@{ub}.  Note that the @{b}libf2c@{ub} code is not
part of the program @{b}g77@{ub}, just distributed with it.

   @{b}f/@{ub} contains text files that document the Fortran compiler, source
files for the GNU Fortran Front End (FFE), and some other stuff.  The
@{b}g77@{ub} compiler code is placed in @{b}f/@{ub} because it, along with its contents,
is designed to be a subdirectory of a @{b}gcc@{ub} source directory, @{b}gcc/@{ub}, which
is structured so that language-specific front ends can be "dropped in"
as subdirectories.  The C++ front end (@{b}g++@{ub}), is an example of this--it
resides in the @{b}cp/@{ub} subdirectory.  Note that the C front end (also
referred to as @{b}gcc@{ub}) is an exception to this, as its source files reside
in the @{b}gcc/@{ub} directory itself.

   @{b}libf2c/@{ub} contains the run-time libraries for the @{b}f2c@{ub} program, also
used by @{b}g77@{ub}.  These libraries normally referred to collectively as
@{b}libf2c@{ub}.  When built as part of @{b}g77@{ub}, @{b}libf2c@{ub} is installed under the name
@{b}libg2c@{ub} to avoid conflict with any existing version of @{b}libf2c@{ub}, and thus
is often referred to as @{b}libg2c@{ub} when the @{b}g77@{ub} version is specifically
being referred to.

   The @{b}netlib@{ub} version of @{b}libf2c/@{ub} contains two distinct libraries,
@{b}libF77@{ub} and @{b}libI77@{ub}, each in their own subdirectories.  In @{b}g77@{ub}, this
distinction is not made, beyond maintaining the subdirectory structure
in the source-code tree.

   @{b}libf2c/@{ub} is not part of the program @{b}g77@{ub}, just distributed with it.
It contains files not present in the official (@{b}netlib@{ub}) version of
@{b}libf2c@{ub}, and also contains some minor changes made from @{b}libf2c@{ub}, to fix
some bugs, and to facilitate automatic configuration, building, and
installation of @{b}libf2c@{ub} (as @{b}libg2c@{ub}) for use by @{b}g77@{ub} users.  See
@{b}libf2c/README@{ub} for more information, including licensing conditions
governing distribution of programs containing code from @{b}libg2c@{ub}.

   @{b}libg2c@{ub}, @{b}g77@{ub}'s version of @{b}libf2c@{ub}, adds Dave Love's implementation of
@{b}libU77@{ub}, in the @{b}libf2c/libU77/@{ub} directory.  This library is distributed
under the GNU Library General Public License (LGPL)--see the file
@{b}libf2c/libU77/COPYING.LIB@{ub} for more information, as this license governs
distribution conditions for programs containing code from this portion
of the library.

   Files of note in @{b}f/@{ub} and @{b}libf2c/@{ub} are described below:

@{b}f/BUGS@{ub}
     Lists some important bugs known to be in g77.  Or use Info (or GNU
     Emacs Info mode) to read the "Actual Bugs" node of the @{b}g77@{ub}
     documentation:

          info -f f/g77.info -n "Actual Bugs"

@{b}f/ChangeLog@{ub}
     Lists recent changes to @{b}g77@{ub} internals.

@{b}libf2c/ChangeLog@{ub}
     Lists recent changes to @{b}libg2c@{ub} internals.

@{b}f/NEWS@{ub}
     Contains the per-release changes.  These include the user-visible
     changes described in the node "Changes" in the @{b}g77@{ub} documentation,
     plus internal changes of import.  Or use:

          info -f f/g77.info -n News

@{b}f/g77.info*@{ub}
     The @{b}g77@{ub} documentation, in Info format, produced by building @{b}g77@{ub}.

     All users of @{b}g77@{ub} (not just installers) should read this, using the
     @{b}more@{ub} command if neither the @{b}info@{ub} command, nor GNU Emacs (with its
     Info mode), are available, or if users aren't yet accustomed to
     using these tools.  All of these files are readable as "plain
     text" files, though they're easier to navigate using Info readers
     such as @{b}info@{ub} and GNU Emacs Info mode.

   If you want to explore the FFE code, which lives entirely in @{b}f/@{ub},
here are a few clues.  The file @{b}g77spec.c@{ub} contains the @{b}g77@{ub}-specific
source code for the @{b}g77@{ub} command only--this just forms a variant of the
@{b}gcc@{ub} command, so, just as the @{b}gcc@{ub} command itself does not contain the C
front end, the @{b}g77@{ub} command does not contain the Fortran front end (FFE).
The FFE code ends up in an executable named @{b}f771@{ub}, which does the actual
compiling, so it contains the FFE plus the @{b}gcc@{ub} back end (GBE), the
latter to do most of the optimization, and the code generation.

   The file @{b}parse.c@{ub} is the source file for @{b}yyparse()@{ub}, which is invoked
by the GBE to start the compilation process, for @{b}f771@{ub}.

   The file @{b}top.c@{ub} contains the top-level FFE function @{b}ffe_file@{ub} and it
(along with top.h) define all @{b}ffe_[a-z].*@{ub}, @{b}ffe[A-Z].*@{ub}, and
@{b}FFE_[A-Za-z].*@{ub} symbols.

   The file @{b}fini.c@{ub} is a @{b}main()@{ub} program that is used when building the
FFE to generate C header and source files for recognizing keywords.
The files @{b}malloc.c@{ub} and @{b}malloc.h@{ub} comprise a memory manager that defines
all @{b}malloc_[a-z].*@{ub}, @{b}malloc[A-Z].*@{ub}, and @{b}MALLOC_[A-Za-z].*@{ub} symbols.

   All other modules named XYZ are comprised of all files named @{b}XYZ*.EXT@{ub}
and define all @{b}ffeXYZ_[a-z].*@{ub}, @{b}ffeXYZ[A-Z].*@{ub}, and @{b}FFEXYZ_[A-Za-z].*@{ub}
symbols.  If you understand all this, congratulations--it's easier for
me to remember how it works than to type in these regular expressions.
But it does make it easy to find where a symbol is defined.  For
example, the symbol @{b}ffexyz_set_something@{ub} would be defined in @{b}xyz.h@{ub} and
implemented there (if it's a macro) or in @{b}xyz.c@{ub}.

   The "porting" files of note currently are:

@{b}proj.h@{ub}
     This defines the "language" used by all the other source files,
     the language being Standard C plus some useful things like
     @{b}ARRAY_SIZE@{ub} and such.

@{b}target.c@{ub}
@{b}target.h@{ub}
     These describe the target machine in terms of what data types are
     supported, how they are denoted (to what C type does an @{b}INTEGER*8@{ub}
     map, for example), how to convert between them, and so on.  Over
     time, versions of @{b}g77@{ub} rely less on this file and more on run-time
     configuration based on GBE info in @{b}com.c@{ub}.

@{b}com.c@{ub}
@{b}com.h@{ub}
     These are the primary interface to the GBE.

@{b}ste.c@{ub}
@{b}ste.h@{ub}
     This contains code for implementing recognized executable
     statements in the GBE.

@{b}src.c@{ub}
@{b}src.h@{ub}
     These contain information on the format(s) of source files (such
     as whether they are never to be processed as case-insensitive with
     regard to Fortran keywords).

   If you want to debug the @{b}f771@{ub} executable, for example if it crashes,
note that the global variables @{b}lineno@{ub} and @{b}input_filename@{ub} are usually
set to reflect the current line being read by the lexer during the
first-pass analysis of a program unit and to reflect the current line
being processed during the second-pass compilation of a program unit.

   If an invocation of the function @{b}ffestd_exec_end@{ub} is on the stack,
the compiler is in the second pass, otherwise it is in the first.

   (This information might help you reduce a test case and/or work
around a bug in @{b}g77@{ub} until a fix is available.)

@endnode

@node "Overview of Translation Process" "g77.guide/Overview of Translation Process"
@next "Philosophy of Code Generation"
@prev "Overview of Sources"
@toc "Front End"

Overview of Translation Process
===============================

The order of phases translating source code to the form accepted by the
GBE is:

  1. Stripping punched-card sources (@{b}g77stripcard.c@{ub})

  2. Lexing (@{b}lex.c@{ub})

  3. Stand-alone statement identification (@{b}sta.c@{ub})

  4. INCLUDE handling (@{b}sti.c@{ub})

  5. Order-dependent statement identification (@{b}stq.c@{ub})

  6. Parsing (@{b}stb.c@{ub} and @{b}expr.c@{ub})

  7. Constructing (@{b}stc.c@{ub})

  8. Collecting (@{b}std.c@{ub})

  9. Expanding (@{b}ste.c@{ub})

   To get a rough idea of how a particularly twisted Fortran statement
gets treated by the passes, consider:

           FORMAT(I2 4H)=(J/
          &   I3)

   The job of @{b}lex.c@{ub} is to know enough about Fortran syntax rules to
break the statement up into distinct lexemes without requiring any
feedback from subsequent phases:

     `FORMAT'
     `('
     `I24H'
     `)'
     `='
     `('
     `J'
     `/'
     `I3'
     `)'

   The job of @{b}sta.c@{ub} is to figure out the kind of statement, or, at
least, statement form, that sequence of lexemes represent.

   The sooner it can do this (in terms of using the smallest number of
lexemes, starting with the first for each statement), the better,
because that leaves diagnostics for problems beyond the recognition of
the statement form to subsequent phases, which can usually better
describe the nature of the problem.

   In this case, the @{b}=@{ub} at "level zero" (not nested within parentheses)
tells @{b}sta.c@{ub} that this is an @{i}assignment-form@{ui}, not @{b}FORMAT@{ub}, statement.

   An assignment-form statement might be a statement-function
definition or an executable assignment statement.

   To make that determination, @{b}sta.c@{ub} looks at the first two lexemes.

   Since the second lexeme is @{b}(@{ub}, the first must represent an array for
this to be an assignment statement, else it's a statement function.

   Either way, @{b}sta.c@{ub} hands off the statement to @{b}stq.c@{ub} (via @{b}sti.c@{ub}, which
expands INCLUDE files).  @{b}stq.c@{ub} figures out what a statement that is, on
its own, ambiguous, must actually be based on the context established
by previous statements.

   So, @{b}stq.c@{ub} watches the statement stream for executable statements,
END statements, and so on, so it knows whether @{b}A(B)=C@{ub} is (intended as)
a statement-function definition or an assignment statement.

   After establishing the context-aware statement info, @{b}stq.c@{ub} passes
the original sample statement on to @{b}stb.c@{ub} (either its
statement-function parser or its assignment-statement parser).

   @{b}stb.c@{ub} forms a statement-specific record containing the pertinent
information.  That information includes a source expression and, for an
assignment statement, a destination expression.  Expressions are parsed
by @{b}expr.c@{ub}.

   This record is passed to @{b}stc.c@{ub}, which copes with the implications of
the statement within the context established by previous statements.

   For example, if it's the first statement in the file or after an @{b}END@{ub}
statement, @{b}stc.c@{ub} recognizes that, first of all, a main program unit is
now being lexed (and tells that to @{b}std.c@{ub} before telling it about the
current statement).

   @{b}stc.c@{ub} attaches whatever information it can, usually derived from the
context established by the preceding statements, and passes the
information to @{b}std.c@{ub}.

   @{b}std.c@{ub} saves this information away, since the GBE cannot cope with
information that might be incomplete at this stage.

   For example, @{b}I3@{ub} might later be determined to be an argument to an
alternate @{b}ENTRY@{ub} point.

   When @{b}std.c@{ub} is told about the end of an external (top-level) program
unit, it passes all the information it has saved away on statements in
that program unit to @{b}ste.c@{ub}.

   @{b}ste.c@{ub} "expands" each statement, in sequence, by constructing the
appropriate GBE information and calling the appropriate GBE routines.

   Details on the transformational phases follow.  Keep in mind that
Fortran numbering is used, so the first character on a line is column 1,
decimal numbering is used, and so on.


 @{" g77stripcard " link "g77stripcard"}  
 @{" lex.c      " link "lex.c"}  
 @{" sta.c      " link "sta.c"}  
 @{" sti.c      " link "sti.c"}  
 @{" stq.c      " link "stq.c"}  
 @{" stb.c      " link "stb.c"}  
 @{" expr.c     " link "expr.c"}  
 @{" stc.c      " link "stc.c"}  
 @{" std.c      " link "std.c"}  
 @{" ste.c      " link "ste.c"}  

 @{" Gotchas (Transforming) " link "Gotchas (Transforming)"}  
 @{" TBD (Transforming) " link "TBD (Transforming)"}

@endnode

@node "g77stripcard" "g77.guide/g77stripcard"
@next "lex.c"
@toc "Overview of Translation Process"

g77stripcard
------------

The @{b}g77stripcard@{ub} program handles removing content beyond column 72
(adjustable via a command-line option), optionally warning about that
content being something other than trailing whitespace or Fortran
commentary.

   This program is needed because @{b}lex.c@{ub} doesn't pay attention to
maximum line lengths at all, to make it easier to maintain, as well as
faster (for sources that don't depend on the maximum column length
vis-a-vis trailing non-blank non-commentary content).

   Just how this program will be run--whether automatically for old
source (perhaps as the default for @{b}.f@{ub} files?)--is not yet determined.

   In the meantime, it might as well be implemented as a typical UNIX
pipe.

   It should accept a @{b}-fline-length-N@{ub} option, with the default line
length set to 72.

   When the text it strips off the end of a line is not blank (not
spaces and tabs), it should insert an additional comment line
(beginning with @{b}!@{ub}, so it works for both fixed-form and free-form files)
containing the text, following the stripped line.  The inserted comment
should have a prefix of some kind, TBD, that distinguishes the comment
as representing stripped text.  Users could use that to @{b}sed@{ub} out such
lines, if they wished--it seems silly to provide a command-line option
to delete information when it can be so easily filtered out by another
program.

   (This inserted comment should be designed to "fit in" well with
whatever the Fortran community is using these days for preprocessor,
translator, and other such products, like OpenMP.  What that's all
about, and how @{b}g77@{ub} can elegantly fit its special comment conventions
into it all, is TBD as well.  We don't want to reinvent the wheel here,
but if there turn out to be too many conflicting conventions, we might
have to invent one that looks nothing like the others, but which offers
their host products a better infrastructure in which to fit and coexist
peacefully.)

   @{b}g77stripcard@{ub} probably shouldn't do any tab expansion or other fancy
stuff.  People can use @{b}expand@{ub} or other pre-filtering if they like.  The
idea here is to keep each stage quite simple, while providing excellent
performance for "normal" code.

   (Code with junk beyond column 73 is not really "normal", as it comes
from a card-punch heritage, and will be increasingly hard for
tomorrow's Fortran programmers to read.)

@endnode

@node "lex.c" "g77.guide/lex.c"
@next "sta.c"
@prev "g77stripcard"
@toc "Overview of Translation Process"

lex.c
-----

To help make the lexer simple, fast, and easy to maintain, while also
having @{b}g77@{ub} generally encourage Fortran programmers to write simple,
maintainable, portable code by maximizing the performance of compiling
that kind of code:

   * There'll be just one lexer, for both fixed-form and free-form
     source.

   * It'll care about the form only when handling the first 7 columns of
     text, stuff like spaces between strings of alphanumerics, and how
     lines are continued.

     Some other distinctions will be handled by subsequent phases, so
     at least one of them will have to know which form is involved.

     For example, @{b}I = 2 . 4@{ub} is acceptable in fixed form, and works in
     free form as well given the implementation @{b}g77@{ub} presently uses.
     But the standard requires a diagnostic for it in free form, so the
     parser has to be able to recognize that the lexemes aren't
     contiguous (information the lexer @{i}does@{ui} have to provide) and that
     free-form source is being parsed, so it can provide the diagnostic.

     The @{b}g77@{ub} lexer doesn't try to gather @{b}2 . 4@{ub} into a single lexeme.
     Otherwise, it'd have to know a whole lot more about how to parse
     Fortran, or subsequent phases (mainly parsing) would have two
     paths through lots of critical code--one to handle the lexeme @{b}2@{ub}, @{b}.@{ub},
     and @{b}4@{ub} in sequence, another to handle the lexeme @{b}2.4@{ub}.

   * It won't worry about line lengths (beyond the first 7 columns for
     fixed-form source).

     That is, once it starts parsing the "statement" part of a line
     (column 7 for fixed-form, column 1 for free-form), it'll keep
     going until it finds a newline, rather than ignoring everything
     past a particular column (72 or 132).

     The implication here is that there shouldn't @{i}be@{ui} anything past that
     last column, other than whitespace or commentary, because users
     using typical editors (or viewing output as typically printed)
     won't necessarily know just where the last column is.

     Code that has "garbage" beyond the last column (almost certainly
     only fixed-form code with a punched-card legacy, such as code
     using columns 73-80 for "sequence numbers") will have to be run
     through @{b}g77stripcard@{ub} first.

     Also, keeping track of the maximum column position while also
     watching out for the end of a line @{i}and@{ui} while reading from a file
     just makes things slower.  Since a file must be read, and watching
     for the end of the line is necessary (unless the typical input
     file was preprocessed to include the necessary number of trailing
     spaces), dropping the tracking of the maximum column position is
     the only way to reduce the complexity of the pertinent code while
     maintaining high performance.

   * ASCII encoding is assumed for the input file.

     Code written in other character sets will have to be converted
     first.

   * Tabs (ASCII code 9) will be converted to spaces via the
     straightforward approach.

     Specifically, a tab is converted to between one and eight spaces
     as necessary to reach column N, where dividing @{b}(N - 1)@{ub} by eight
     results in a remainder of zero.

     That saves having to pass most source files through @{b}expand@{ub}.

   * Linefeeds (ASCII code 10) mark the ends of lines.

   * A carriage return (ASCII code 13) is accept if it immediately
     precedes a linefeed, in which case it is ignored.

     Otherwise, it is rejected (with a diagnostic).

   * Any other characters other than the above that are not part of the
     GNU Fortran Character Set (see @{"Character Set" link "Character Set"}) are rejected with a
     diagnostic.

     This includes backspaces, form feeds, and the like.

     (It might make sense to allow a form feed in column 1 as long as
     that's the only character on a line.  It certainly wouldn't seem
     to cost much in terms of performance.)

   * The end of the input stream (EOF) ends the current line.

   * The distinction between uppercase and lowercase letters will be
     preserved.

     It will be up to subsequent phases to decide to fold case.

     Current plans are to permit any casing for Fortran (reserved)
     keywords while preserving casing for user-defined names.  (This
     might not be made the default for @{b}.f@{ub} files, though.)

     Preserving case seems necessary to provide more direct access to
     facilities outside of @{b}g77@{ub}, such as to C or Pascal code.

     Names of intrinsics will probably be matchable in any case,

     (How @{b}external SiN; r = sin(x)@{ub} would be handled is TBD.  I think
     old @{b}g77@{ub} might already handle that pretty elegantly, but whether we
     can cope with allowing the same fragment to reference a @{i}different@{ui}
     procedure, even with the same interface, via @{b}s = SiN(r)@{ub}, needs to
     be determined.  If it can't, we need to make sure that when code
     introduces a user-defined name, any intrinsic matching that name
     using a case-insensitive comparison is "turned off".)

   * Backslashes in @{b}CHARACTER@{ub} and Hollerith constants are not allowed.

     This avoids the confusion introduced by some Fortran compiler
     vendors providing C-like interpretation of backslashes, while
     others provide straight-through interpretation.

     Some kind of lexical construct (TBD) will be provided to allow
     flagging of a @{b}CHARACTER@{ub} (but probably not a Hollerith) constant
     that permits backslashes.  It'll necessarily be a prefix, such as:

          PRINT *, C'This line has a backspace \\b here.'
          PRINT *, F'This line has a straight backslash \\ here.'

     Further, command-line options might be provided to specify that
     one prefix or the other is to be assumed as the default for
     @{b}CHARACTER@{ub} constants.

     However, it seems more helpful for @{b}g77@{ub} to provide a program that
     converts prefix all constants (or just those containing
     backslashes) with the desired designation, so printouts of code
     can be read without knowing the compile-time options used when
     compiling it.

     If such a program is provided (let's name it @{b}g77slash@{ub} for now),
     then a command-line option to @{b}g77@{ub} should not be provided.
     (Though, given that it'll be easy to implement, it might be hard
     to resist user requests for it "to compile faster than if we have
     to invoke another filter".)

     This program would take a command-line option to specify the
     default interpretation of slashes, affecting which prefix it uses
     for constants.

     @{b}g77slash@{ub} probably should automatically convert Hollerith constants
     that contain slashes to the appropriate @{b}CHARACTER@{ub} constants.  Then
     @{b}g77@{ub} wouldn't have to define a prefix syntax for Hollerith
     constants specifying whether they want C-style or straight-through
     backslashes.

   * To allow for form-neutral INCLUDE files without requiring them to
     be preprocessed, the fixed-form lexer should offer an extension
     (if possible) allowing a trailing @{b}&@{ub} to be ignored, especially if
     after column 72, as it would be using the traditional Unix Fortran
     source model (which ignores @{i}everything@{ui} after column 72).

   The above implements nearly exactly what is specified by
@{"Character Set" link "Character Set"}, and @{"Lines" link "Lines"}, except it also provides automatic
conversion of tabs and ignoring of newline-related carriage returns, as
well as accommodating form-neutral INCLUDE files.

   It also implements the "pure visual" model, by which is meant that a
user viewing his code in a typical text editor (assuming it's not
preprocessed via @{b}g77stripcard@{ub} or similar) doesn't need any special
knowledge of whether spaces on the screen are really tabs, whether
lines end immediately after the last visible non-space character or
after a number of spaces and tabs that follow it, or whether the last
line in the file is ended by a newline.

   Most editors don't make these distinctions, the ANSI FORTRAN 77
standard doesn't require them to, and it permits a standard-conforming
compiler to define a method for transforming source code to "standard
form" however it wants.

   So, GNU Fortran defines it such that users have the best chance of
having the code be interpreted the way it looks on the screen of the
typical editor.

   (Fancy editors should @{i}never@{ui} be required to correctly read code
written in classic two-dimensional-plaintext form.  By correct reading
I mean ability to read it, book-like, without mistaking text ignored by
the compiler for program code and vice versa, and without having to
count beyond the first several columns.  The vague meaning of ASCII
TAB, among other things, complicates this somewhat, but as long as
"everyone", including the editor, other tools, and printer, agrees
about the every-eighth-column convention, the GNU Fortran "pure visual"
model meets these requirements.  Any language or user-visible source
form requiring special tagging of tabs, the ends of lines after
spaces/tabs, and so on, fails to meet this fairly straightforward
specification.  Fortunately, Fortran @{i}itself@{ui} does not mandate such a
failure, though most vendor-supplied defaults for their Fortran
compilers @{i}do@{ui} fail to meet this specification for readability.)

   Further, this model provides a clean interface to whatever
preprocessors or code-generators are used to produce input to this
phase of @{b}g77@{ub}.  Mainly, they need not worry about long lines.

@endnode

